<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Aliens     09-14 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Aliens,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Priest Who Refused To Be Fingerprinted Jailed for Refusing
to Pay Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French priest chose today to spend 12 days in
prison rather than pay $200 in fines for refusing to be
fingerprinted under Japan's Alien Registration Law, an official said.
   The priest, Debion Maxime, 47, was jailed in Yokohama prison, an
official from the Yokohama District Public Prosecutors Office said
on condition of anonymity.
   He said Maxime, who has lived in Japan since 1974, was a resident
of Sagamihara city, south of Tokyo.
   Maxime refused to be fingerprinted when he applied for a
registration card. His refusal was a sympathy protest over the
arrest of a South Korean resident who refused to be fingerprinted in
May 1985.
   A local court subsequently ordered Maxime to pay $684, but the
priest refused to paye. In June, the fine was reduced to $200.
   Opponents of law say the fingerprint requirement is
discriminatory and violates human rights. Violators are subject to
up to one year in prison, deportation and a fine of up to $1,400.
</TEXT>
