<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Jets-Pigeons     09-14 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Jets-Pigeons,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor Declares War on Pigeons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense contractor says its F-16
fighter jets are being bombarded. By pigeons.
   And General Dynamics Corp. is planning to fight back. It has
hired an exterminator to scatter poisoned seed at its assembly plant
in west Forth Worth.
   ``Would you want to pick up a $15 million airplane full of bird
droppings?'' asked spokesman Z. Joe Thornton.
   Thornton said this week that bird droppings damage aircraft paint
and cockpit canopies.
   ``It sounds crazy, but it's a very serious problem for us,'' he
said.
   Linda Yarbrough of the Animal Liberation League, objects to the
attack plan.
   ``They could move them,'' she said. ``Pigeons are very easy to
move.''
   Steve Hamilton of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said pigeon
extermination is allowed.
   General Dynamics builds the F-16 Fighting Falcons for the U.S.
Air Force and about a dozen foreign customers.
</TEXT>
