<FIRST>r a PM-TugboatPageant     09-14 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tugboat Pageant,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>``Miss Tugboat'' is Crowned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She may not be shaped like Miss America,
but for the judges who flagged her ``Miss Tugboat,'' she is just as
beautiful.
   As part of a day-long celebration of the resurgence of Jersey
City's waterfront, 13 tugboats chugged into New York Harbor on
Wednesday for a Tugboat Beauty Contest. The master of ceremonies
were former Miss America host Bert Parks.
   The event coincided with this year's Miss America Pageant, which
will be televised live from Atlantic City on Saturday.
   ``Beauty is all in the eye of the beholder, whether it's a cat or
a tugboat or a lady,'' said the 74-year-old Parks.
   A 105-foot, blue, white and yellow-trimmed tugboat named Rebecca
P. was crowned fairest of them all.
   The 9-year-old tug from Poling Transportation of Staten Island,
N.Y., won $2,500 for her crew and a flag proclaiming it the most
beautiful tug in the country.
   Each towboat traveled along an ``aisle,'' a channel leading into
the harbor from Jersey City, as Parks belted out the tug's vital
statistics to more than 1,000 onlookers.
   He did not have a chance to croon ``There She Is,'' the popular
Miss America theme.
   Each vessel was judged by Jersey City Mayor Gerald McCann, Hudson
County Executive Robert Janiszewski and a representative from the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, who rated their ``evening
gowns,'' trim, sparkle, maneuverability, charm and overall
appearance.
</TEXT>
