<FIRST>r a PM-MineDisaster-List     09-14 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine Disaster-List,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>List of U.S. Mine Disasters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mine Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of some major U.S. mine disasters:
   Dec. 19, 1984 _ Faulty air compressor starts underground fire
that kills 27 coal miners at the Wilberg Mine near Orangeville, Utah.
   March 9-11, 1976 _ Fifteen miners and 11 rescuers die as two
methane gas explosions shake mine in Oven Fork, Ky.
   May 3, 1972 _ Fire fills the Sunshine Mine in Kellogg, Idaho,
with smoke and poisonous gas, killing 91 miners. Two people survived
the fire in the nation's richest and deepest silver mine, living for
a week 4,800 feet below the surface by eating the lunches of their
fallen comrades and tapping water from pipes.
   Dec. 30, 1970 _ Mine disaster in Hyden, Ky., kills 38 miners.
   Nov. 20, 1968 _ Explosions and fire at Consolidated Coal's No. 9
mine in Farmington, W.Va., kill 78 people. Twenty major explosions
and many more minor ones rocked the mine's 100 miles of tunnels for
nine days. This disaster led to the landmark Federal Coal Mine
Health and Safety Act passed by Congress in 1969.
   Dec. 21, 1951 _ West Frankfort, Ill., mine disaster kills 119
people.
   March 25, 1947 _ Mine disaster in Centralia, Ill., kills 111 coal
miners.
   May 19, 1928 _ Coal mine disaster in Mather, Pa., kills 195.
   Feb. 28, 1923 _ Second major mine disaster within 10 years in
Dawson, N.M., kills 120 people.
   Oct. 22, 1913 _ Mine explosion in Dawson. N.M. kills 263 people.
   Nov. 13, 1909 _ Mine explodes at Cherry, Ill., killing 259.
   Dec. 19, 1907 _ Explosion at Jacobs Creek, Pa., kills 239 people.
   Dec. 6, 1907 _ In the nation's worst mine disaster, 361 to 370
miners are killed as electrical sparks apparently ignite an
explosion in a network of coal mines at Monongah, W.Va.
   May 1, 1900 _ Premature blasting powder explosion kills 200
people at Scofield, Utah.
  
</TEXT>
