<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-14 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy-footed drivers may think they've
taken a wrong turn on the New Jersey Turnpike and gone to heaven _
some of the electronic speed limit signs are mistakenly reading 75
mph.
   State police and turnpike authority officials said the erroneous
speed limit has been flashing on about half a dozen of the lighted
signs in northern New Jersey because of a computer programming
error. The legal limit is 55 mph.
   Gordon Hector, a spokesman for the turnpike authority, said
technicians were trying to track down the problem. Meanwhile,
workers are adjusting the errant signs manually.
   Some motorists find it funny.
   ``It was kind of strange to see everybody below the speed limit
for a change,'' joked Casey Raskob, an attorney from Springfield.
   A state police official said no traffic problems were reported as
result. ``But I don't think any judge is gonna buy that excuse'' for
speeding, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who've been wronged by a boss,
jilted by a lover or otherwise insulted, are finding the ultimate
revenge has just plopped in their laps.
   A new company catering to the revenge-minded will send a genuine
cow pie _ nestled in an 8-inch pie tin, wrapped in plastic and boxed
like baked goods _ for $16.95, or $9.95 on special. Fake flies are
75 cents extra.
   ``They have no idea what they're getting _ they think it's an
apple pie in red cellophane,'' said Jennifer Sanders, president of
Cowpies, recently founded in this San Francisco Bay-area city.
   Sanders and her two partners _ Gayle Massey, a San Francisco
advertiser, and Santa Monica businessman Donald Grant _ actually
scour the fields for the real thing.
   So far, they've filled about 100 orders. Many are for birthday
parties, but nearly half of the pies carry a more pointed message.
One homeowner ordered a pie for a carpenter whose work he didn't
like; another sent a bovine confection to his bank.
   More popular are orders from employees seeking a memorable gift
for a boss or co-worker.
   ``It's strictly anonymous unless they specify otherwise,''
Sanders said. ``But some people do put their names with really awful
things.''
</TEXT>
