<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia     09-14 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Investigate Mercenaries in Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia-Addicts, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers have launched an inquiry into
reports of American, Israeli and British mercenaries operating
freely in Colombia to train scores of paramilitary groups, including
drug traffickers.
   Colombian congressmen, along with Minister of Defense Gen. Oscar
Botero, watched a film Wednesday night at the Congress building of
alleged paramilitary training in Colombia.
   Scenes included men firing guns from moving vehicles, practicing
assaults on houses, and taking explosives training. The film was
made available by the Bogota television news program Noticiero
Nacional.
   A Colombian police general who appeared at the hearings Wednesday
said in a televised interview he had told lawmakers a month ago that
foreign mercenaries were training the paramilitary groups.
   The general, Miguel Daza Marquez, heads Colombia's Administrative
Security Police, which handles national criminal investigations.
   Foreign Minister Julio Londono Paredes told the lawmakers,
however, that the Ministry had no proof foreign mercenaries had
actually trained Colombian drug traffickers or paramilitary groups.
   But he acknowledged there were no restrictions on many foreigners
who want to travel to this South American republic.
   ``British, German and Israeli nationals, in accordance with
agreements with the respective countries, don't need a visa to enter
this country,'' said the foreign minister. ``As for nationals of the
United States, they only need a tourist card.''
   Colombian media reported last month that former Israeli army
colonel Yair Klein and other foreign mercenaries trained drug
traffickers' hit squads in Colombia.
   The traffickers have used their private armies to recruit
right-wing death squads that have killed more than 1,000 Colombian
leftists in the last four years.
   The congressional investigation comes amid a U.S.-backed war that
President Virgilio Barco declared on the world's most powerful drug
cartels after the assassination Aug. 18 of Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, a
popular presidential candidate and foe of the drug barons.
   In Medellin, home of a leading drug gang, Mayor Juan Gomez on
Wednesday lifted a nighttime curfew imposed two weeks ago in an
attempt to stem a rash of bombings, killings and arson blamed on the
traffickers.
   Motorists still must drive at night with their inside lights on,
however, and there is a ban on motorcycles from 6:30 p.m. to 6 a.m.
Most firebombings in the city are the work of speeding motorcyclists.
   Gomez said he lifted the curfew because his city had returned to
``absolute normalcy.'' No bombs had exploded in Medellin for three
days.
   The lifting of the curfew highlights the mayor's disagreement
with the government about how to deal with narco-terrorism.
   Gomez favors negotiating with the drug barons, a tactic Barco
rejects.
   Also Wednesday, the government reinforced security in the
Medellin region, sending hundreds of additional police and soldiers
to Antioquia state.
   Medellin, a city of 2 million people, is the capital of Antioquia.
   The measures followed the assassination Monday of former Medellin
mayor Pablo Pelaez Gonzalez by unidenfied gunmen. Pelaez was an avid
drug fighter.
   The government vows to continue its crackdown, but Colombia's
most wanted trafficking suspects have so far eluded the manhunt.
   Barco said he will extradite those traffickers who are arrested
and wanted in the United States.
   The only alleged drug cartel member extradited in the crackdown
so far is Eduardo Martinez Romero, charged with laundering more than
a billion dollars of cocaine money.
</TEXT>
