<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William F. Buckley Jr. says the president's
drug plan is doomed to failure, and the nation might have better
luck fighting drugs by legalizing them.
   ``If Bush's plan could work, then I would favor it,'' the
conservative pundit told reporters Wednesday at the University of
Mississippi before a broadcast of his TV talk show, ``Firing Line.''
   ``Our borders are indefensible,'' he said, explaining the
legalization rationale. ``The overhead cost for penetrating the U.S.
borders is only 3 percent of the street value of imported illegal
drugs. We should attack what we can, legalize drugs and concentrate
on drug education.''
   That's not to say Buckley is soft on drug abusers. He's
especially ready to crack down on those who sell drugs to minors:
``In my case, I would support capital punishment.''
