<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Auschwitz     09-14 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Auschwitz,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Leaders Discuss Formal Contacts With Catholics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the European Jewish Congress has
disputed a French colleague's claim that the organization has backed
a call for freezing all formal contacts between Jewish groups and
the Roman Catholic Church.
   ``They have not been frozen. This is not my interpretation of
what was said or wanted,'' Lionel Kopelowitz, British president of
the 17-nation organization, said Wednesday.
   But French delegate Theo Klein, the congress' past president and
chief Jewish negotiator in a dispute over a Carmelite convent at the
Nazi death camp at Auschwitz in occupied Poland, reiterated that the
congress backed freezing formal, high-level contacts.
   Kopelowitz and Klein commented in interviews on questions arising
from a news conference they held Monday after the congress' two-day
annual meeting.
   The London meeting, largely behind closed doors, was dominated by
the issue of the convent, which many Jews regard as offensive. Of
the 4 million people killed at the Auschwitz death camp in World War
II, 2.5 million were Jews.
   Klein led an international Jewish negotiating team that in 1987
reached an agreement with a Polish Catholic representative to
relocate the convent by Feb. 22.
   But the convent remains and the Polish primate, Cardinal Jozef
Glemp, has said the accord was not negotiated by competent people.
   At Monday's news conference, Klein said that on July 20 he told
French Cardinal Albert Decourtray in a letter that all ``dialogue
and official meetings'' were frozen until the Carmelite convent
dispute was resolved.
   Klein added that the European Jewish Congress meeting had
endorsed this position ``because this decision was the decision of
the Jewish delegation and all the work of the Jewish delegation was
approved by the conference.''
   Kopelowitz, seated beside Klein on Monday, did not contradict
this statement, although he referred several times to the formal
resolutions passed by the meeting. These made no mention of a freeze
in Catholic-Jewish relations, although they did endorse the position
of the Jewish negotiating team.
   Hayim Pinner, secretary-general of the Board of Deputies of
British Jews, said Wednesday that Klein's interpretation of this as
endorsing a freezing of formal contacts was ``reasonably fair, but
perhaps he went a bit far.''
   ``My sensitivity in interpretation would be that, without having
specifically discussed this or specifically endorsed it, there was
an undercurrent of feeling that we couldn't engage in major
negotiations, have business as usual,'' said Pinner.
   European Jewish Congress sources said on condition of anonymity
Wednesday that Kopelowitz did not intervene because he felt that if
he had, ``headlines will appear in all the papers saying Jewish
leaders are in disagreement.''
   The sources said that, instead, Kopelowitz ``tried gently'' to
draw attention to the formal resolutions.
   The sources also said Kopelowitz had not invited Klein to join
him at the news conference.
   Klein, in a telephone interview from Paris, said the congress
approved the freezing of Catholic-Jewish relations as set out in his
July letter. He said the letter was ``not a personal position'' but
had been approved by the Jewish negotiating team and other Jewish
organizations.
   Reiterating that the congress had supported the letter, Klein
said: ``Because it was not the important point of our deliberations
you have no mention of that in the resolutions we took.''
   The conflicting views appear to reflect differences about the
repercussions of the dispute on Jewish-Catholic relations.
   Both Kopelwitz and Klein agreed that informal contacts continue.
These include Klein's contacts with European cardinals who want the
1987 accord honored and the convent removed.
   But Klein argued that all formal contacts are frozen, and he said
Catholics understand this because the convent dispute overshadows
Catholic-Jewish relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
