<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Russell     09-14 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Russell,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Nevada Governor Dies of Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Russell, a newspaper publisher
who turned to politics and served as governor and congressman, died
of a heart attack. He was 85.
   Russell died Wednesday, two days after being hospitalized for
breathing problems. He suffered from emphysema, a lung illness he
contracted from cigarette smoking, and had a cardiac arrest, said
his son Todd.
   Russell, a Republican, was governor from 1951 to 1958, when he
was defeated in a bid for a third term by Democrat Grant Sawyer.
   He served two terms in the state Assembly and three terms in the
state Senate, one term in Congress and several years administering
the Marshall Plan in Europe and foreign aid programs in Paraguay.
   Russell was publisher of the Ely Record between 1929 and 1946,
competing against Vail Pittman's Ely Daily Times. The two were
political rivals, with Russell defeating Pittman twice for governor.
   While governor, Russell pushed for creation of the state Gaming
Control Board, the enforcement arm for the Nevada Gaming Commission,
which oversees casinos.
   Approval of the Control Board by the 1955 Legislature was viewed
by Russell as one of his top achievements as the state's chief
executive.
   Russell is survived by his wife, Marjorie Anne, and five
children: Clark, Craig, David and Todd, and Virginia Sakal. Funeral
arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
