<FIRST>r w PM-CommoditiesBill     09-14 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Bill,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Commodities Trading Reform Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation reforming the commodity futures
trading industry will strengthen the authority of federal
regulators, say lawmakers.
   The Commodity Futures Improvements Act, which passed the House
420-to-0 on Wednesday, makes sweeping changes in trading practices
exposed in last month's indictments of 45 brokers and traders and a
clerk at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and Chicago Board of Trade.
   The bill also would give extra muscle to the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission, which congressional critics have called too
gentle a watchdog of the nation's futures markets.
   ``With this action, the House makes clear that the integrity of
futures markets will be maintained and that the public's interest
will be protected,'' said Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., who
co-sponsored the bill with Rep. Thomas Coleman, R-Mo.
   ``This bill is an attempt to restore public confidence to these
markets,'' said Coleman.
   The bill, if passed by the Senate and signed by the president,
would:
   _Ban insider trading on the nation's 13 active futures exchanges;
   _Require floor traders, those who trade only for themselves and
not for outside customers, to register with the CFTC;
   _Limit trading among broker associations that could conflict with
customers' accounts, and,
   _Severely restrict the practice of dual trading.
   In dual trading, floor traders on an exchange can trade for
themselves as well as their customers on the same day. While not
illegal, the practice has raised questions about whether traders
take care of themselves ahead of their customers. Supporters of the
practice say it helps maintain market liquidity when there are few
customer orders.
   The House also added an amendment that would require that future
presidential appointees to the CFTC have some ``demonstrated
knowledge'' of futures trading, its regulation or the production,
merchandising, processing or distribution of goods subject to
futures contracts.
   ``We can no longer afford to conduct on-the-job training for the
agency's commissioners,'' said English, the amendment's sponsor.
   President Bush has nominated Margot Machol, a member of the
Federal Trade Commission with little experience in commodity futures
matters, to a spot on the five-member CFTC.
   The Senate has yet to take up the CFTC's reauthorization, but
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Agriculture, Nutrition
and Forestry Committee, said last week he was asking staffers to
draw up legislation to correct gaps in the agency's surveillance of
trading activities.
   The House bill also requires exchanges to maintain accurate
trading records so investigators can reconstruct any given
transaction.
   The Chicago indictments included numerous charges of customers
defrauded through falsified trading records. Transactions on the
Chicago exchanges, as well as others around the country, use
handwritten paper cards to record sales and purchases with the
trader entering the information.
   Within weeks of the indictments, the two big Chicago exchanges
announced they were working to develop hand-held computer terminals
to record floor trading.
   One year after enactment, the bill would require exchanges to
develop systems that would pinpoint the time of a trade's execution
to within one minute of its occurrence.
   That standard would be tightened to 30 seconds within three years
of enactment.
   The bill also would make permanent the CFTC, which Congress has
reauthorized on a temporary basis every three or four years since it
was created in 1974.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
