<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-FifthMan     09-14 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fifth Man,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: KGB Man Says British Spy Ring Had A Fifth Member</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior KGB official says the four-man British spy
ring that betrayed Western secrets to Moscow for more than three
decades was aided by a fifth man, a London newspaper reported today.
   The Independent quoted Yuri Modin as saying in Moscow Wednesday
when asked by its reporter Rupert Cornwell if there was a fifth
member: ``Yes there was.''
   There has been repeated news media speculation in Britain over
the years about the existence of a so-called fifth man.
   The Independent identified Modin as the Soviet intelligence
agency's key contact with one of the ring, Kim Philby, and the
controller of three other members _ Anthony Blunt, Guy Burgess and
Donald Maclean.
   Cornwell reported that he spoke with Modin following a news
conference given in Moscow Wednesday by KGB officers and attended by
foreign reporters.
   The news conference was held after the screening of a film called
``The KGB Today'' made by the Soviet government news agency Novosti
and billed as the first Soviet documentary about the organization.
   Cornwell said the film identified Modin, who was an attache at
the Soviet Embassy in London in 1951, as a ``KGB colleague who had
worked with Kim Philby abroad.''
   But Cornwell said reference works on the spy ring showed that
Modin was ``no mere friend of Philby during the last 25 years of his
life in Moscow.''
   He reported that Modin ``had been ... controller of Anthony
Blunt, and of Guy Burgess and Donald Maclean when they fled in 1951.
For years after that he would remain the key Soviet contact of
Philby himself.''
   Cornwell added: ``I inquired of Mr. Modin after the press
conference: `Well then, was there really a fifth man?' `Yes there
was,' said the person better placed to know than anyone.''
   Cornwell continued: ``And so the obvious question: who was he?
`British counter-intelligence has been trying to work that one out
without success for nearly 30 years now,' was all Mr. Modin would
answer.''
   Cornwell gave no other details on this.
   Philby became a Soviet agent in 1933. When he ran the Soviet desk
of Britain's MI6 agency responsible for gathering foreign
intelligence he told the Soviets who was spying on them.
   He served in Washington as liason officer with the U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency, fled to Moscow in 1963 while posing as a
journalist in Beirut and died in Moscow in May 1988 at age 76.
   Art historian Blunt recruited spies for Moscow in the 1930s and
spied for the Soviets during World War II while working for
Britain's MI5 counter-intelligence service.
   He was unmasked in 1964 but was granted immunity in return for
information about Soviet spying. He was publicly exposed in 1979 and
stripped of his knighthood awearded for his services as art adviser
to Queen Elizabeth II. He died in London in March 1983 at age 75.
   Burgess became a Soviet agent in the 1930s. He worked as a
British diplomat in Washington and looked after Far Eastern affairs
during the Korean War.
   Maclean was posted to Washington as a British diplomat in 1944
but was recalled home because of heavy drinking. He worked with
Americans and Canadians on the Combined Policy Committee for Joint
Atomic Development and gave the Soviets documents on nuclear
planning.
   Burgess and Maclean fled to Moscow in 1951 when tipped by Philby
that they were about to be arrested. Burgess died in Moscow in 1963
at age 52. Maclean died there in 1983 at age 69.
   Veteran defense correspondent Chapman Pincher and former MI5
officer Peter Wright, whose book ``Spycatcher'' the British
government failed to suppress after lengthy court battles, have both
alleged that the late Sir Roger Hollis was almost certainly a Soviet
spy. Hollis was head of MI5 from 1956 to 1965.
   But Prime Minister Mrs. Thatcher told Parliament in 1981
following publication of Pincher's book ``Their Trade is Treachery''
that investigators probing allegations against Hollis had found no
evidence incriminating him. They therefore concluded he was not been
a Soviet agent, she said.
</TEXT>
