<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LakeExploration Bjt   09-14 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lake Exploration, Bjt,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historians, Scientists Search for Revolutionary War Battleship</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto MR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE R.V. MELOSIRA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a venture that's part history
and part high technology, scientists are scanning the bottom of Lake
Champlain for the last missing boat of Benedict Arnold's sunken
fleet.
   In the cabin, skipper Dick Furbush and a crew of
sailor-scientists are keeping track of two sonars _ one to show the
depth of the water below, the other a state-of-the art side-scanner
that looks for underwater objects.
   On the deck of the University of Vermont research vessel,
historian Art Cohn from the Lake Champlain Maritime Museum regales
listeners with tales of Arnold's exploits on the lake during the
Revolutionary War.
   That was before frustration with a stalled career and financial
woes drove Arnold to treason. His plot to betray the rebels' post at
West Point, N.Y., was discovered and foiled, but he escaped and
joined the British.
   ``From 1775 to 1777, Benedict Arnold was one of the best field
commanders the Americans had,'' Cohn said. ``That story is
frequently forgotten because of his later treason.''
   While it isn't the only purpose of the two-week lake exploration,
most of those aboard the Melosira are hoping for a prize find: the
Providence. It is the last unaccounted for vessel of five that
Arnold ordered burned in Ferris Bay _ now called Arnold's Bay _ to
prevent their capture by the British.
   The torpedo-shaped side-scan sonar searches a 600-foot-wide swath
of lake bed by bouncing sound waves off of the bottom and whatever
may lie on it. Electrical impulses carry the findings through
hundreds of feet of cable back to the cabin of the Melosira, where
marine scientist Story Fish interprets spots and squiggles that
appear on a roll of special graph paper.
   If the Providence were to appear, ``it would be about that big,''
Fish said, plopping the plastic cap of a ballpoint pen on the paper.
   Divers and sonar have been used with increasing frequency in the
lake in recent years in an attempt to piece together details on the
crucial role Lake Champlain played as a naval theater in the
Revolutionary War.
   The goal, Cohn said, is not to bring historic ships up, but to
examine them as closely as possible and leave them in the cold,
fresh water that has preserved them for more than 200 years.
   ``It's a good, stable environment,'' Cohn said. ``You bring them
up, and they start to deteriorate. If we leave them there, future
generations will have the same opportunity to study them, but with
better technology.''
   Lake Champlain, the nation's sixth largest body of fresh water,
has what is widely regarded as ``the best collection of historic
shipwrecks in the United States,'' he said.
   The one exception to the leave-it-on-the-bottom rule was another
of the ships in Arnold's original fleet, the Philadelphia, which was
raised in 1935 and is now on display at the Smithsonian Institution
in Washington. The Lake Champlain Maritime Museum, in the Vermont
village of Basin Harbor, is working on an exact replica of the
54-foot, 29-ton Philadelphia.
   Cohn said the aim of the research is to learn more about the
motives and methods of the British and Americans as they prepared
for and then met in the battle of Valcour Island on Oct. 11-13, 1776.
   The Americans had held Fort Ticonderoga at the southern end of
the lake since it was taken by Arnold, Ethan Allen and the Green
Mountain Boys in May, 1775, just three weeks after the war began
with battles at Lexington and Concord.
   The British had amassed a large and powerful fleet on the
northern end of the lake at St. Johns, Quebec.
   When the forces met near Valcour Island, the British easily
outgunned the smaller Revolutionary navy on Oct. 11 and were ready
to finish it off the next day. One of the ships sunk on that first
day of battle was the Providence.
   In a move still admired for its daring, Arnold led his tattered
fleet single-file through the British blockade under cover of
darkness. The British were left to chase the Americans against the
wind the next day.
   Arnold knew he was defeated, so he destroyed most of what
remained of his own fleet.
   He and his troops fled overland to Ticonderoga, N.Y., and the
battle-weary British returned to Canada for the winter.
   The delay gave the Americans a chance to prepare for a series of
engagements that ended with the British defeat at the pivotal battle
at Saratoga, N.Y., on Oct. 17, 1777.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
