<DOCNO> AP890914-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0258EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Senate-FSX     09-14 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-FSX,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Wins Veto Fight Over Japanese Jet Fighter Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's agreement to share
U.S. technology with Japan for a new $6 billion jet fighter will go
forward after the Senate's failure by one vote to restrict the deal.
   ``The Congress has lost this struggle; the president has
prevailed,'' said Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., after the Senate on
Wednesday sustained President's Bush's veto of legislation aimed at
short-circuiting the technology transfer. The 64-34 roll call vote
fell one short of the two-thirds majority required to override a
veto.
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk said Bush was ``very
pleased'' at the result, which came after the White House and some
lawmakers accused the legislation's supporters of trying to
monopolize power over trade regulation.
   Dixon and other senators opposed to the FSX fighter deal vowed to
oppose similar agreements with other nations, including one now
under consideration between the United States and South Korea.
   ``I think the administration will come to regret what has
occurred here,'' Dixon said. ``This is a very unsound, unfavorable
agreement for us.''
   The vote means the $6 billion co-development, co-production
agreement with Japan will go forward with the aim of producing an
advanced, high technology Japanese fighter by the end of the 1990's.
   Rep. Terry L. Bruce, D-Ill., one of the leading opponents of the
FSX deal in the House, said the Senate ``gave away the technology in
the one industry where we have worldwide preeminence.''
   ``I hope the president can negotiate a better agreement with
South Korea,'' Bruce said. ``It would be tragic to give away the
technology a second time.''
   The agreement calls for development by General Dynamics and
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of an advanced version of the F-16
fighter, named FSX.
   The Senate legislation would have barred Japan from transferring
U.S. aerospace technology to third parties or to its own civilian
aerospace industry.
   Administration supporters said those concerns already had been
satisfied.
   In vetoing the FSX resolution on July 31, Bush tried to shift the
debate to constitutional grounds, a theme adopted by senators on
both sides of the issue.
   ``I cannot accept binding provisions ... that would tie my hands
in the exercise of my constitutional responsibilities'' (to conduct
foreign policy), he said.
   Bush said the legislation would inject the General Accounting
Office, an agency of the legislative branch, into the administration
of the jet program ``in a highly intrusive manner, trespassing on
the constitutional powers of the president.''
   And he said it would require the reopening of negotiations,
``damage the prospects for a successful agreement,'' and damage the
U.S.-Japanese security relationship.
   Speaking immediately before the vote, Senate Republican Leader
Bob Dole of Kansas urged colleagues to forego ``meddling'' and
``micromanagement.''
   But senators seeking to overturn _ including a number of
Republicans _ said the veto represented a direct threat to the power
specifically granted Congress by the Constitution to regulate trade.
   ``If we agree (with the veto) then there has been a very
substantial rollback in the authority of the Congress of the United
States on issues related to international trade,'' said Sen. John C.
Danforth, R-Mo.
   ``This is trying to muscle the other fellow off the beach.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
