<FIRST>r w PM-NixonImpeachment     09-14 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nixon Impeachment,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate to Take Up Judge's Case in October</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate committee hearing
evidence in the impeachment case against U.S. District Judge Walter
Nixon says he expects the trial before the full Senate to begin next
month.
   ``The parties should be prepared to proceed by Oct. 17,'' Sen.
Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., said Wednesday.
   During four days of testimony from five witnesses, the committee
heard evidence concerning allegations that Nixon lied about his
involvement in a marijuana smuggling case against the son of a
wealthy oil man with business connections to the judge.
   Nixon, 60, the chief federal judge in Mississippi's southern
district, is serving a five-year prison sentence after being
convicted of perjury in a federal trial in 1988.
   He'll lose his judgeship and its $89,500 annual salary if the
Senate reaches the same conclusions as the trial jury.
   The House, which acts as prosecutor in impeachment cases,
contends Nixon lied when he told federal investigators he had never
discussed the drug case with anyone or influenced its outcome.
   The Senate committee will prepare a report of the undisputed
facts of Nixon's case and a summary of the disputed facts with
evidence from both sides, but will not make a recommendation on
whether Nixon should be impeached.
   All senators will get copies of the documents, a transcript of
the hearings and the evidence presented at the hearings before they
hear final statements from both sides of the case in public session.
They will then lock themselves in a closed session, similar to jury
deliberations, to debate the case.
   The vote on three articles of impeachment, which were approved
unanimously by the House, will take place in public session.
   In his closing statement Wednesday, Nixon's lawyer said the judge
had no reason to lie because there was nothing improper about his
only contact with the narcotics case in question.
   But Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., in closing arguments for
the House, said Nixon ``fixed'' the narcotics case for Drew
Fairchild because he had made a lucrative investment in oil
properties with his father, Wiley Fairchild, and wanted more.
   ``Obviously, there are two versions of the events here,'' said
Sensenbrenner. ``Judge Nixon's version ... is certainly more benign
than the collective picture painted by the other witnesses.''
   The articles of impeachment allege:
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he never discussed the case
against Drew Fairchild with Holmes.
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he had nothing to do
officially or unofficially with the Fairchild case and never
influenced anyone in the case.
   _Nixon undermined ``the integrity of the judiciary'' and
disobeyed the law by making 14 false or misleading statements during
an interview with the federal investigators and in his sworn grand
jury testimony.
</TEXT>
