<FIRST>r w PM-HelperMonkeys     09-14 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helper Monkeys,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animal Activists Fight Use of Monkeys by Disabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal welfare activists are opposing attempts
to train Capuchin monkeys to provide small tasks and companionship
to quadriplegics because they say the animals are subjected to cruel
government treatment and never become fully tame.
   ``It simply is not possible to use monkeys in this type of
program and still be humane,'' the Committee for Humane Legislation,
an umbrella group for several animal welfare groups, told a House
panel Wednesday.
   The testimony came before the Veterans Affairs subcommittee on
hospitals and health care, which is considering legislation
introduced by Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy, D-Mass., that would set up a
program providing helper monkeys for 20 disabled veterans and helper
dogs for 10.
   Although veterans' groups are pushing the idea, the animal rights
activists said attempts to domesticate the monkeys are misguided.
   ``Monkeys are wild animals and no amount of training will ever
change that,'' said Leslie Fain of the Committee for Humane
Legislation.
   According to the activists, monkeys trained as helpers have their
teeth removed and are subjected to electric shock that causes them
to have diarrhea. Fain said the monkeys' natural curiosity could
cause them to harm people they are supposed to help.
   ``Quadriplegics have lost caretakers who quit because of monkey
attacks ...,'' she said. ``Driving controls on the quadriplegics'
wheelchairs have been used in some cases by monkeys to drive their
owners into walls.''
   The humane group and the American Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals say other, mechanical devices can be used.
   But the Paralyzed Veterans of America, one of the groups favoring
the legislation, disputes such claims.
   ``At the present time there is no effective technology which can
imitate the simple, routine tasks which humans perform,'' said John
C. Bollinger, associate legislative director of the paralyzed
veterans group.
   Dr. Mary Joan Willard, professor of medicine at the Boston
University School of Medicine and director of the non-profit Helping
Hands group, said the use of the simians saves $3,777 a year by
reducing _ never eliminating _ the need for a human attendant.
   She said the monkeys can be trained and that after several months
they treat the owner, attendant and family as part of a ``troop.''
   Tooth extraction is necessary to control biting, she said, and
this is done ``without any deleterious effects on their health or
subsequent behavior.'' It has been done for years with organ-grinder
monkeys, she said.
   About 220,000 people in the United States have spinal cord
injuries, and about half of those are quadriplegics. About 28,000
veterans are quadriplegic, according to VA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
