<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearNomination     09-14 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Nomination,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Considering Dropping Choice for Key Energy Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is considering dropping its
widely criticized nomination of a former department store buyer to
head an Energy Department office responsible for monitoring safety
at nuclear weapons plants, an official said.
   Diane Kay Morales is a ``very competent, accomplished person,''
but may not be the right choice for the sensitive position of
assistant secretary for environment, safety and health, Deputy
Secretary Henson Moore said in an interview Wednesday.
   ``Diane Morales is reconsidering what she wants to do and the
White House is reconsidering what it wants her to do,'' Moore said,
adding the requirements of the job have grown as more problems have
been uncovered at the weapons plants.
   He cited as an example a new Energy Department investigative
report on the Fernald nuclear weapons plant in Ohio. A summary of
the report released Wednesday listed dozens of environmental
problems at the uranium processing plant, although it said none of
the shortcomings posed an imminent threat to the public.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins, in an internal memorandum
obtained Wednesday, said he was dispatching a team of environment,
safety and health experts to Fernald to beef up the staff there
until he can hire permanent additions.
   Moore said the investigation's results showed ``we have to get
this department into a serious high-gear mode of operation to come
into compliance'' with federal and state environmental and health
and safety standards.
   The department's office of environment, safety and health was
created in 1985 to monitor the nuclear weapons facilities _
including 17 major installations in 12 states _ which have fallen
into disrepair and in some cases contaminated soil and groundwater
with improperly stored hazardous wastes.
   Moore said no decision had been made on whether to resubmit the
Morales nomination to the Senate, which sent it back to the White
House in late July after putting off a hearing. The Senate Energy
and Natural Resources Committee said it wanted more information
about Watkins' plans for reorganizing the department before
considering Ms. Morales.
   ``We now realize that the demands of the job are much more severe
than we had seen previously,'' Moore said. He said there had been no
effort so far to look for another nominee.
   Moore said, however, the administration is ready to fight for the
controversial nomination of Victor Stello as assistant secretary for
defense programs, the office responsible for weapons production. The
Senate energy panel is expected to consider the Stello nomination in
October.
   Stello came under renewed fire this week from environmental
groups that claim his record at the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
shows a lack of commitment to nuclear safety.
   ``We haven't seen anything to cause us to review or reassess
this,'' Moore said. ``The choice of Victor Stello sends a signal
that for the first time in the history of these nuclear facilities
... we have chosen a regulator to lead this program rather than a
producer.''
   The Morales nomination drew fire from environmental and labor
groups soon after the White House announced it April 12. The main
objection is that Ms. Morales' previous experience lends little to
the demands of an office seeking to improve the weapons plants'
compliance with environmental, health and safety laws.
   Ms. Morales worked from 1971 to 1980 for Neiman-Marcus, the
department store chain, managing two departments and assisting in
buying for 14 stores.
   She held several government jobs from 1981 to 1986, including
membership on the Civil Aeronautics Board, and she later founded an
environmental consulting company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
