<FIRST>r w PM-Cheney-Congress     09-14 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheney-Congress,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney to Congress: Do As I Say, Not As I Did</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is attempting to
get his former colleagues on Capitol Hill to show the willpower he
admits he lacked at times as a congressman.
   ``I think it's important for people to remember that as a member
of Congress, I voted for every single defense program that was ever
put in front of me. You can't name a defense program I didn't like.
I loved them all,'' Cheney said in a speech Wednesday before a
conservative forum.
   But now, as the top man at the Pentagon, Cheney says he has a new
perspective.
   ``Now ... I've got to figure out how to pay for them,'' he said.
   In remarks before the Hudson Institute, Cheney conceded he may
have made mistakes in some of his votes on Capitol Hill and he tried
to use some introspection to convince his former colleagues that
he'd learned a lesson.
   The former Wyoming representative said that as Congress makes key
budget decisions, lawmakers must show they have the willpower to cut
entire programs in order to hold the line on the nation's defense
budget.
   Attempts to cut overall spending while leaving programs intact
with less money will not solve the budget problem, Cheney said.
   In presenting President Bush's fiscal 1990 budget to Capitol
Hill, Cheney recommended killing the V-22 Osprey, a vertical
take-off plane, and canceling the F-14D jet fighter. He called the
requests ``a whole new concept in this town.''
   The House voted to restore funds to both programs and the Senate
has authorized research and development funds for the Osprey.
   The secretary said congressmen ``love to vote to reduce the top
line, to cut back on the overall amount on spending'' to solve
budget problems.
   ``Then it's my task to keep all the programs alive and the bases
open, because they don't want to cancel anything,'' he said.
   Cheney said members of Congress who have voted against defense
programs for the past decade are ``now coming down to my office ...
saying I hope you won't cut out my base or shut down my production
line.''
   But the former congressman admitted he'd done the same thing.
   ``I will not argue here today, that I was above, on occasion,
trying to have it both ways on an issue. That's a normal human
desire,'' Cheney said. ``But these decisions are far too important
for us to allow that to happen this time around. Congress must make
some choices.''
   He praised the Senate for coming closer to the administration's
wish-list in its work on the Pentagon's budget, although he
criticized the Senate Appropriation defense subcommittee for voting
Tuesday to slash funding for the Trident 2, the Navy's newest and
most supposedly most deadly weapon.
</TEXT>
