<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0402EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EmergencyCare     09-14 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emergency Care,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Say Emergency Rooms Being Stretched Thin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getting emergency room treatment in some
hospitals can be as stressful these days as the emergency itself,
say physicians who warn another health-care crisis is looming.
   In some cities, ambulances roam the streets trying to find an
emergency room that has space and patients can wait hours, even
days, in the emergency department for a hospital bed to become
available.
   ``This is the future health care crisis,'' said Dr. Charlotte S.
Yeh, a board member of the American College of Emergency Physicians
and chief of emergency medicine at the Newton-Wellesley Hospital in
Newton, Mass.
   ``We are the safety net,'' she said. ``When you're sick and don't
have anywhere to go and you're scared and don't know what you've
got, our doors are open 24 hours a day, seven days a week. But we're
becoming overloaded.''
   ``The net is being stretched so thin we're worried about the
future of the health care system,'' she said.
   Emergency physicians described the problems Wednesday as they
released a draft report based on a survey of the college's state
chapters.
   The pressure on hospital emergency rooms is coming from the
growing AIDS epidemic, increased illegal drug use and an estimated
37 million Americans who have no health insurance and who get health
care only through emergency rooms.
   Adding to the burden are medical staff shortages, financial
pressures that are leading a growing number of hospitals to close
their doors, and an inadequate number of nursing home beds, they
said.
   Some patients in New York City emergency rooms have waited for
hospital beds for more than a week, said Dr. Stephan G. Lynn,
director of emergency medicine at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital
Center in New York City.
   ``Frequently, we admit people to the hospital with a diagnosis
like heart attack and we do cardiograms and blood tests and three or
four days later they leave ... never having seen an intensive care
unit or a cardiac care unit, never having left the emergency
department,'' Lynn said.
   The Harbor UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles emergency room is
so crowded it is closed to ambulance traffic 25 percent of the time,
said Dr. Robert Hockberger, chairman of the Department of Emergency
Medicine.
   The problem is most critical in the Northeast and on the West
Coast, but the survey found emergency rooms across the country are
backed up. Forty-one state chapters of the college reported
overcrowding in emergency rooms in their states. Nine reported no
backups: Idaho, Minnesota, Nebraska, New Hampshire, New Mexico,
North Dakota, Oregon, Utah and Wyoming.
   Chapters in West Virginia, North Carolina, Alabama and Alaska
noted ``overcrowding is not simply a problem of this nation's
cities,'' according to the draft report.
   The physicians said it is not known whether long emergency room
stays have led to more patient deaths, but they said these patients
often receive only marginal care.
   ``The lights never go out. The noise never turns off. Meals are
served, but on an irregular basis and rarely are as palatable or
warm as they are on the in-patient side,'' Lynn said.
   Patients ``spend their entire stay lying on a stretcher with a
mattress that is two inches thick.''
   ``That level of care is inadequate,'' he said. ``Emergency
departments were not designed and are not equipped or staffed to
provide intensive care services or in-patient services.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
