<DOCNO> AP890914-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0410EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SocialSecurity-Morale     09-14 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Security-Morale,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Morale Seen Low Among Social Security Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of Social Security Administration
employees depicts a discontented and overworked work force, but the
agency's new chief says she is confident morale is improving.
   ``I am absolutely confident that the problem of low morale is one
that we're going to spend a lot of time paying some attention to and
making some changes in those numbers,'' Social Security
Administration Gwendolyn King said Wednesday.
   According to the survey conducted in April, 51 percent of Social
Security employees say their morale is poor or extremely poor, up
from 43 percent in 1987. Seventy-four percent said they were often
or very often overworked.
   The share of supervisors who said the SSA was doing a poor or
very poor job of providing the best possible service to Social
Security recipients rose to 37 percent, up from 26 percent in the
1987 poll.
   The survey, conducted by the Institute for Behavioral Research in
Creativity in Salt Lake City, Utah, was released by Mrs. King, who
took office last month.
   The April survey came toward the end of a six-year period in
which the SSA work force was slashed by 20 percent to 65,000 as part
of a campaign to modernize and streamline operations.
   ``Downsizing, the introduction of new technology and the
inevitable difficulties in managing change could be expected to lead
to a rise in employee discontent,'' the report said.
   Mrs. King said workers would be encouraged to take the time
necessary to provide quality service, more would be done to reward
good performance, and more equipment and personnel might be shifted
to areas in need.
   Among other findings in the survey:
   _68 percent of workers said there was quite a lot or some signs
of employee discontent.
   _46 percent of supervisors said they were given encouragement and
opportunities to learn and improve their job skills, up from 40
percent in 1987.
   The report's recommendations included: improved communication
with lower-level employees about the agency's long-term goals, more
discussion among employees and management, paying increased
attention to worker contributions, and providing more flexibility to
solve problems at lower management levels.
</TEXT>
