<FIRST>r w PM-PainTherapy     09-14 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pain Therapy,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>NIH Panel Endorses Some Use Of Pain To Control Destructive Behavior</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocacy groups for the retarded charge that a
report saying the use of pain as part of medical treatment to
prevent the retarded from hurting themselves can be beneficial is
``biased and unscientific.''
   A panel of experts convened by the National Institutes of Health
issued the report Wednesday saying that although the techniques may
seem distasteful, it's possible to control self-destructive acts
like head-banging, biting and eye poking.
   Experts have been unable to explain why some people do such
things, or why the pain involved does not halt the action and
prevent a recurrence.
   Some techniques involving pain include an electrical shock device
that is sold for use in private homes, and the use of foul-tasting
chemicals or smells.
   While the panel did not oppose the use of pain to modify
self-destructive behavior, its report said it ``should only be used
in the context of a comprehensive and individualized behavior
enhancement treatment package.''
   ``Most successful approaches involve multiple types of therapy,''
said Dr. R. Rodney Howell, a University of Miami School of Medicine
professor who chaired the committee. He acknowledged ``certain of
these techniques have a negative impression to the public ... even
though they might be beneficial.''
   But Dr. Ralph Maurer, a professor of medicine at the University
of Florida, attacked the finding as ``bad medicine.''
   ``If a medical student used the kind of logic used here, you
would fail him,'' Maurer said. ``The use of these procedures is bad
medicine and its being carried off as good medicine.''
   The NIH panel was convened to consider the appropriate methods of
treating mentally disabled patients, mostly children, who habitually
hurt themselves. The committee said about 160,000 patients in the
United States exhibit destructive behavior and the cost of caring
for them last year was about $3 billion.
   Some doctors and parents control the behavior through aversion
techniques that use pain or discomfort to cause the patient to
change actions. These techniques include delivering a mild
electrical shock, forcing lemon juice or bitter tastes into the
mouth, blowing air on the face, or forcing the patient to smell
strong ammonia salts.
   Officials from several organizations representing the mentally
retarded presented testimony in opposition to the use of painful
therapy and held a news conference after the NIH panel report was
presented.
   Marcia D. Smith, a psychologist for a Maryland organization
called Community Services for Autistic Adults and Children, said,
``For the last 10 years, we have not used painful methods and our
techniques have worked.''
   She said the panel ignored ``the great body of work'' that has
shown pain-based therapy to be flawed, and, as a result, the report
by the committee is ``biased and one-sided.''
</TEXT>
