<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor     09-14 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley Says City Attorney's Report Clears Him of Wrongdoing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley insists a lengthy
investigation exonerated him of wrongdoing as a paid consultant to
two banks, even though the probe resulted in a lawsuit against him.
   ``I would never do anything to harm Los Angeles,'' the fifth-term
mayor said in a televised speech Wednesday. ``I will not let you
down.''
   Hours earlier, City Attorney James Hahn said Bradley had stepped
into a ``gray area of the law'' for his dealings with the banks that
do business with the city. Hahn said the evidence was insufficient
to prosecute Bardley.
   Still, Hahn filed a Superior Court lawsuit that alleges six
failures to report investments, two of them in excess of $100,000.
   The lawsuit was timed with the release of a 1,613-page report on
a five-month investigation by Hahn's office into Bradley's ties with
Far East National Bank and Valley Federal Savings and Loan
Association.
   While Hahn's report cleared the 71-year-old mayor of prosecutable
offenses, ``no vindication of the mayor's conduct is intended,
implied or should in any way be inferred,'' the report said.
   Bradley acknowleged a perceived conflict of interest with his
tenure as a paid director of Valley Federal. The city attorney found
no evidence Bradley was aware he was acting on zoning for
subsidiaries of Valley Federal.
   Bradley also acknowledged that his role as a paid international
trade adviser to Far East and the deposit, without bidding, of $2
million in city funds there, had created ``regrettable
misperceptions.'' But he said he was not involved in the city
treasurer's decision to make the deposit.
   ``When all is said and done, the inquiry confirms what I have
said all along: I did not engage in conflicts of interest. I did not
violate the public's trust,'' he declared.
   After the speech, City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky said Bradley
had some more explaining to do. ``This is not a speech that is going
to close the door on this,'' Yaroslavsky said.
   Councilman Michael Woo said the day's events should prompt the
council to ``write new laws that will prevent these types of
conflicts from taking place in the future.''
   Bradley still faces possible state and federal investigations of
his ties to a city-funded task force for Africa and to the
investment banking firm of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and of an
alleged cover-up by the city treasurer's office.
   Hahn said it was apparent that a March 22 telephone call from
Bradley to City Treasurer Leonard Rittenberg did influence
Rittenberg to deposit $2 million with Far East. Bradley was paid
$18,000 as a consultant to the bank, which he returned when media
attention fell on the case.
   It was also obvious, Hahn said, that someone altered financial
bid sheets following a reporter's inquiry about the deposit.
   Bradley, however, insisted that the report's failure to find any
wrongdoing by him was ``the bottom line.'' The mayor also expressed
confidence his attorneys and Hahn would settle the lawsuit.
   ``The errors I made were not deliberate; they only show that I am
not an accountant, and that I shouldn't have tried to be one,'' he
said, smiling.
   Citing his 47 years as a police officer, councilman and mayor,
Bradley tried to put the investigation behind him and look ahead.
   ``The issue is _ I'm going to put it to rest, put it behind us
and I think the people are going to do the same,'' he said. ``Let me
enjoy for a moment my fifth term.''
</TEXT>
