<HEAD>Singer Wayne Newton Offers Help in Vegas Musicians Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Wayne Newton, the biggest ongoing draw in
Las Vegas showrooms, met with striking musicians to help end the
3-month-old labor dispute that forced him to cancel a
$250,000-a-week engagement.
   Newton spent most of Wednesday's session with the executive
committee of Musicians Union Local 369, which is striking the Las
Vegas Hilton and four other resorts in a dispute over taped music
and guaranteed work.
   ``He said it's a tough spot to be in but he doesn't mind taking
the heat if there is a way to help,'' said union leader Mark Tully
Massagli. ``He's offered his services in whatever way he's needed to
help settle this thing.''
   Newton, who on Tuesday canceled a scheduled three-week engagement
at the Hilton because of the strike, previously had held an informal
meeting between Massagli and Hilton executives.
   ``He's got a lot at stake personally in terms of his contract,
which is for a lot of money,'' said Owen Daley, a Hilton spokesman.
``But he's also a community activist and he knows people on both
sides in this thing.''
   Massagli said no role for Newton was defined in the meeting with
the union's executive committee but that Newton, a Las Vegas
resident who spends much of his time performing before packed
showrooms, could provide a spark to get talks moving.
   The two sides last met Monday. No new talks were scheduled.
   The dispute centers over the insistence of the hotels to replace
musicians in production shows with live music and their
unwillingness to guarantee work for musicians who work the main
showrooms.
