<FIRST>r w PM-DOD-Environment     09-14 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DOD-Environment,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says DOD Should Check Environmental Problems at Bases
Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department should look into
environmental problems at U.S. bases in Europe as those countries
continue to emphasize cleaning up the environment, a Georgia
congressman says.
   Rep. Richard Ray, chairman of the House Armed Services
environmental restoration subcommittee, said Wednesday that his
12-day tour of bases in Europe last month convinced him that there
is ``a changing environmental consciousness in Europe.''
   Ray, a Democrat, said the United States should begin cataloging
environmental problems at its European bases to determine if each
problem was caused by the United States or already existed.
   ``We need to know in advance the cause of these problems,'' he
said. ``Many of them could have been there since World War II.''
   Ray said he intends to hold hearings next year on Defense
Department environmental programs outside U.S. borders.
   ``Changing environmental laws throughout Europe could require
large expenditures of funds in order to comply with the new laws or
to clean up past disposal, storage or spill problems,'' he said.
   Ray said he will focus the hearings initially on U.S. bases in
Europe, but that the department also should be preparing an
assessment of environmental problems at its bases throughout the
world.
   ``Anywhere we are located in the world we need to be a good
citizen, and we need to be practicing good environmental policies,''
he said.
   Ray said U.S. military bases abroad generally operate under much
less stringent environmental standards than do domestic bases
covered by American environmental laws.
   Ray visited U.S. bases in Germany, Great Britain and Italy during
his European trip. He also visited the headquarters of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization in Brussels and met with government
leaders in Bonn, West Germany.
</TEXT>
