<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-14 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Nikkei Rebounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen for a third
day today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main barometer rebounded.
   The dollar closed at 145.85 yen, down 0.85 yen from the previous
day's 147.03-yen finish. It opened at 146.05 yen and ranged between
145.50 yen and 146.43 yen.
   The dollar has fallen 1.92 yen since closing at a nearly
three-month high of 147.77 yen on Monday.
   Its lower opening Thursday followed a decline on overseas markets
overnight. It fell further during the day as the Bank of Japan
intervened to support the yen by selling dollars, traders said.
   Other traders said the market was awaiting such U.S. economic
figures as August retail sales, due to be announced later Thursday
in Washington, and the July merchandise trade figures, due Friday.
   Volume was estimated at $9.861 billion, up from $7.696 billion
Wednesday.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose by 114.94 points, or 0.34
percent, ending the week's trading at 34,401.80. The index had lost
45.94 points Wednesday.
   The stock and foreign exchange markets will be closed Friday for
the Respect for the Aged national holiday.
   ``Many market players bought issues based on their optimistic
outlook for next week, when they expect economic factors to turn
more favorable for stock investment,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama, a
senior dealer with Nikko Securities.
   ``As a whole, however, the market was rather inactive, with many
participants sitting on the sidelines,'' he said. They, too, were
awaiting the U.S. economic figures, he said.
   First section volume was estimated at 550 million shares, down
from Wednesday's 600 million. Nearly 1 billion shares are traded in
a normal trading day.
   Other dealers attributed the index's recovery to the yen's
recovery against the dollar.
   Meanwhile, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. stock was quoted
at 1.53 million yen ($10,490), up 20,000 yen ($137) from Wednesday,
following the government's announcement that it will put off its
fourth sale of NTT shares at least until March 1990.
   Traders said NTT share buying was based on confidence there would
not be a surge in the supply of NTT stock in the market.
   The original date for the fourth sale had not been made public.
Since NTT, the former government monopoly in telecommunications, was
turned into a private firm on April 1, 1985, the government has sold
5.4 million shares, 35 percent of the shares it owned.
   In announcing the decision to postpone the fourth sale, the
government cited a recent slump in NTT share prices.
   NTT posted a 14.3 percent decline in unconsolidated pretax
profits for the fiscal year that ended March 31, its reorganization
now is being discussed, and its chairman resigned last December in
connection with a widespread bribery case that also has shaken the
governing Liberal Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
