<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Bases 1stLd-Writethru a0499 09-14 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Bases, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino: Bases To Be Determined Primarily By Filipino Not Regional
Interests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: RESTORES dropped word in 4th graf, CORRECTS in 7th graf that
$461 million a year. Picks up 8th, `U.S. officials ...' ^By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said today
that she will decide whether to allow U.S. military bases to stay
after 1991 primarily on Filipino interests rather than regional
security concerns.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Mrs. Aquino said she
was waiting to hear what Washington was prepared to offer before
making her decision on the bases, whose lease expires in September
1991.
   U.S. and Filipino officials are expected to begin talks late this
year on the future of Clark Air Base, the Subic Bay naval base and
four smaller installations.
   U.S. officials claim the bases are essential for maintaining
security in the Far East, including the six-member Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, to which the Philippines belongs.
   ``I will decide this based on what I believe will be in the
interest of the Filipino people,'' Mrs. Aquino said. ``While it is
true we are of ASEAN, my first consideration naturally is for the
interest of the Filipino people and after that what will benefit the
ASEAN region.''
   Singapore has offered air and naval facilities in case the
Philippines closes the U.S. installations. But American officials
say Singapore's facilities cannot match the size and location of
those in the Philippines.
   Last October, the United States agreed to pay $461 million a year
in aid to keep the bases until 1991.
   U.S. officials warn that Washington is not prepared to pay
substantially more for the bases because they contribute to
Philippine defense.
   During the interview, Mrs. Aquino refused to say whether she
believes the bases guarantee regional security. She noted, however,
that the presence of American bases did not prevent Japanese forces
from invading this island nation during World War II.
   ``If you are referring to the Second World War, they didn't, as
you know, contribute too much,'' she said. ``In fact, there are
people who think that perhaps we were the first to be attacked
simply because of the presence of U.S. bases.''
   Vice President Dan Quayle is expected to discuss the bases issue
when he arrives Sep. 26 for a three-day visit. The issue is also
expected to be raised when Mrs. Aquino visits the United States in
November.
   Any new bases agreement must be ratified by two-thirds of the
23-member Philippine Senate. Last month, 12 senators called for the
bases to be closed in 1991. That would be enough to block any
extension of the agreement.
   Mrs. Aquino also refused to say whether she personally believes a
new agreement would be in the national interest.
   ``I don't think this is the time to be defining it because we
don't know, first of all, do the Americans still want to use these
facilities,'' she said.
   ``And secondly, what are they wanting in the matter of the use of
these bases, and, also, what are they prepared to do. This has to be
discussed lengthily if and when we start talks on the bases.''
   Regardless of the outcome, Mrs. Aquino said she wanted to retain
close ties with the United States, the Philippines' former colonial
ruler.
   ``I am hoping that both the Americans and the Filipinos can
maintain a very friendly relationship because we Filipinos would
like to believe that there is more (to the relationship) than just
the matter of the bases,'' she said.
   ``I think sometimes some of us believe that maybe where some
Americans are concerned, the only thing that probably ties the two
nations together is the presence of the U.S. facilities in our
bases.''
</TEXT>
