<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0602EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OperationRescue     09-14 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Operation Rescue,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Operation Rescue Founder, Four Other Anti-Abortionists Acquitted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury declared Operation Rescue founder
Randall Terry and four members of the radical anti-abortion group
innocent of misdemeanor charges stemming from blockades of women's
health clinics.
   Jurors indicated Wednesday after delivering their verdicts that
they had accepted Terry's ``necessity defense,'' in which he and his
co-defendants claimed laws can be broken to prevent a greater harm.
   The Municipal Court judge had told the jury to disregard this
defense because abortions are legal.
   Terry, who represented himself, praised the jury's decisions.
   ``Thank God that the jurors had the courage to declare that our
efforts were to save children and not a deliberate attempt to commit
a crime,'' Terry said in a statement.
   The acquittals were greeted with dismay by the California
Abortion Rights Action League.
   ``I am flabbergasted that the jury did not convict the defendants
of trespassing and conspiracy,'' said Robin Schneider, the group's
executive director.
   After four days of deliberation, the jury found the activists
innocent of five misdemeanor charges, including trespassing and
resisting arrest.
   The jury also deadlocked 8-4 for conviction on conspiracy counts
against Terry, 30, of Binghamton, N.Y., Michael McMonagle, 36, of
Philadelphia and Jeff White, 31.
   Judge Richard Paez declared a mistrial on those counts, meaning
they could be refiled. Prosecutors said a decision on refiling would
be made by Oct. 2.
   The others on trial were Don Bennette, 36, of Mission Viejo, and
Andrew Eppink, 41, of Palmdale.
   The case stemmed from the blockade of a Los Angeles women's
clinic on March 25. The demonstrations were held as the U.S. Supreme
Court considered a Missouri law it eventually upheld, broadening the
role of states in regulating abortions.
   The five were on trial for allegedly ignoring a federal
injunction barring activists from blocking entrances to abortion
clinics. Terry denied he ever was served a copy of the injunction.
   Juror Priscilla Ramos agreed with Terry, saying the men ``were
trying to save lives and we were for that, too. I'd love to shake
Randall Terry's hand.''
   Juror Edmond Bleavins, 43, said he hoped the verdict would send a
message to the police department. ``The police just brutalized these
people in my opinion,'' he said.
   Bleavins said he did not intend to give Operation Rescue the
message they could ``keep on doing what they've been doing.'' He
said the jury deadlocked on conspiracy because at least one juror
believed the defendants' intent was not to break the law but to save
babies.
   The judge had admonished Terry and the other defendants for
repeatedly drawing the jury's attention to their stance against
legal abortions.
   During the trial, Terry frequently referred to abortion clinics
as ``aboratorium,'' ``killing centers'' and ``abortion mills,''
prompting Paez to rebuke him for using inflammatory language.
   The issue at trial was not abortion, but trespassing, the judge
said, ruling the defendants' motives for their actions were not
legitimate defenses in the case.
</TEXT>
