<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Students     09-14 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Students,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Humanities Graduate Students Must Take A Year Off And Work In The
Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most new humanities graduate students will have to
take a year off to work in factories or rural areas to improve their
``political understanding'', an official report said today.
   The China Youth News daily said first-year graduate students will
be sent to work in ``grass-roots units'' for ``training.''
   The announcement by the State Education Commission applies to
students studying philosophy, economics, history, law, education and
literature.
   It was the latest effort by the government to increase student
exposure to work programs and political education following
authorities' violent crackdown on the pro-democracy movement in June.
   The government claims students joined the movement because they
were politically and socially naive.
   The daily quoted the Education Commission as saying, ``Working in
grass-roots units is good for reforming graduates' thinking. It
helps to correct their problems of lacking practical experience, and
ignorance of the country and the masses.''
   It said the training will help ensure that students remain
faithful to ``socialist principles'' and oppose ``bourgeois
liberalization'', or support of Western ideas.
   The students can only go back to school after they complete their
training, the newspaper said.
   The government has denied the work programs are a throwback to
the Cultural Revolution, when millions of students and intellectuals
were sent to the countryside to work as manual laborers for up to 10
years.
   Last month the government announced that civil servants who
graduated from college in 1985 or later must work one or two years
in ``grass-roots units'' to improve their political understanding.
   Many young government workers joined the demonstrations or
expressed support for their democratic goals.
   The civil servants were warned that their residence permits,
required for living and working in Beijing, will be switched to
their new locations and they will only be allowed to return to the
capital if they perform well.
   Beijing University, a hotbed of protest during the spring
pro-democracy movement, has had its freshman class cut from 2,100 to
800 and has been told that the majority of new students must spend a
year studying at a military school in another city before coming to
Beijing.
   Students at all Beijing universities are being required to start
the school year with a month of political education classes in which
they must study government documents justifying the crackdown on the
``counterrevolutionary rebellion'' and the need to fight bourgeois
liberalization.
</TEXT>
