<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan-Murder     09-14 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-Murder,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Pioneer Slain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yu Teng-fa, a pioneer in Taiwan's political
opposition movement, was slain at his home, police said today.
   Yu, 86, a member of the Democratic Progressive Party, was found
dead Wednesday at his home in Kaohsiung, about 210 miles south of
Taipei, where he lived alone. Relatives said a visitor found him on
his back in a pool of blood.
   Chen Yueh-ying, Yu's daughter-in-law and Kaohsiung magistrate,
told reporters he suffered a deep wound on the back of his head. The
local coroner said Yu probably died of a blow by a blunt object.
   Police declined to speculate on whether Yu was slain by political
opponents, but Democratic Progressive Party leaders suggested he was
the victim of a plot by the ruling Nationalist Party.
   ``Violence has overshadowed Taiwan as we are preparing to
campaign for the December elections,'' opposition party chairman
Huang Hsin-chieh said in a statement.
   The December elections for legislative, mayoral and magisterial
seats will be the first since opposition parties were legalized
after martial law was lifted in 1987.
   The Nationalist Party denied the accusations and issued a
statement condemning ``any individuals or groups that try to provoke
disputes with sensational remarks.''
   Yu, a rich land and property owner, had supported his
daughter-in-law and two grandchildren running in the December
elections as opposition candidates. The Yu family has dominated
Kaohsiung politics for the past three decades.
   Yu, born in Taiwan to a farm family in 1903, was elected a member
of the Nationalist government's National Assembly in 1947. But he
left the Nationalist Party the following year and subsequently
became a pioneering member of Taiwan's opposition movement.
   Yu was elected Kaohsiung magistrate in 1960. He was suspended
from the job three years later on corruption charges.
   He was sentenced to eight years' imprisonment in 1979 on charges
of helping spread Communist propaganda but was released on bail the
following year for hospital treatment of an undisclosed illness from
which he later recovered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
