<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0607EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Romania     09-14 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Romania,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Tourists Report Beating By Romanian Border Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty Poles told their embassy in Hungary
they were beaten by Romanian border soldiers after being forced off
a train en route to Bucharest, the state news agency reported today.
   The tourists were traveling from Budapest Tuesday night when they
were told by the Romanian soldiers to leave the train, forced to
turn over their passports and left on a station platform while the
train departed, according to the PAP report.
   ``When I asked for my passport, I was dragged by force inside the
office, where I was brutally beaten,'' PAP quoted Bogdan Zapart of
Legnica as saying.
   He said the soldiers used rifles and tear gas to beat and harass
other Poles coming to his aid, and the group was locked in a waiting
room, PAP reported.
   Zapart said he was handcuffed to a chair and beaten repeatedly,
PAP said.
   Emilia Kwietniewska, of Bialogard, said she saw messages on the
walls of the waiting room written in Polish by other Poles about
beatings, robberies and other attacks.
   ON Wednesday morning, the Romanians demanded a payment of 2,000
lei ($167 at the official exchange rate or $28 on the black market)
to release Zapart, and then put the travelers on a train back to
Budapest, PAP said.
   The story was reported on the front pages of several Polish
newspapers today, including one that used the headline ``Romanian
border soliders are robbing and raping?'' and then asked, ``Does Mr.
Ceausescu know about this?'' referring to Romania's hard-line
Communist leader.
</TEXT>
