<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-14 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower against most major currencies
in nervous European trading early today as traders awaited the
release of key U.S. economic indicators. Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said the dollar fell sharply in earlier Asian trading
amid speculation that West Germany may raise its interest rates,
then recovered some of its losses in European dealings.
   They said the dollar, whose underlying trend is bullish, should
be little affected by today's release of U.S. retail sales figures,
which were expected to rise by 0.1 percent.
   U.S. trade figures for July, due out on Friday, should have a
greater impact, dealers said. The market anticipated the deficit to
widen to $9 billion from $8.17 billion in June.
   ``The bullish sentiment will only disappear if West Germany
raises interest rates or if the U.S. trade deficit is higher than
expected,'' said a trader in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.85 Japanese yen to a closing 145.85 yen. Later, in
London, it edged back up to 146.33 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.9680 West German marks, down from 1.9800
   _1.6965 Swiss francs, down from 1.7095
   _6.6440 French francs, down from 6.6805
   _2.2147 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2300
   _1,414.25 Italian lire, down from 1,419.00
   _1.1833 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1858
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5612 from $1.5530 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $360.35 a troy ounce, up
from $358.50 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $359.80 dollars.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $359.75, up from $358.25 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 47 cents to a closing bid of
$360.40.
   Silver rose in London to a bid price of $5.09 a troy ounce, up
from $5.08 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
