<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0621EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-EthiopianTalks     09-14 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopian Talks,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter: Ethiopian-Eritrean Talks Continue Without Deadline for Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter says he is trying to move
peace negotiations between Ethiopia and Eritrea toward compromise,
but both sides seem satisfied that they were even able to get
together.
   Carter said during a college forum Wednesday that he won't give
the Ethiopian government and the Eritrean People's Liberation Front
a deadline on reaching an agreement. He just wants to move them
beyond the excitement over their first negotiations after 28 years
of fighting.
   ``I spent very frustrating hours this morning with the Eritreans
and Ethiopians, trying to get them to agree on a compromise,''
Carter said. ``They've been in the same room, eating at the same
table, exchanging ideas and information.
   ``Both sides are so proud of what they've done so far that they
are inclined to look upon this partial success as adequate.''
   The talks continued through a sixth day Wednesday without Carter.
   Carter Center spokeswoman Beth Carpenter said talks broke off
late Wednesday and were expected to continue today.
   Carter said he had cautioned both sides against ``negative
reports to the press,'' saying such statements ``make it doubly
difficult for them to go back into negotiations the next day.''
   About 1 million people have died in fighting and famine related
to the war over the independence of Eritrea, a northern province
that contains the East African country's only direct access to the
Red Sea.
   The Eritrean Front in the past has demanded the people of Eritrea
be allowed to vote on whether they want independence, federation
with Ethiopia or autonomy. The government has proposed a greater
measure of autonomy for the province but has unequivocally ruled out
any referendum.
   Carter has said the delegates had agreed to 13 items, but he has
not said what those items were. He also has said that agreeing on an
agenda for future talks would be the most difficult issue.
   The college forum Wednesday was Carter's eighth annual Town Hall
Meeting for students and faculty of Emory University.
   Carter called for more funding for drug treatment, a strong
commitment to the Coast Guard in stopping drugs from reaching the
country, and for encouraging international cooperation in the drug
war. He also called for the Bush administration to monitor the
transfer of funds between U.S. and foreign banks to help monitor the
flow of drug money.
   The crowd roared when one student asked what Carter's favorite
late-night TV program was, and he replied he only watched late-night
television when his daughter, Amy, was on David Letterman's show.
   ``We'd watch to see if Amy had been arrested lately,'' he joked
of his daughter's four civil disobedience arrests, which Letterman
has parodied. ``But so far we've been proud of her every time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
