<FIRST>r a PM-MissAmerica     09-14 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miss America,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss Louisiana, Miss Oklahoma Win Prelims</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss Louisiana gave in to a craving
for chocolate chip cookies after winning the swimsuit contest on the
second night of preliminary competition for the Miss America Pageant.
   Miss Oklahoma won the talent portion Wednesday night with a
rendition of ``Since I Fell For You,'' which she listened to as a
child with her mother.
   Miss Louisiana Stacy King, a green-eyed 5-foot-5 blonde who
weighs 105 pounds, wore a white swimsuit with spaghetti straps at
the shoulders.
   To stay in shape, Miss King plays softball, dances, bicycles and
trains with weights every day.
   She said she also ran up and down steps at her high school
stadium. ``All those stadium steps really paid off,'' Miss King said.
   She said one of her biggest sacrifices for the pageant was giving
up chocolate chip cookies. ``I gave them up right after I won the
state pageant on June 18 _ that's 2{ months. If I lose in Atlantic
City, I'll eat a lot of them.''
   She said she would allow herself the two chocolate chip cookies
left for each contestant before bed as part of a sponsor promotion.
   Miss King, a 23-year-old from Slidell, has a degree in fashion
merchandising from Louisiana Tech University and plans to obtain a
degree in dental hygiene. Eventually, she said she hopes to combine
both degrees to design work uniforms.
   Miss Oklahoma Tamara Denise Toshiko Marler, a 26-year-old from
Tulsa, said she did not rehearse her selection during the day.
   ``I don't practice because it's not fresh that way,'' she said.
``It's just not real.''
   Miss Marler said ``Since I Fell For You'' is special because she
listened to it during her childhood with her mother, who is at the
pageant.
   She said the song rarely fails to move listeners because ``when
you sing love songs ... about hearts getting broken, the audience
can feel it.''
   For her performance, she wore a full-length navy silk gown beaded
with Mediterranean blue bugle beads and featuring a sweetheart
neckline.
   Miss Marler is a marketing graduate of the University of Tulsa
and hopes to become a lawyer.
   The three nights of preliminary competition for the 51
contestants are the first steps to the nationally televised Miss
America finals Saturday night.
   The 10 women who have accumulated the most points in preliminary
competitions and interviews with the judges will become the top 10
finalists. Those 10 will start with a clean slate Saturday night,
competing to succeed Miss America 1989 Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson.
   The 63rd annual pageant will be broadcast on NBC-TV at 10 p.m.
EDT Saturday.
</TEXT>
