<DOCNO> AP890914-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0636EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nader-Japan     09-14 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nader-Japan,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Advocate Urges Greater Protection for Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Nader, America's leading consumer crusader,
said today that information is the root of all consumer protection
and urged a national freedom of information law for Japan.
   Nader said such a law should be patterned after the U.S. Freedom
of Information Act, which he called the strongest guarantee of
information access in the world.
   Japan has no national freedom of information law, although some
states, or prefectures, possess weak ones, Nader told reporters at a
luncheon.
   He said access to information about government spending and
standards is crucial to challenging policies in such areas as
asbestos in public buildings, auto safety, air quality and nuclear
power.
   Access to information also would serve as a tonic to Japan's
lifeless consumer movement, he said.
   ``Now, the ability to turn civic voices into civic success just
isn't here,'' he added.
   For instance, he said a movement to rid public schools of
asbestos can't get off the ground because citizens are unable to
obtain information on what school buildings contain insulation or
roofing made with asbestos.
   Japan's consumers pay among the highest prices in the world for
housing, food and services and its consumer movement has been
relatively weak.
   Big business has had the ear of the governing Liberal Democratic
Party for the past 34 years.
   Consumer groups and analysts say, however, that with the party's
flagging popularity, resulting primarily from a 3 percent sales tax
imposed in April, consumer interests are commanding the attention of
the highest levels of government.
   Nader, whose non-profit Congress Watch is based in Washington,
D.C., said both the United States and Japan aid selected domestic
industries with subsidies, and use trade policies and barriers to
keep competitive products out of their markets.
   Subsidies to Japanese rice farmers cost consumers $18 billion
annually, according to U.S. estimates.
   Since citizens pay for these subsidies and pay higher prices
because of such trade policies, Nader proposed a consumer trust
fund, paid for by protected industries, to support consumer
protection activities.
   He also urged stronger health and safety standards and rigorous
enforcement of anti-monopoly laws, and said citizens should have the
right to file class action lawsuits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
