<FIRST>r a PM-ZsaZsaTrial     09-14 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Fears Aggressive Jailhouse Lesbians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Zsa Zsa Gabor, on trial for
slapping a Beverly Hills cop, says she doesn't want to go to jail
because she's ``afraid of lesbians.''
   The Municipal Court jury that could put the flamboyant actress
behind bars were sworn in Wednesday. Opening arguments were to begin
today.
   On the steps of the courthouse Wednesday, Miss Gabor confided in
reporters her fears of being convicted. A conviction carries a
maximum two years in jail and $4,000 fine.
   ``Mother is so worried,'' Miss Gabor said. ``In a deathly voice,
she phoned me this morning and asked me, `Dahling, are they going to
book you in jail?'
   ``I told her I hoped not. I have claustrophobia and would be very
unhappy in jail.
   ``And besides, they are all lesbians in jail. And I'm so scared
of lesbians. Can you imagine being in jail with all those women?''
   Miss Gabor is charged with misdemeanor battery on a police
officer, disobeying a police officer's orders, driving with an
expired license, having an open container of alcohol in her car and
having an expired car registration.
   She was arrested June 14 after a policeman stopped her for having
expired registration tags on her $215,000 Rolls-Royce Corniche
convertible. While the officer was checking for other infractions,
Miss Gabor allegedly drove away, only to be caught again two blocks
away.
   At that point, the officer said, she slapped him.
   The former Miss Hungary pleaded innocent July 12 and maintains
she was verbally and physically abused by the officer, Paul Kramer.
   The defense's strategy in the trial, which is expected to last
about two weeks, is to show that Kramer had a history of harassing
celebrities.
   Prosecutors have said they would try to prevent the testimony
from being heard. Some of the past incidents involving Kramer are
too old or different from Miss Gabor's to be pertinent to her trial,
prosecutors said.
   Miss Gabor denied she savored the publicity accompanying her
trial.
   ``The Beverly Hills police started this. It was two days later my
press agent called and said, `Zsa Zsa, you have to protect
yourself.' I don't need this publicity,'' she said.
   Whether she needs it or not, the press has hounded Miss Gabor and
her eighth and current husband Prince Frederick von Anhalt,
Germany's Duke of Saxony.
   He wore dark sunglasses in court Wednesday, the third day of
tedious jury selection. Reporters were watching closely to see if he
would fall asleep as he had been reported doing the previous two
days.
   Court documents reveal Miss Gabor was born June 6, 1923, making
her 66, although she has been extremely secretive about her age.
</TEXT>
