<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0653EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Quake     09-14 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Quake,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tremor Shakes Northern Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake shook a wide area of
northern Italy during the night, cracking walls in old buildings and
sending thousands of panicked residents into the streets, officials
reported today.
   At least six people suffered minor injuries from rushing out of
their homes in Trento, near the epicenter in the foothills of the
Dolomite Alps in northeastern Italy, the Civil Defense Ministry in
Rome said.
   Another person was hospitalized with shock, the ministry said.
   It said it could not confirm reports that a woman died of a heart
attack.
   The tremor, which lasted about 15 seconds, was felt from Trieste,
near the Yugoslav border, to Bologna about 240 miles to the west.
   Thousands of people, many in their nightclothes, rushed out of
their homes when the ground shook just before midnight. Many spent
the night in their cars.
   The National Geophysics Institute in Rome said the quake measured
between 6 and 7 on the 12-point Mercalli scale, which gauges the
intensity of an earthquake as felt in a specific location.
   A quake of that magnitude can crack the walls and ceilings of
buildings.
   The epicenter was pinpointed near Rovereto, 16 miles south of
Trento, a quake-prone area in the Adige River valley.
   The jolt damaged some old buildings in Rovereto, Ala and Rival
Del Garda, along the shores of Lake Garda, officials said.
</TEXT>
