<FIRST>u a PM-ShipAground 1stLd-Writethru a0521 09-14 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0521,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grounded Barge Spills Gasoline into East River</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Coast Guard now saying 75,600
gallons spilled; CORRECTS name of company to Morania Oil Tankers sted Marania
Oil Corp. and name of barge to Morania. Picks up 7th graf, `Crawley said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maritime traffic resumed on the East River today
and bridges were reopened after removal of a tank barge that ran
aground and spilled 75,600 gallons of gasoline, the Coast Guard said.
   The barge, carrying a cargo of 96,000 barrels or about 4.03
million gallons of gasoline, ran aground Wednesday night just north
of the Triborough Bridge, said Petty Officer Jeff Crawley.
   Most of the gasoline that spilled was expected to evaporate,
Crawley said.
   The vessel, belonging to the Manhattan-based Morania Oil Tankers,
was towed to a dock, where a second barge arrived early today to
take on the remaining gasoline from a damaged 315,000-gallon tank,
said Crawley.
   Refloating the 300-foot barge took only 15 minutes, said another
Coast Guard spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Paul Mulligan.
   The Triborough Bridge and a railroad bridge that had been closed
to avoid igniting fumes were reopened 6{ hours after the Morania 440
struck bottom about 150 to 200 feet offshore in a rocky channel.
   Crawley said the tugboat East Coast, which was towing the barge,
apparently took a curve too tight or got too close to the bank.
   The barge was en route from Philadelphia to New Haven, Conn.
</TEXT>
