<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0818EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CityOpera     09-14 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-City Opera,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Musicians Strike New York City Opera</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the New York City Opera orchestra
showed up at Lincoln Center in full dress and with their instruments
in tow _ but only to walk a picket line.
   The opera canceled Wednesday's season opener of Rossini's ``The
Barber of Seville'' after the musicians went on strike in a wage
dispute.
   The opera's singers, who are represented by another union, and
other workers are not on strike but generally honored the musicians'
picket lines.
   ``We will not perform while they are on strike,'' said Martin
Oppenheimer, the company's board vice chairman. ``The sad part about
this is ... we will never have the performances that have to be
canceled because of the strike.''
   The opera's season runs through Nov. 19.
   No talks were scheduled.
   The musicians voted 53-4 Tuesday night to strike after talks
failed to resolve disputes over weekly wages and how many weeks per
year the musicians will be guaranteed a paycheck.
   Except for 1986, no contract with the orchestra since 1962 was
achieved without some type of work stoppage.
</TEXT>
