<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0830EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Protest     09-14 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Protest,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mixed-Race Officer Disperses Rally in His Honor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MITCHELL'S PLAIN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mixed-race policeman who
accused white police officers of brutally suppressing an election
protest in his neighborhood peacefully dispersed a demonstration in
his honor today.
   Lt. Gregory Rockman has become a folk hero among township youths
near Cape Town since he accused white officers of beating protesters
and bystanders during an anti-election protest Sept. 5 in his
neigbhorhood, Mitchell's Plain.
   The black majority of 28 million was excluded from the Sept. 6
parliamentary elections for whites, Asians and people of mixed-race.
   Rockman, a policeman for 12 years and a crime prevention officer
in the mixed-race township, says he has kept protests peaceful by
allowing demonstrators a suitable length of time to make their point
before ordering them to disperse. But he said riot squad officers
moved in without warning Sept. 5 and gleefully beat protesters at
the Town Center shopping plaza.
   Hundreds of students gathered at the same center today, carrying
placards in praise of Rockman and criticizing emergency detention of
a dozen high school students in the past month.
   After about an hour Rockman appeared on a balcony above a
furniture shop and asked the students to disperse. ``You have made
your point. I don't want you to get hurt. I will see to it that you
dont get hurt. Please go back to your schools,'' he said.
   His address was interrupted frequently by loud applause and
cheers. Before leaving the balcony Rockman said, ``We are going to
show the world that we can be peaceful, and we want to change
through peaceful means in South Africa.''
   The students walked to the nearby police station where Rockman is
assigned, and held their placards for about an hour, then dispersed.
   Col. John Manuel, commander of the Mitchell's Plain police
station, was with Rockman. ``He has my support,'' Manuel said. ``I
have been fighting this thing internally whereas he has fought it
openly.''
   Rockman told journalists he believed his statements had played a
part in persuading authorities to allow the biggest legal
anti-government march ever on Wednesday. After more than 20,000
people marched through Cape Town with no police interference,
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu praised Rockman.
   Rockman has called for a public inquiry into the behavior of riot
squad police. He said he would write a letter today to
President-elect F.W. de Klerk, since Law and Order Minister Adriaan
Vlok had refused to meet with him.
   The Human Rights Commission also sent a letter to de Klerk today,
praising Rockman's ``courageous stand'' and calling for an
independent commission of inquiry into police conduct.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
