<FIRST>r a PM-ActivistSlain     09-14 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Activist Slain,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Man in Slaying of Anti-Drug Crusader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alleged crack dealer has been arrested in the
slaying of a woman who crusaded against drugs in her Brooklyn
neighborhood, and police said they were investigating whether
higher-ups had put out a contract on her.
   The arrest of William Figueroa, 26, came after police made the
case a top priority and after a crackdown on drug dealers got some
of them to talk, police said.
   Figueroa, also known as Willie Bundles, was charged Wednesday
with murder and reckless endangerment in the slaying Aug. 8 of Maria
Hernandez, a 34-year-old mother of three, said Chief of Detectives
Robert Colangelo.
   Mrs. Hernandez was killed as she dressed for work by shots fired
through her bedroom window. She and her husband, Carlos, had tried
to keep drug dealers off their street, and he had received numerous
death threats.
   After seeing news pictures of Figueroa, Hernandez said he
believed the man was a drug dealer with whom he had argued. However,
police said the only drug charges against Figueroa were brought in
Massachusetts.
   Inspector Richard Mayronne described Figueroa as a low-level
crack dealer and said he also apparently had sold heroin. Police
said they were seeking two other people believed to be with Figueroa
when Mrs. Hernandez was killed.
   ``The investigation is continuing to determine whether there was
a broader conspiracy and whether or not some groups, in effect, put
out a contract,'' Colangelo said.
   Colangelo said that whether those firing the shots intended to
kill Mrs. Hernandez or just frighten the couple, ``the result is the
same, an innocent woman dead, fighting drugs.''
   Colangelo said Figueroa has been living in a van on Brooklyn
streets at least since the shooting and that before then he lived in
Springfield, Mass.
   Colangelo said Figueroa had been arrested twice in 1987 for drug
selling and grand larceny, and once in 1988 on a drug charge, all in
Massachusetts. He was sentenced to six months in jail but never
showed up to serve his time.
</TEXT>
