<FIRST>r i PM-Norway-PlaneCrash     09-14 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Norway-Plane Crash,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvage Vessel Finds Flight Record of Norwegian Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A salvage vessel has found the voice recorder
and wreckage of a plane that crashed into the sea north of Denmark,
killing all 55 people on board, officials said today.
   The Norwegian ship first found the tail section of the
twin-engine Convair CV-580 charter plane, then the voice recorder,
which contains a tape of the crew's conversations, said Jon R. Pran,
head of the investigating commission.
   He said the ship, the Bergen Surveyor, still was searching for
the flight recorder, which contains readings from the plane's
technical equipment.
   Officials hope to learn the cause of the crash by studying the
wreckage, the voice recorder, and the flight recorder, if it is
found.
   Norway's NTB news agency reported the bodies of 22 men and nine
women, pulled from the sea after the crash Friday, have been
identified and were to be shipped from Frederikshavn, Denmark, to
Norway today.
   The other 24 passengers and crew members were believed trapped in
the missing fuselage in the muddy seabed under 230 feet of water.
   ``Finding the tail section was a confirmation that we have traced
the wreckage,'' Pran told NTB. ``The fuselage is broken up in
several parts within an area of'' about one square mile.
   NTB said it took 10 hours to lift the tail section from the
seabed. An unmanned mini-submarine sent from the Bergen Surveyor
made contact with eight or nine other pieces assumed to be plane
wreckage, NTB said.
   Experts say metal fatigue in the aging aircraft probably caused
Scandinavia's worst air disaster. The turboprop plane belonged to
the Norwegian charter company Partnair and was en route from Oslo,
Norway, to Hamburg, West Germany, when it plunged into the North Sea.
   Most passengers were Norwegian employees of a shipping line who
had won a company lottery to attend a ship christening in West
Germany.
   The U.S. manufacturer, General Dynamics, made the CV-580 model in
1960 by adding two turboprop engines to the Convair CV-340.
</TEXT>
