<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-BusTerrorist 1stLd-Writethru   09-14 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Bus Terrorist, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0537,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Admits Killing 16 in Bus Crash, Denies Premeditation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 9th, `Police say...' to ADD that defendant
may have shouted name of his friend during attack. Pickup 10th, `Militant...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian accused of slaying 16 Jews by
forcing a crowded bus into a ravine pleaded guilty to murder today
but innocent to a separate charge that the crime was premeditated.
   The July 6 bus plunge, in which an American and two Canadian
tourists died along with 13 Israelis, was the worst attack on Jews
during the 21-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli
occupation.
   Abdel Hadi Ghanem, 23, from Nusseirat refugee camp in the
occupied Gaza Strip, entered the pleas in Jerusalem District Court.
   Authorities maintain Ghanem acted out of Palestinian nationalism
and rode the bus route repeatedly to find the most dangerous spot to
attack.
   He reportedly told investigators he wanted to avenge the beating
of a friend by soldiers.
   Defense lawyer Jonathan Kuttab brought to court Thursday a
paralyzed Palestinian in a wheelchair, Radwan Abu Shamsah, whose
injury he said motivated Ghanem's attack.
   The court agreed to Kuttab's request for an independent
psychiatrist to examine Ghanem. It postponed the trial for three
months.
   ``We are pleading not guilty as far as the planning and the
intent,'' Kuttab told Israel radio outside the court. ``We are going
to get full evidence later to try and see what in fact motivated him
to do something like this when he was not a politicized person at
all.''
   Police say Ghanem grabbed the steering wheel of a Jerusalem-bound
bus on the main highway from Tel Aviv, forcing it into a deep ravine
as he shouted ``Allahu Akbar!'' a religious call meaning ``God is
great!'' that has become a battle cry of the Palestinian revolt.
   It was reported later that Ghanem may have instead screamed the
name of his friend who was beaten. Kuttab said on Thursday that the
defendant shouted ``Radwan, Radwan'' as he wrenched the steering
wheel from the bus driver.
   Militant Israelis responded to the bus attack by stoning cars
driven by Palestinians. One Palestinian was killed in such an attack
near the Gaza Strip.
