<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1014EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru a0472 09-14 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says She Was Misunderstood on Return of Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with testimony; picks up at pvs 9th graf, Rep.
Hamilton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While some Soviet emigres may one day want to
go back to the Soviet Union, the United States will not turn away
any who have already left their country and wish to come here, a
Bush administration official said today.
   Jewel Lafontant, U.S. coordinator for refugees, said reporters
had ``misunderstood'' her comment at a hearing Wednesday that nearly
5,000 Soviet emigres in Italy and Austria who have been denied entry
to the United States can ``always go to Israel or return to Russia.
In these days of glasnost, that's not an impossible thing.''
   All those stranded in Rome and Vienna will be admitted to the
United States, whether as fully funded refugees or as parolees with
private funding, Lafontant said today as she resumed testimony
before the House subcommittees on Europe and on immigration.
   ``Rest assured, they will not be stranded in Europe or forced to
go elsewhere,'' she said.
   Lafonant's comment Wednesday drew immediate criticism from some
in Congress, who said returning to the Soviet Union could subject
emigres to persecution.
   Her remarks reflect the administration's quandary about how to
reconcile the rising tide of Soviet emigres with shrinking U.S.
budgets. For years, U.S. demands that the Soviets allow free Jewish
emigration were a cornerstone of U.S. foreign policy.
   Several congressional committees are holding hearings this week
on the administration's proposal to admit 50,000 Soviets as refugees
in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. The allocation announced
Wednesday is part of the overall U.S. refugee allotment of 125,000
worldwide.
   More than 17,000 Soviets are waiting in Italy for permission to
enter the United States, and about 4,700 have been denied refugee
status.
   Today, the administration told Congress it is phasing out refugee
processing centers in Rome and Vienna and beefing up the U.S.
Embassy staff in Moscow to deal with the flood of applications.
   Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., the immigration subcommittee
chairman, rejected Lafontant's suggestion Wednesday that Jews might
return to the Soviet Union. He said they are still subject to
persecution in the Soviet Union.
   Rep. Hamilton Fish, R-N.Y., said, ``I don't think this is an
appropriate response to someone who's been languishing outside his
country with the expectation of being allowed to come here. You
can't turn around and send them back.''
   While few seriously expect Soviet emigres to return to the Soviet
Union, Lafontant's proposal reflects an increasingly accepted view
that since the United States cannot take in the flood of applicants,
some should consider going to Israel.
   While most Jewish emigres leave on Israeli visas, they opt for
the United States once they reach Vienna or Rome for economic and
cultural reasons.
   Soviet citizens, most of them Jews, are applying to leave their
country for the United States at a rate of about 4,000 a month. This
has created a backlog of about 35,000 applicants in Moscow, and
another 17,000 or more in Italy and Austria.
   If the trend continues, Jewish groups expect at least 72,000
applicants next year and possibly more than 100,000. The
administration knows its proposed slots are insufficient.
   ``With no sign of decline in applications from Soviet citizens
seeking admission to the U.S., we judge that 50,000 is, if anything,
a conservative estimate of the potential admission requirements,''
said Princeton Lyman, the State Department's director of the Office
of Refugee Programs.
   He pledged that top priority would be given those Soviets who
have already applied.
   Jewish groups say this means most of the 50,000 slots will be
taken up with people who have already applied and that new
applicants will mostly have to wait.
   Under the proposed system that will conduct all processing in
Moscow, applicants will have to wait in the Soviet Union, rather
than in Rome or Vienna, at a time when anti-Semitism is rising,
Jewish groups say.
   This raises great concern for the applicants' safety, said Arnold
Leibowitz of the Hebrew Immigrants Aid Society. ``People will be
reluctant to come forward and apply, tell you their tales of
persecution and then wait around for years _ glasnost or not,'' said
the Washington counsel for the organization that helps resettle
Soviet Jews.
   Other Jewish activists worry that at the current rate of denial
for refugee status, which stands at between 20 and 56 percent, many
Soviet Jews will be afraid to apply.
   The denials stem from a change in policy which no longer
automatically grants refugee status to Soviets on the assumption
that they suffer from persecution as a group. Under the new
directive, each applicant must prove a well-founded fear of
persecution.
</TEXT>
