<FIRST>u i PM-China-Dismissal 2ndLd-Writethru a0497 09-14 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dismissal, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0497,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hainan Governor Fired on Graft Charges; Journalist Reported Under
Arrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with successor announced, CORRECTS
age, new restrictions placed on students. Pickup 7th pvs, `China's State...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese authorities have fired the reformist
governor of Hainan province on graft charges, insisting the move was
part of a campaign against corruption and not politically motivated.
   Also today, an official Chinese newspaper reported that most new
humanities graduate students will have to take a year off to work in
factories or rural areas to improve their ``political
understanding.''
   Hainan Gov. Liang Xiang, who has been linked to purged Communist
Party chief Zhao Ziyang, is the highest-ranking official to be
dismissed in what Beijing calls its campaign to root out corruption
from the leadership.
   His dismissal was announced at a Hainan congress meeting
Wednesday and reported by the official China News Service, which
appeared in Hong Kong today. China's nationally televised evening
news today reported Liu Jianfeng, formerly the provincial deputy
party secretary, was elected as Liang's successor.
   Liang, 70, also was stripped of all Communist Party posts and his
case remains under investigation, the report said.
   Meanwhile, the Hong Kong independent Ming Pao newspaper reported
the arrest in Shanghai of Wang Ruowang, one of China's most
prominent investigative writers who reportedly was active in the
spring pro-democracy movement that the government crushed. An
official with the Shanghai Public Security Bureau, reached by
telephone from Hong Kong, said he had no comment.
   The China Youth News daily said first-year graduate students will
be sent to work in ``grass-roots units'' for ``training.'' The
announcement by the State Education Commission applies to students
studying philosophy, economics, history, law, education and
literature.
   It was the latest effort by the government to increase student
exposure to work programs and political education following the
crackdown in Beijing.
   China's State Council accused Liang of allowing his wife and
children to amass personal wealth and of abusing his power by having
his son settle in Hong Kong, the prosperous British colony on the
south China coast, according to the official account.
   The pro-Beijing Wen Wei Po newspaper of Hong Kong today quoted
the governor's son, Liang Ming, as saying Beijing approved his
coming to Hong Kong and that neither he nor his mother had gone to
Hainan to do business.
   Liang Xiang was appointed governor of the southern island of
Hainan last year after it was elevated to provincial status and made
a special economic zone to attract foreign investment.
   Zhao was a major supporter of the rapid development of Hainan and
is believed to have been instrumental in having Liang appointed the
island's leader.
   Liang also reportedly supported a tolerant stance toward the
island's students participating in the pro-democracy movement, which
the central government accused Zhao of backing.
   Hainan Communist Party Chief Xu Shijie was quoted as telling the
provincial congress Wednesday that Liang's firing was a personal
matter. ``It was not related to factional struggle, and it was not
related to the fall of Zhao Ziyang,'' the China News Service said in
a report on Xu's remarks.
   But a foreign diplomat based in Hong Kong, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, said he thought politics was involved in the firing,
noting that Liang ``has been linked in the past to Zhao Ziyang.''
   The diplomat said the dismissal probably indicated an intent by
the central government to reassert some control over the nation's
southern coastal provinces, which have enjoyed much autonomy while
leading China's economic reform and modernization drive.
   The diplomat said it was unclear how many more dismissals might
follow in the region.
   Liang Xiang was vice mayor and party boss in Canton, then vice
governor of Guangdong province before becoming the head of Shenzhen
in March 1981. He took up his post in Hainan after temporarily
retiring in 1986.
   Wang Ruowang, 71, the Shanghai writer reported under arrest, is
one of modern China's most famed and prolific commentators, noted
for his attacks on the abuses of the party system.
   Ming Pao said Wang only recently was detained but that since the
June 4 military crackdown on the pro-democracy movement, police had
been stationed in front of his house and his telephone bugged.
   Wang had participated in movement demonstrations and complained
to senior leader Deng Xiaoping, the newspaper said.
   He was expelled from the Communist Party in 1987 during the
campaign against anti-bourgeois liberalization, or liberal Western
influences.
</TEXT>
