<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Palme-Appeal     09-14 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme-Appeal,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Killer Appeals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug addict convicted of killing Prime
Minister Olof Palme told an appeals court today that he wept when he
read of Palme's death and denied he shot the popular Swedish leader.
   ``Nothing of what will be said here can make me into Olof Palme's
killer,'' said Christer Pettersson. ``It can only make me a suspect
for the killing, but never into the killer,'' he said during two
hours of questioning.
   The 42-year-old Swede with a long criminal record was convicted
by a lower court on July 27 of slaying the four-term premier in 1986
as he walked home from a movie with his wife, Lisbeth.
   Pettersson appealed the conviction and life sentence imposed by
the district court. The prosecution made a counter-appeal, seeking
to upgrade a second charge from endangering Mrs. Palme to attempted
murder.
   Pettersson said he learned of Palme's death from a newspaper the
day after the Feb. 28 killing.
   ``I get the paper. I see a picture of Olof Palme and read the
headline, `Olof Palme Killed.' I think `my God,' and go into the
kitchen and sit down. I am so sad that I shed a tear _ no, I shed
several tears,'' he told the court.
   ``I really liked and admired that man. I always have done,'' he
said, adding that he voted for Palme's Social Democrats every time
but once.
   Pettersson, who has a previous manslaughter conviction and has
undergone court-ordered psychiatric treatment, said he did not hate
Palme or anyone else. ``Hate blinds you. I have a short temper, but
I have never felt hatred,'' he said.
   Prosecutors have suggested Pettersson loathes authority and
offered this alleged hatred as a motive for the killing.
   The convicted man admitted he threatened or assaulted drug
dealers about 600 times to steal amphetamines during a six-year
period in the 1970s when he was not in jail or a psychiatric
institution.
   But he said he never used a gun, never attacked anyone from the
back, and was violent ``only in acute situations.''
   Repeating his alibi, Pettersson said he came into Stockholm from
his suburban home to get amphetamines and went to a gambling club
before catching a 10:46 p.m. commuter train home. He fell asleep and
missed his station, but still returned to his apartment by midnight,
he said. Palme was shot at 11:21 p.m.
   During the lower-court trial, Mrs. Palme identified Pettersson as
the man she saw standing a few feet away immediately after the
shooting, when her husband fell to the ground fatally wounded by a
shot in the back. She saw no gun, and the murder weapon never was
found.
   The six laymen on the eight-member jury voted Pettersson guilty
on the basis of Mrs. Palme's testimony. Two professional judges on
the jury voted for acquittal, citing lack of forensic evidence.
   The Svea Court of Appeals, consisting of four judges and three
laymen, is expected to conclude Pettersson's case on Oct. 9.
</TEXT>
