<FIRST>r w PM-Nunn 1stLd-Writethru a0552 09-14 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nunn, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says Success of Arms Talks At Stake In Defense Bill Negotiations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, The House, to CORRECT to `all $100 million' sted
`all but $100 million'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The success of strategic arms reduction talks
with the Soviet Union will hang in the balance during the next month
as congressional conferees draw up military spending plans for next
year, the chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee said today.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said the vast differences between the House
and Senate over U.S. strategic programs must be negotiated into a
consensus if the strategic arms reduction talks (START) are to
succeed.
   ``I think the START talks are at stake in the next 30 days,''
Nunn said in a breakfast speech at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
   ``If we do not come out with a sensible strategic nuclear program
that the president himself has confidence in and the Joint Chiefs
(of Staff) have confidence in, START talks are going to be a long,
long time coming,'' he said.
   The House cut $502 million from the $1.1 billion President Bush
had sought for the rail-based MX nuclear missile system and
eliminated all $100 million the president had sought for the
Midgetman nuclear missile program.
   The Senate endorsed Bush's request in both missile programs, and
Nunn argued today that Congress must give Bush ``the tools to do the
job'' in the arms negotiations in Geneva.
   ``If we are going to have any kind of successful outcome in arms
control ... we've got to have consensus at home,'' Nunn said. ``If
we don't develop consensus at home, we're not going to be able to
develop one with the Soviets.''
   In a separate area, Nunn said the United States should provide
whatever military assistance is requested by the government of
Colombia in its war against drug cartels.
   ``My view is the government of Colombia is not going ask the U.S.
to come in and fight all their battles with military forces,'' he
said. ``They have a very large military force ....''
   ``I think they can handle it if we give them help, equipment,
assistance and training,'' he said. ``I would view us primarily in
that role. If they want further help, then we should consider it
very carefully.''
   For the long-term, Nunn said he favors Jamaican Prime Minister
Michael Manley's proposal for the creation of an inter-American drug
squad ``where the U.S. would participate but not be the only
participant.''
</TEXT>
