<FIRST>r i PM-Rushdie-Bombing 1stLdWritethru a0491 09-14 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie-Bombing, 1st Ld Writethru, a0491,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Outside Rushdie Publisher's Bookstore, Three Other
Bombs Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with arrests in Holland related
to Rushdie. Pickup 12th, ``Moslem militants...'' TRIMS to tighten.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small bomb shattered the window of a York
bookstore owned by the publisher of Salman Rushdie's novel ``The
Satanic Verses,'' and bombs were found at three of the publisher's
stores in other towns, police say.
   The Viking Penguin bookstore in the center of this northern city
was closed Wednesday night when the blast occurred, causing minor
damage and no injuries, police said.
   In Holland, four teen-age students were arrested for threatening
to bomb stores belonging to a retail chain if it did not stop
stocking the controversial novel, which many Moslems consider
blasphemous.
   York city police Inspector Ron Johnson said the bomb at the
Penguin bookstore was spotted by a member of the public and the area
was evacuated. He said it exploded before an army bomb squad could
arrive.
   Three other bombs found outside Penguin bookstores in three other
cities and towns were defused or otherwise made safe before they
could explode.
   No group claimed responsibility for planting the bombs in York,
in Guildford 30 miles southwest of London, in Nottingham in central
England and in Peterborough 75 miles north of London.
   But the British Broadcasting Corp. said in a radio news bulletin
that it seemed likely the bombs were the latest in a series of
attacks by Moslem extremists angered by Rushdie's novel.
   The BBC reported that the bomb found in Nottingham, made from a
length of metal pipe filled with explosives, seemed almost identical
to one that exploded outside a store in central London earlier this
month.
   In Amsterdam, Dutch police today reported the arrest of four
schoolboys for threatening to attack a prominent department store
chain unless it removed ``The Satanic Verses'' from its shelves.
   The four, aged 17 and 18, confessed to mailing an Aug. 31 letter
threatening the Vroom and Dreesman chain, the retail branch of the
Dutch trade and retail conglomerate Vendex International, according
to Amsterdam police spokesman Klaas Wilting.
   In response to the threat, Vroom and Dreesman withdrew Dutch and
English versions of the novel from its 60 department stores around
the nation.
   The four schoolboys called themselves ``Followers of the
Revolutionary Justice Organization,'' Wilting said.
   ``It all began as kind of hoax ... but they never realized this
could be the effect,'' he said.
   The four, who were not identified in line with Dutch police
practice, were charged with threatening the use of force, he said.
   Rushdie has been in hiding since Feb. 14, when Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, Iran's former spiritual leader, called on Moslems to kill
him, and Moslem clerics placed a multimillion dollar bounty on the
author's head.
   Rushdie is an Indian-born naturalized British citizen based in
London.
</TEXT>
