<FIRST>d a PM-Heroes     09-14 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heroes,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foundation Recognizes 16 Heroes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Carnegie Hero Fund Commission today
recognized 16 Americans and Canadians as heroes.
   The winners, who receive $2,500 cash and a medal, were recognized
for risking their lives to save, or attempt to save, the lives of
others.
   The commission has recognized 73 heroes this year and 7,367 since
it was founded in 1904 by industrialist Andrew Carnegie to honor
civilian heroism in the United States in Canada.
   The commission identified its latest heroes as:
   _Bryan E. Kratochvill, 24, of Lincoln, Neb.
   _Dominic Possamai, 22, of Montreal.
   _Charles O. Stickles, 36, of Cornwall-on-Hudson, N.Y.
   _Junior David Phillips, 48, of Pamplin, Va.
   _Donald G. Tolbert, 26, of Cedartown, Ga.
   _Sylvester O. McHolmes, 34, of Atlanta.
   _Gisele Gagnon, 20, of Dummondville, Quebec.
   _Katherine Finkbeiner, 38, of Greenwood, S.C.
   _Anthony Figurski, 29, of Sun City, Calif.
   _Jackson E. Stallcup, 36, of San Fernando, Calif.
   _Murl Jay Sines, 23, of St. Maries, Idaho.
   _William B. Shelander II, 20, of Washington, Ill.
   _Eddie A. Turner, 33, of Catawba, N.C.
   _Deborah J. Shelly, 35, of Chattanooga, Tenn.
   _Despina Buhagiar, 56, of St. Catharines, Ontario.
   _J. Gordon Stevens, 26, of Peace River, Alberta.
</TEXT>
