<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1144EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Colombian-Extradition 1stLd-Writethru a0ngoCountyjurydeliberatedjustongExtraditionofConvictedDrugTrafficker
09-14 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombian-Extradition, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0568,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Seeking Extradition of Convicted Drug Trafficker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with additional details on association with
Medellin cartel, additional details on sentence, provisional arrest request.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Pelaez Roldan was indicted. ^By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department announced today it is
seeking the extradition from Colombia of Bernardo Pelaez Roldan, an
alleged associate of the Medellin drug cartel convicted of drug
trafficking charges five years ago in Detroit.
   ``We are seeking his extradition,'' said Justice spokesman David
Runkel. ``The papers have gone down'' to Colombia.
   Pelaez Roldan, identified as an associate of the Medellin cartel
that is one of the world's largest cocaine trafficking
organizations, faces a 15-year sentence in the Detroit case, said
Frank Shults of the Drug Enforcement Administration.
   In addition to the extradition papers, the United States also has
sent to Colombia a request for Pelaez Roldan's provisional arrest,
which would allow the Colombian government to keep him in custody
until the extradition proceedings are completed, Shults said.
   Pelaez Roldan was indicted in November 1983 on federal charges of
conspiracy to possess with intent to distribute cocaine, Runkel
said. He was arrested in Florida and taken before a U.S. magistrate
in Detroit in January 1984, and the trial was set to begin that
March.
   He was released on bond and ``never seen again,'' said Runkel,
who added that he did not know how much the bond was.
   Tried in absentia, Pelaez Roldan was convicted in April 1984 and
sentenced to 15 years in prison, Shults said. A warrant for his
arrest was issued in May 1984, Runkel said.
   The United States sought his extradition from Colombia, and the
government there granted that request in March 1986. However, Pelaez
Roldan was not in custody, and the Colombian Supreme Court threw out
the extradition treaty in 1987.
   Under emergency measures imposed by Colombian President Virgilio
Barco following the Aug. 18 assassination of leading presidential
candidate Luis Carlos Galan, extraditions to the United States were
resumed.
   The only person sent to the United States under the newly
reinstituted agreement is Eduardo Martinez Romero, who faces
money-laundering and drug-trafficking charges in Atlanta.
   The Washington Post reported today that Colombian Gen. Miguel
Maza Marquez, director of the Administrative Security Department,
described Pelaez Roldan as ``the most important person yet taken
into custody.'' A DAS spokesman for the Administrative Security
Department said he was ``one of the biggest money launderers in
Colombia, much bigger that Martinez Romero,'' and the general
agreed, the Post said.
   However, Pelaez Roldan faces no money-laundering charges in the
United States, Runkel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
