<FIRST>u a PM-WVaPlea 1stLd-Writethru a0550 09-14 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WVa Plea, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0550,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former W.Va. Senate President Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with sentencing date, no-comment
from Tonkovich, to move up reference to previous resignations, and to CORRECT
in 6th graf pvs reason that Tonkovich said he gave money back. Picks up
7th graf pvs, `One of...'. DELETES penultimate graf pvs, now redundant.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former state Senate President Dan
Tonkovich pleaded guilty today to taking a $5,000 payoff from a
casino company to help get a bill legalizing gambling passed.
   The surprise plea was announced by U.S. Attorney Michael Carey on
the sixth day of Tonkovich's trial.
   Since July, West Virginia's treasurer, attorney general, a former
Senate majority leader and Tonkovich's successor as Senate president
have also either resigned, pleaded guilty or agreed to plead guilty
in various investigations.
   The 16-year legislator had been charged with three counts of
extortion, two of attempted extortion and one of racketeering.
   He pleaded guilty to one count of extortion carrying up to 20
years in prison and $250,000 in fines. A conviction on all counts
could have brought the Democrat from Benwood 120 years in prison and
$1.5 million in fines.
   Sentencing was set for Nov. 16.
   A teary-eyed Tonkovich walked out of the courtroom with his wife
after the announcement and declined to comment.
   Tonkovich was indicted on three counts of extorting $5,000 each
from the West Virginia Casino Co. to help win passage of a bill that
would have allowed casino gambling in West Virginia. It never passed.
   After he was indicted, Tonkovich admitted he took the money but
said he thought it was for polling work to be done his public
relations firm.
   He said he eventually returned the money because the casino
company never followed up on its original request for polling work
and because of editorial criticism about his business dealings.
   One of the attempted extortion counts alleged that Tonkovich
tried to sell his influence on the gambling bill to Resorts
International Inc. in 1986. The other attempted extortion count
charged that Tonkovich promised to fix insurance-industry
legislation in 1988 in return for political donations.
   The racketeering count alleged that Tonkovich used his office as
a criminal enterprise by selling his influence.
   Tonkovich was elected to the House in 1972 and the Senate in
1976, serving as Senate president from 1984 to 1988. He did not seek
re-election in 1988 to seek the Democratic nomination for governor.
He lost to now-Gov. Gaston Caperton.
   Three people testified against Tonkovich after pleading guilty to
tax charges: former administrative assistant Robert Cain, former
Senate Majority Leader Si Boettner, and insurance lobbyist Bonnie
Wymer.
   Former state Senate President Larry Tucker was the lead defense
witness. He resigned Sept. 8 after agreeing to plead guilty to
extortion.
   In July, state Treasurer A. James Manchin resigned over $270
million in investment losses, averting a Senate impeachment trial.
Attorney General Charlie Brown quit Aug. 21, averting a federal
grand jury investigation of campaign finances and allegations he
lied during a child custody hearing.
</TEXT>
