<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru   09-14 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0530,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virgin Islands Woman Says She Saw D.C. Mayor With Cocaine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Ms. Hedrington testifying
before grand jury. Picks up 4th graf pvs `Barry has ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legal secretary who reportedly told FBI
agents she saw District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry in a U.S.
Virgin Islands hotel room with what she believed was a large
quantity of cocaine testified today before a federal grand jury.
   Dixie Lee Hedrington was before the grand jury for about an hour
before the panel recessed for lunch. Prosecutors and witnesses
refused to discuss the proceedings.
   The grand jury is investigating contentions by a convicted drug
offender that he smoked crack cocaine with Barry, an allegation
Barry denies.
   The Washington Post, citing unamed sources, reported in today's
editions that Ms. Hedrington told the FBI that someone offered her
cocaine in the St. Thomas hotel room where she saw Barry in March
1988, but she declined.
   Barry has consistently denied using illegal drugs and has accused
the newspaper of being out to get him. He also said he did not
recognize Ms. Hedrington's name.
   ``This is part of a continuing witch hunt by The Washington Post,
an attempt to frame me, an attempt to run me out of office,'' Barry
told the newspaper after being asked about Ms. Hedrington. ``The
Post intends to run a story a day of unsubstantiated charges.''
   Ms. Hedrington and her attorney, former Virgin Islands Lt. Gov.
Julio Brady, were met by FBI agents Wednesday at Washington National
Airport and whisked away, the Post said.
   Ms. Hedrington is one of several women named by Charles Lewis, a
former Virgin Islands government official, as potential witnesses
against the mayor, the sources told the newspaper.
   Lewis, a onetime friend of Barry's, has been convicted on drug
charges in the Virgin Islands and is awaiting trial in Washington on
perjury and cocaine charges.
   Lewis has told federal authorities that he and Barry smoked crack
in a Washington hotel and that they used cocaine in the Virgin
Islands, several news media have reported. Lewis' trial, scheduled
to start Sept. 18, was postponed indefinitely last week, after a
prosecutor told a judge there may be ``another disposition'' to the
case.
</TEXT>
