<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Poland     09-14 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Poland,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans in Warsaw Embassy Hoping to Go West</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR50</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germans hoping to emigrate West have
taken refuge in the West German Embassy in Warsaw, the Foreign
Ministry said Thursday. It said the government hopes to resolve the
problem ``in a few days.''
   The East Germans are following the course of thousands of their
countrymen who crowded the West German Embassy in Hungary. They were
allowed to go West after the reformist government of Hungary opened
its border.
   Polish television reported Wednesday night that there were about
50 East Germans in the Warsaw embassy. They reportedly began
arriving several weeks ago.
   Ministry spokesman Stefan Staniszewski confirmed Thursday that
East Germans were in the embassy but said he did not know how many
were there.
   One 9-year-old boy interviewed on television said there were
about 60 people housed inside a large room. Laundry could be seen
hanging in the embassy yard, and the youngster said a hotel was
providing food for the East Germans.
   Several young men lounged and read in the embassy courtyard. One
raised his fingers in a ``V'' for victory sign.
   The 9-year-old said he traveled to Warsaw with his 13-year-old
brother and their parents about 10 days ago from Goerlitz, an East
German city near the Polish border.
   The other refugees mainly come from Goerlitz, Dresden and East
Berlin, the boy said before he was called away by his father.
   ``Soon we are going to deal with this matter and we will try to
solve it, probably in a few days,'' Staniszewski said in a report
carried by the official PAP news agency.
   The pro-Solidarity daily Gazeta Wyborcza said that because Poland
is a much bigger country and is in a more difficult geopolitical
situation than Hungary, it should be cautious.
   ``Hungary's attitude may evoke sympathy, but as a state we should
not follow their example or even praise them loudly,'' the
commentary said.
   Poland is bordered by Communist East Germany, Czechoslovakia and
the Soviet Union, while Hungary shares a border with non-Communist
Austria.
   Both Hungary and Poland are at the forefront of reforms in the
East bloc. Poland this week approved the East bloc's first
government not led by Communists.
   Falko Schreiber, press spokesman for the East German Embassy in
Warsaw, said the embassy had not been authorized to hold talks with
West German diplomats. The West German Embassy in Warsaw refused
comment on the situation.
   PAP reported that talks between top representatives of the Polish
and West German government opened in Warsaw on Thursday. It did not
say if the refugee situation was raised.
   In addition to Warsaw and Budapest, East Germans also holed up in
the West German Embassy in Prague, Czechoslovakia, hoping to go
West. About 250 agreed to return home after promises they would not
be punished, but 150 reportedly remain in the embassy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
