<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru   09-14 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0579,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijan Rail Strike Paralyzing Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf, ``Cutting supplies...'' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with more from Pravda on the rail strike. Pickup 7th, ``The dispute...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by Azerbaijani railroad workers to press
nationalist demands has cut fuel supplies into the neighboring
Soviet republic of Armenia and left ambulances, trucks and cars
without gas, Pravda said today.
   ``Because of the halt on the Azerbaijan railroad, Armenia is
practically in a state of economic blockade,'' Armenian Deputy
Premier Y. Khodzhamiryan told the Communist Party daily.
   The official said Armenia gets 87 percent of its freight,
including fuel supplies, from Azerbaijan.
   Since February, the two southern republics have been locked in a
bitter dispute about control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region. The
mountainous territory is part of Azerbaijan, but its predominantly
Armenian population and the Armenian republic demand that it be
transferred to Armenian control.
   The Azerbaijani People's Front political movement called a
general strike last week, demanding Azerbaijan reassert control over
Nagorno-Karabakh. Moscow moved in to directly administer the enclave
after ethnic violence flared.
   Cutting supplies to Armenia was not one of the stated aims of the
general strike, which was called off on Monday.
   Pravda did not make it clear whether some Azerbaijani rail
workers who took part in the general strike were still on a walkout,
or whether the current rail paralysis was caused by an earlier
strike. The newspaper said that on Sunday, 250 trains had been
abandoned on lines leading to Yerevan, Armenia's capital.
   The dispute between Armenian and Azerbaijan has killed about 100
people in the past 18 months and caused hundreds of thousands of
people to flee their homes in Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   Official Soviet newspapers have said the situation remains tense.
   Pravda said the 19-mile road from the Armenian city of Goris to
the boundary of Nagorno-Karabakh is so dangerous that it is
``impossible to pass even with a military escort.''
   The national youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda reported on
Wednesday that there were few cars on even the main streets of
Yerevan, the Armenian capital, and there were long delays in public
transportion service.
   Pravda said gas stations did not have enough fuel to fill the
tanks of even ambulances.
   The lack of fuel and supplies was particularly threatening in
northern Armenia where workers are trying to reconstruct cities
devastated by the earthquake Dec. 7 that killed 25,000 people.
   ``The coming winter is putting people under the real threat of
being without shelter,'' Pravda said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
