<HEAD>Israelis, Palestinians Differ on Egyptian Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT that army, sted suspect, opened
fire. Pickup 3rd pvs, ``The victim...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharp differences emerged today among
Palestinians and Israelis over the plan Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak put forward to end the uprising in the occupied territories.
   Soldiers shot and killed a 28-year-old Palestinian while trying
to arrest him on charges of being an activist in the uprising, the
army said. It said soldiers fired after the suspect ignored orders
to halt in the Gaza Strip.
   The victim, Mohammed Arafat Al-Akra, died of a bullet wound to
the head, Arab reporters said. They said he had been jailed three
times without charges during the uprising.
   Seventeen other Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes
with soldiers elsewhere in the occupied lands, Arab hospital
officials said.
   The army confirmed two injuries in Nablus, saying stoning attacks
occurred there after a 12-day curfew was lifted. The army denied an
Arab report that an 18-year-old Palestinian was wounded by a soldier
shooting from a helicopter.
   Al-Akra's death raised to 568 the number of Palestinians killed
in clashes with soldiers and Israeli civilians in the 21-month-old
uprising. Another 114 Palestinians were slain by fellow Arabs as
alleged collaborators with Israel. Forty Israelis also have been
killed.
   An Israeli soldier, Corporal Yosef Haba, 20, died of
electrocution Wednesday while he was on a rooftop in Gaza and the
aerial on his military radio touched a high-tension wire, the army
said.
   The Islamic fundamentalist movement Hamas, or Zeal, distributed a
leaflet rejecting the peace proposal by Mubarak, who has been trying
to persuade PLO chairman Yasser Arafat to accept the plan.
   Hamas, which has organized the uprising along with PLO-backed
leaders, warned residents of the territories about ``Arab regimes
who are acting with the backing of the United States.''
   U.S. officials have said that Mubarak's plan could be an avenue
to revive Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's stalled proposal for
holding elections in the West Bank and Gaza Strip as a first step
toward peace talks.
   Shamir's plan calls for electing Palestinians from the West Bank
and Gaza Strip to negotiate an interim peace plan with Israel. The
final status of the occupied territories would be decided in later
talks.
   Mubarak's plan calls for allowing the Arabs in Jerusalem to vote
and for conducting talks on the basis of trading occupied land for
peace, two controversial issues not included in the Shamir plan
approved by the joint Likud-Labor Cabinet.
   Two leading members of the prime minister's right-wing Likud bloc
criticized Shamir and other top leaders for meeting to discuss
Mubarak's 10-point peace proposal on Wednesday.
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon, on a visit to the United States,
told Israel radio that Israel should reject without discussion any
effort to alter Shamir's election plan.
   ``There is no other plan, and there is no need for another
plan,'' Sharon said. ``It is inconceivable that the government of
Israel will be pushed from time to time in directions it does not
intend to go.''
   David Levy, the housing minister, also was quoted in the
Jerusalem Post as complaining that the meeting was held despite
Shamir's statement that he opposed even talking about Mubarak's plan.
   ``This shows that what we say doesn't hold for even one day,''
Levy told the English-language Post.
</TEXT>
