<FIRST>r w AM-UrbanYouth     09-14 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Urban Youth,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Corps Program Being Developed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Youngsters in 15 cities will have a chance to
participate in a $65 million job-skills project, officials of two
non-profit groups said Thursday.
   The Urban Corps Expansion Project will ``provide young adults
with paying jobs that will give them work, academic skills and a
chance to demonstrate that they can be socially responsible,'' said
Michael Bailin, president of Philadelphia-based Public-Private
Ventures.
   Also involved in the project is the National Association of
Service and Conservation Corps, based here.
   The effort will combine $10 million in private funds with $55
million from local and state governments and community groups,
Bailin said.
   ``Many urban areas have more work to do than the budget can bear
and too many unproductive and underskilled young people,'' he said.
   The proposal calls for employing 200 youths a year in each of 15
cities, which will be chosen from 23 communities that will receive
$10,000 planning grants.
   The communities are: Denver; Bridgeport and New Haven, Conn;
Miami and Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Savannah, Ga.; Chicago; Detroit and
Flint, Mich.; St. Paul, Minn.; St. Louis and Kansas City, Mo.;
Durham and Winston-Salem, N.C.; Albany and Rochester, N.Y.; Eugene
and Portland, Ore.; Charleston, S.C.; Dallas and El Paso, Texas;
Spokane, Wash.; and Milwaukee.
</TEXT>
