<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--PipeExplodes     09-14 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pipe Explodes,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pipe Explodes in Philly; None Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A steampipe explosion Thursday sprayed dirt
and gravel on more than 100 parked cars and a restaurant, officials
said.
   A 12-inch split in the pipe, buried about 8 feet underground at a
construction site, caused escaping steam to blew out gravel and
dirt, said Steve Smith, vice president and general manager of
Philadelphia Thermal Energy Corp., which placed the pipe.
   No one was injured in the 4 a.m. incident.
   Several cars had smashed windows. Most were covered with dust and
mud. Rocks and dirt punched holes in the third- and first-floor
roofs of Westy's Tavern and Restaurant located across from the site.
   Crews worked through the morning to replace the pipe, which the
company plans to test to find out what caused the split, Smith said.
   Company officials already have contacted most of the car owners,
Smith said.
   ``Most of it was confined to windows and cars parked adjacent to
the site. We'll be paying for a lot of car washes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
