<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0567 09-14 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0567,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Contacts, No Dialogue with Sandinistas Seen by US Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with Nicaraguan comment after 4th graf, The
officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unannounced high-level contact between U.S.
and Nicaraguan officials last weekend is not a prelude to a
resumption of direct dialogue between the two countries, according
to State Department officials.
   The weekend meeting in Managua _ the first such contact between
the two countries in almost five years _ involved President Daniel
Ortega and a U.S. delegation consisting of members of Congress and
Assistant Secretary of State Janet Mullins. The American delegation
stopped in Managua as part of a tour of Central America.
   Officials of the Nicaraguan Contras expressed disappointment over
the meeting, but State Department officials said Wednesday night
that no diplomatic signal to the Sandinistas was intended.
   The officials, insisting on anonymity, said the administration
believes the Sandinista government should work out its differences
with the Nicaraguan opposition, including the Contras, without
direct U.S. participation.
   In Managua today, Nicaraguan Foreign Ministry spokesman David
Silva confirmed the weekend but said he had no details.
   Asked if he could ask for more information from higher officials
at the Foreign Ministry, Silva declined, saying: ``It looks like
they want to conduct this with some caution.''
   The Reagan administration carried on a six-month dialogue with
the Sandinista government that ended in January 1985 when U.S.
officials accused Nicaragua of negotiating in bad faith. High-level
contacts with Nicaragua were barred afterward but that policy
apparently did not carry over into the Bush administration.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Wednesday
there have been no guidelines on official discussions with
Sandinista authorities. Even so, there were no high-level contacts
until the Sunday meeting in Managua.
   In addition, the State Department's top official for Latin
America, Bernard Aronson, rebuffed a Nicaraguan vice minister's
efforts several weeks ago to engage in a substantive discussion at a
social gathering, according to U.S. officials.
   During the meeting with Ortega, Ms. Mullins reaffirmed the U.S.
view that the electoral process now beginning in Nicaragua should be
monitored by observers of many countries including the United
States, Ms. Tutwiler said. Ms. Mullins heads the State Department
office of congressional relations.
   National elections are scheduled to be held in Nicaragua on Feb.
25. The Bush administration and other governments have been pressing
the Sandinistas to allow opposition forces a fair chance to win the
balloting.
   At the White House today, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration was ``still examining the possibilities with
Congress'' of whether to channel money to the campaign of opposition
presidential candidate Violeta Chamorro through an independent U.S.
foundation.
   Officials have suggested helping Mrs. Chamorro through the
National Endowment For Democracy, which receives most of its funding
from congressional grants to support democratic efforts around the
world.
   Asked if such intervention, which could also include the
foundation's more typical activities such as voter registration
might be used by Ortega as proof of U.S. meddling in internal
matters, Fitzwater said, ``That's always a concern.''
   But he also praised Mrs. Chamorro, saying she has ``been a leader
in the struggle for democracy for many years ... I think she's a
very good candidate for the opposition.''
   A spokesman for the Nicaraguan resistance, Bosco Matamoros, said
the rebel movement was not consulted in advance about the weekend
meeting in Managua.
   He also complained that the Bush administration has refused to
have contact with representatives of the Contra political
leadership. No replies have been received to Contra letters sent to
Aronson and to Secretary of State James A. Baker III, he said.
   Meanwhile, Paul Reichler, a Washington-based lawyer who
represents the Sandinistas, saw the weekend meeting as a positive
step and expressed hope that it will lead to a normalization of
relations.
   Ms. Tutwiler said the meeting with Ortega was not scheduled until
Ms. Mullins and the congressional delegation arrived in Nicaragua.
Ms. Tutwiler was uncertain whether Ms. Mullins had sought prior
approval from Washington before agreeing to take part in the meeting.
   In another development Wednesday, the Nicaraguan Embassy said it
had denied the application of the privately funded Commission on
Free and Fair Elections in Nicaragua for visas for a delegation to
monitor preparations for the February national elections.
   ``Our elections are not something to be manipulated by
individuals and groups interested in furthering conflict,'' said
charge d'affairs Leonor Arguella de Huper.
   The Nicaraguan electoral process was the subject of meetings
Tuesday among Baker and senators and House members.
   Among other subjects, Baker stressed the importance of U.S.
financial assistance to ensure Nicaragua's democratic process is
free and fair, Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Congress has the option of suspending the assistance at the end
of November. The Central American presidents have called for the
voluntary demobilization of the Contras by Dec. 5.
</TEXT>
