<SECOND>PM-Lotto Fever,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Tickets Hold the Key to $55 Million Jackpot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of friends who pooled their money to buy
at least 200 lottery chances today claimed to have one of the nine
winning tickets to a $55 million jackpot, the second-largest in
California history.
   Each ticket with the six winning numbers in Wednesday's drawing
is worth more than $6.1 million.
   Jackie Wagner of San Diego said she and 19 friends chipped in $10
each for a block of the $1 tickets, with the numbers selected at
random by the lottery computer. She said she couldn't believe her
eyes when she checked the numbers drawn against the tickets.
   ``I was hyperventilating,'' Ms. Wagner told Los Angeles radio
station KNX-AM. ``I said, `Oh my God, I don't believe this.'''
   ``We're celebrating and having champagne and all kinds of good
stuff,'' she said. ``We're just so excited.''
   The chances of picking the six winning numbers were 1 in nearly
14 million. The jackpot sparked a frenzy of ticket-buying, with more
than $66 million sold since Saturday.
   The biggest jackpot in California is the $61.9 million won by
three ticketholders in October 1988.
