<FIRST>r a AM-Metro-NorthConduct     09-14 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Metro-North Conduct,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metro North Drafts Rules for Public Conduct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter railroad has drafted regulations for
public conduct on trains and in stations, including rules banning
nudity and sexual actvities.
   The rules, given preliminary approval Wednesday by Metro-North,
could lead to confrontations with the homeless, especially at Grand
Central terminal, critics argued.
   The Long Island Rail Road drafted similar regulations Tuesday.
   The draft outlines penalties for offenders such as summonses or
ejection, and fines of $50 and 30 days in jail.
   The proposals prohibit bathing at a drinking fountain, washing
clothing in restrooms or at any other source of water, changing
clothes or ``remaining undressed'' in a Metro-North station or
property and lying on ``floors, platforms, stairs or landings.''
Regulations for such activities as specific forms of sexual conduct
were spelled out.
   The proposals came days after Metro-North closed the large
waiting room at Grand Central _ long a haven for the homeless. The
Coalition for the Homeless estimates that 500 to 1,000 people stay
in the terminal or the streets and subway stations around it on a
given night.
   Metro-North President Peter Stangl said the draft was part of a
continuing effort by the Metropolitan Transportation Authority to
make all its agencies codify ``quality of life'' regulations.
   Stangl said he did not foresee the regulations creating
unnecessary confrontations with the homeless.
   ``But there are also people pretending to be homeless who are
selling crack and committing other crimes in Grand Central, and we
want them out of there,'' Stangl said.
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties
Union said confrontations were inevitable. ``These rules would
transform a social and economic problem into a criminal problem,''
he said.
   He said Metro-North should continue efforts to help the homeless
into city shelters and enroll in drug or alcohol treatment programs.
   The proposals were unanimously approved with minor discussion at
a monthly meeting of Metro-North's board. They must be discussed at
public hearings and require the approval of the full MTA board.
</TEXT>
