<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Terrorism     09-14 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Terrorism,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terrorist Wanted in United States Appeals For Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian accused in the bombing of a
Pan Am jet asked Thursday to be released from prison while Greece
decides on a U.S. extradition request, his lawyer said.
   Mohammed Rashid, 39, has been held in Greece since his May 1988
arrest on charges of planting a bomb on a Pan Am jumbo jet in 1982.
A Japanese teen-ager was killed and 15 people were injured in the
blast over Hawaii.
   The Athens Supreme Court upheld a U.S request for his extradition
in May, but the final decision rests with the justice minister.
   Greece's conservative-leftist government said in July that
Rashid's extradition will not be decided until new elections are
held by Nov. 5.
   American officials say Rashid's case is a test of Greece's
willingness to fight terrorism.
   The Palestinian asked prosecutor Dimitris Evthimiadis to take up
his petition. If the prosecutor decides it has merit, Rashid can
seek a hearing before the Appeals Court Council, which rules on
requests for temporary releases.
   Evthimiadis is expected to make a decision in the next few days.
   ``The lack of any final decision being taken by the justice
minister for such a long time period clearly violates basic tenets
which call for the swift processing of extradition cases, and it
stretches out my detention indefinitely, thus violating basic human
rights,'' lawyer Spyros Fytrakis quoted Rashid's petition as saying.
   Rashid first was held for entering Greece on a false passport.
His detention was extended after homemade knives were found in his
cell.
</TEXT>
