<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Romania     09-14 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Romania,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland Protests Reported Beating of Tourists by Romanian Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry filed a protest
Thursday after 30 Polish tourists said Romanian border soldiers beat
them brutally with rifle butts after dragging them off a train, the
state news agency PAP reported.
   The tourists were traveling from Budapest, Hungary, to the
Romanian capital, Bucharest, on Tuesday night when Romanian soldiers
ordered them to leave the train, forced them to turn over their
passports and kept them on a station platform while the train
departed, according to the PAP report.
   ``When I asked for my passport, I was dragged by force inside the
office, where I was brutally beaten up,'' the agency quoted Bogdan
Zapart of Legnica as saying.
   Boguslaw Miernik, general director of Poland's Foreign Ministry,
summoned Romania's charge d'affaires to demand an explanation, PAP
said.
   Miernik stressed such incidents ``do not serve the friendly
cooperation'' between the Warsaw Pact allies, the agency reported.
   It quoted Zapart as saying the soldiers fired tear gas and
wielded their rifles to subdue other Poles coming to his aid. The
group was locked in a waiting room, PAP reported.
   Zapart said he was handcuffed to a chair and beaten repeatedly,
PAP said.
   It quoted Emilia Kwietniewska of Bialogard as saying she saw
messages on the walls of the waiting room written in Polish about
similar attacks on other Poles, including rapes and robberies.
   The Romanian soldiers reportedly demanded payment Wednesday of
2,000 lei _ $167 at the official exchange rate or $28 on the black
market _ to release Zapart. He paid and the travelers were put back
on a train for Budapest, PAP said.
   Zapart was treated for injuries to his back, arms and head in
Budapest, where the group complained to the Polish Embassy,
according to state television.
   Their story was reported on front pages of several Polish
newspapers Thursday, including one that used the headline ``Romanian
border soliders are robbing and raping?'' then asked, ``Does Mr.
(Nicolae) Ceausescu know about this?'' referring to Romania's
hard-line Communist leader.
   Romania is a vehement opponent of recent East bloc reforms.
Poland is at the forefront of the reforms, having elected the East
bloc's first government not led by Communists.
</TEXT>
