<FIRST>u a PM-BakkerTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0590 09-14 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bakker Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0590,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bakker Aide Says Bakker Considered Fund-Raising Scheme Divine Inspiration</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Dortch's testimony. EDITS to tighten.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker's former chief aide today said
he objected to Bakker's use of the word ``investment'' in a brochure
offering free hotel rooms to $1,000 contributors, but the TV
evangelist got his way.
   The Rev. Richard Dortch, who pleaded guilty to fraud and drew
eight years in prison and $200,000 in fines for his role in the PTL
scandal, said Bakker insisted on keeping the word to entice
contributions.
   Bakker considered the fund-raising idea an ``inspiration'' from
God, Dortch said.
   Bakker is accused of overbooking his ministry's hotels and
diverting for his own use nearly $4 million raised from PTL
``lifetime partners'' _ $1,000 contributors who were promised three
nights' lodging a year for life at PTL's Heritage USA theme park
near Fort Mill, S.C.
   A parade of witnesses have said they paid the $1,000 only to be
told there was no room at the inn.
   If found guilty of all 24 counts of fraud and conspiracy, Bakker
could be sentenced to 120 years in prison and fined more than $5
million.
   Dortch today testified that Bakker was told at least daily about
the ministry's contributions and got updates even when he was on
television raising money. Dortch said Bakker kept a notebook with
daily listings of contributions and the number of ``lifetime
partnerships'' sold.
   Dortch said that he first heard of the partnerships about three
weeks after joining PTL in 1983 and that he was concerned with
brochures that called the partnerships an ``investment.''
   ``I had concern about the word because I had some experience in
the use of that term and I objected to the use of it in the
brochure,'' Dortch said.
   Dortch testified a week after being released from a Florida
hospital, where he had been held for several days for treatment of
an undisclosed ailment.
   Earlier today, the Rev. Don George, a former PTL board member,
said Bakker kept the board in the dark about the ministry's
financial straits and his six-figure bonuses and gave a rosy report
months before his 1987 downfall in a sex and money scandal.
   ``I was concerned about the endless fund-raising projects,'' said
George, who resigned over the ministry's fund-raising practices.
   ``There never seemed to be a balance period in the ministry when
large amounts of money were not being raised on TV.''
   George, of Irvine, Texas, joined the board in 1985 and quit in
February 1987, the month before Bakker resigned. He said Bakker gave
the board a financial overview at a meeting in January 1987.
   ``He gave a positive report. It was upbeat and encouraging,''
George said.
   On Wednesday, jurors were told that Bakker and his wife, Tammy,
were given more than $3 million in bonuses as the ministry narrowly
avoided financial collapse in the mid-1980s.
   Former PTL finance director Peter Bailey read from more than 70
memos he had sent the evangelist between 1983 and 1987 detailing the
TV ministry's chronic cash problems.
   ``We are continuing to operate far in excess of what is coming
in,'' Bailey read from a memo dated April 16, 1986, two weeks after
Bakker got a $200,000 bonus. ``The contributions are flat. We can
have all the financial controls in the world but if we don't live
within our means it doesn't mean anything.''
   In testimony today, George said the largest bonus he ever voted
for Bakker was $150,000, despite minutes from a November 1986
meeting at which Bakker was given a $500,000 bonus. The amount of
the bonus, as well as $150,000 for Bakker's wife, are in a memo
added to the board minutes.
   ``Did you ever vote for a $500,000 bonus for the Rev. Bakker,''
prosecutor Deborah Smith asked.
   ``No,'' George responded.
</TEXT>
