<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-14 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Trooper G.R. Johnson's infant son already
can boast about a ride in Dad's police car. He was born there.
   Johnson and his wife, Rosemarie, had planned on a delivery at
Cabell Huntington Hospital, and when Mrs. Johnson started having
contractions on Sunday, the couple began the more than one hour
drive there from their home.
   Their son, Robert Lee ``Cruise'' Johnson, had other plans, so
they made a quick turn after starting their journey at 11:05 a.m.
Trooper Johnson hit the siren and the flashing lights and they
threaded through traffic on U.S. 119 toward a closer hospital, Logan
General.
   As Mrs. Johnson's contractions came closer together, she decided
it was time.
   The 29-year-old bookkeeper and furniture accessory buyer
unfastened her seatbelt, slid to the edge of her seat and put one
foot up on the dashboard, at which time her 34-year-old husband's
heart went aflutter.
   ``I tried talking her out of it,'' he said, adding that he called
for an ambulance to meet them as they headed down the highway.
   ``I remained calm,'' Mrs. Johnson said of her first childbirth.
``I more or less said `mind over matter' going down the road and
just blocked everything out and concentrated on my breathing. I read
so much, I knew what to expect.
   ``I just grabbed his head with my left hand and held it. I put my
other hand around his side and held onto him that way. It was a
matter of just a few seconds, he just started crying.''
   Trooper Johnson said the sight of his 7-pound, 11-ounce boy was
quite a relief.
   ``When I heard that baby cry, it was like a ton of bricks was
lifted off my shoulders because I knew he was breathing,'' he said.
``I was all right then. It was fantastic.''
   The baby was born at 11:55, and the Johnsons arrived at the
hospital at noon. About 48 hours later, they returned home with the
healthy infant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HEMINGFORD, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People around here still talk about the
day Jeff Gaertig socked it to the Hemingford School Board.
   Gaertig, the Student Council president at Hemingford Public
School, went before the board recently to ask members to drop a
dress code requirement that the school's 176 students wear socks.
   Gaertig said shoe designs and fashions have changed in the 20
years or so since the board developed the dress code.
   ``There are the boat shoes and tennis shoes with better
ventilation,'' he said. ``I didn't think it would be a distraction
to learning whether students wore socks or not.''
   His presentation impressed school board members. They agreed
unanimously Monday to give the boot to the sock rule at the western
Nebraska school, which ranges from kindergarten to 12th grade.
   ``It was nice that he had the determination to come before the
school board,'' said board secretary Ken Sestak. ``A lot of times,
students get a little intimidated by authority.''
   Sestak said the policy had become difficult to enforce.
   ``It got to be where the principal would have to pull up pant
legs to tell or some students were wearing half-socks,'' Sestak
said. ``It wasn't a problem with learning.''
</TEXT>
