<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FCCSpending     09-14 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC Spending,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Lawmakers Hope for Better Relations with FCC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House lawmakers warmly greeted a new Federal
Communications Commission on Thursday, saying they hoped for a new
era of cooperation with the agency.
   ``During the Reagan administration, the FCC's style most often
reflected that of the hard rock group The Clash,'' said Rep. Edward
J. Markey, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
telecommunications and finance subcommittee.
   ``It is my hope that the workings and relationships of the (new
commission) ... will more closely resemble the Modern Jazz Quartet,
bringing with it an appreciation of tradition accompanied by both
creativity and innovation.''
   At a hearing on a bill to authorize $109.8 million in spending
for the FCC in fiscal 1990 and $121.5 million in fiscal 1991,
Democrats and Republicans alike expressed pleasure at seeing former
Missouri broadcaster Alfred Sikes as chairman of the agency.
   Sikes, who has been on the job five weeks, was accompanied by
three commissioners.
   Energy and Commerce Committee Chairman Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich., said Sikes' predecessors ``somehow didn't have a full
awareness of this committee'' and of Congress.
   He urged Sikes, along with incumbent commissioner James Quello
and newcomers Sherrie Marshall and Andrew Barrett, not to conduct
FCC business based on ideology or administration policy.
   Under the leadership of Mark Fowler and Dennis Patrick, the FCC
significantly loosened its regulation of the broadcasting and
telephone industries.
   It repealed the fairness doctrine for broadcasters, ended a
20-year-old regulatory scheme for American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
and made other changes in broadcast licensing and ownership rules.
   Sikes and the commissioners fielded a long list of
not-too-difficult questions at the hearing, generally repeating
earlier statements that indicate they'll take a more moderate
free-market regulatory stance than did Patrick or Fowler.
   ``The public needs a firm basis to believe that its fundamental
interests are being adequately safeguarded,'' Sikes said.
   ``Those striving for commercial success in the marketplace,
moreover, need adequate assurance that their success or failure will
depend chiefly on their own talents and endeavor _ and not be
affected significantly by the actions of unconstrained monoploy
power.''
   Sikes' commission, still one member short, will face a number of
thorny issues, including moves in Congress to deregulate the local
Bell telephone companies; how best to ensure that a U.S.
high-definition television industry emerges; and how to re-allocate
scarce space on the airwaves.
   There was no opposition expressed during the hearing to the FCC's
spending request, which is about $10 million more than this year's
appropriation. The Senate is considering the same level of spending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
