<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To add detail on what Lowe told inmates, subs lead and inserts
3 grafs after 5th graf of DAYTON, Ohio-dated 4th item of rdp. Picks up
6th graf, `While in...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Rob Lowe paid his debt to society this
week for his sex video by speaking to inmates at detention and
rehabilitation centers in his hometown, telling them to set goals
and ``believe in something.''
   George Waldo, a spokesman for the Georgia Department of Labor,
confirmed that Lowe served more than 20 hours of community service
Monday through Wednesday, giving formal and informal speeches to
Dayton inmates.
   Lowe's father, Chuck Lowe, a prominent Dayton attorney, helped
arrange the time with the Montgomery County probation office, Waldo
said.
   The star of such films as ``St. Elmo's Fire,'' who left Dayton 12
years ago, was back for the first time since he was accused of
making a sexually explicit videotape involving a teen-age girl
during the 1988 Democratic National Convention in Atlanta. A Georgia
court sentenced him to 20 hours of community service.
   He agreed to the community service to avoid possible criminal
action on allegations that he videotaped a 16-year-old girl in a sex
scene with a woman in an Atlanta hotel room.
   Lowe said he addressed youthful offenders in Project MonDay, a
program that provides job and education counseling to first-time,
non-violent offenders.
   ``I've been talking individually and in groups with people my age
who have been in trouble and saying to them, `Look, I went to the
same school that many of you did and I didn't know anybody who went
to Hollywood. I was lucky enough to have a dream, smart enough to
pursue it, and dumb enough not to know the odds (against being
successful).'
   ``I want them to have a goal, too, and to believe in something,
and that's basically been my message,'' Lowe told reporters.
   While in Ohio, Lowe also took a side trip to Cincinnati to visit
former Cincinnati Reds star Pete Rose.
   ``Pete's always been kind to me, great to me,'' Lowe said. ``We
both have had rough years. But friends are friends and I need
friends.''
   Rose last month was banned for life from major league baseball
after being accused of gambling on games involving his team. He can
appeal the ban after a year.
</TEXT>
