<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSAds-Lawsuit     09-14 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Ads-Lawsuit,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU Sues Chicago Transit Authority for Rejecting AIDS Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union has sued the
Chicago Transit Authority, alleging it arbitrarily rejected an AIDS
prevention ad as too explicit.
   The federal class-action lawsuit was filed Wednesday on behalf of
all groups wanting to put ads on public trains and buses. It charges
the agency with violating the constitutional rights of the Kupona
Network, the only black community organization in Chicago devoted
entirely to educating blacks about AIDS, said John Hammell, ACLU
Illinois director of the AIDS and Civil Liberties Project.
   ``Apparently one person or two persons at the CTA decided the
graphics were inappropriate,'' Hammell said. ``They have policies
which are applied arbitrarily, capriciously and in an invidious
discriminatory manner.''
   The ad features a drawing of two eyes, one reflecting the image
of a naked man and woman holding a condom package, the other an
image of a youth using drugs with a hypodermic syringe drawn
diagonally across the scene.
   The caption says ``Sex Without Condoms Plus Drug Abuse = AIDS.
AIDS in the Black Community is Very Real.''
   CTA spokeswoman Rosemarie Gulley said the ``ad was turned back
because the graphic art was far too explicit.'' She declined to
comment on the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
