<DOCNO> AP890914-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Poland 5thLd-Writethru a0653 09-14 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Poland, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0653,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration To Increase Aid To Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new, expanding attribution in lead, adding pork,
and includes more information on terms.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, yielding to
congressional pressures, was set today to announce a $50 million
increase in U.S. food aid to Poland, administration and
congressional sources said.
   The aid, to be made available during the fiscal year beginning
Oct. 1, is to include shipments of beef, pork, corn, butter, butter
oil, cotton and rice, according to the sources, who declined to be
identified.
   The aid is in addition to the $119 million aid package President
Bush announced earlier this summer, nearly half of which was
earmarked for food assistance.
   The new infusion of aid will bring the total food aid component
of the package to $100 million.
   Poland is obliged to repay the $50 million in this year's aid in
local currency. But the $100 million for fiscal 1990, which begins
Oct. 1, will be mostly in the form of grants _ or gifts, said a U.S.
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the increase had been in the works for some time, but
that the announcement was sped up in light of congressional calls
for giving Poland more help.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas broached the subject
of additional food aid to Poland following talks with leaders of
Poland's new government in Warsaw last month.
   Dole met with Bush at the president's Kennebunkport, Maine, home
to urge additional assistance as a signal of support to the new
governement and continued to press the administration on it as
recently as today.
   Several other House and Senate members also have called on the
administration to increase aid to Poland or have introduced
legislation outlining their own assistance plans.
   As the White House prepared the announcement, State Department
officials extended assurances to Poland and its congressional
supporters.
   ``The Polish government can count on our continued support,''
said department spokesman Richard Boucher. He said the emergence of
the Solidarity labor movement as in control of the government was a
``key factor'' in a situation that he described as evolving.
   ``We felt that additional measures might be appropriate and we
are seriously considering some,'' Boucher said.
   Some members of Congress are pushing the White House to increase
U.S. assistance in order to help the Warsaw government cope with its
adjustment to a new economic system that has some elements of
capitalism.
   The president and his advisers are eager for the economic and
political changes in Poland, and Bush traveled to Warsaw and Gdansk
this summer to symbolize U.S. support. But the predominant view
within the administration is that Poland should demonstrate its
ability to make the transition and to hold down inflaion before more
U.S. aid is committed.
   Lech Walesa, the Solidarity leader whose non-communist trade
union movement commands a dominant role in the Warsaw government, is
due to visit Washington in November.
   Walesa has called for $10 billion in emergency assistance,
including $2.7 billion from the International Monetary Fund, $3
billion from the World Bank and $4.1 billion in new bilateral
credits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
