<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InmateJailers     09-14 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inmate Jailers,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator's Bill Would Bar Inmates from Being Jailers, Dispatchers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Mississippi, a rape victim reporting the
crime to the sheriff's office could end up talking to a dispatcher
doing time for rape himself.
   And because state law doesn't spell out what jobs felons are
allowed to do in jail, someone arrested on a drug charge could
discover the man with custody of the keys on that shift is serving a
sentence for peddling dope.
   Although it is uncertain how many convicted felons actually
perform important duties, such as dispatcher or jailer,
unsupervised, Rep. J.B. Van Slyke says he plans to introduce a bill
next legislative session to make the practice illegal.
   ``I do not favor an inmate taking care of the jail or being a
dispatcher, not at all,'' Van Slyke said.
   Lafayette County Sheriff F.D. East, president of the Mississippi
Sheriffs Association, said he informally polled about 20 sheriffs on
their policies on assigning felons after the issue was raised. He
said there were some counties that use felons for responsible jobs,
but he declined to identify them.
   Most counties regularly use inmates for traditional work such as
cleaning up and cooking, he said.
   In the 1970s, a federal court ordered major reforms of the state
prison system, including a ban on convicted murderers serving as
armed guards. But the law does not ban state prisoners who are
serving their time in county jails from serving as unarmed jailers,
officials said.
   Ken Jones, a spokesman for the State Corrections Department, said
more than 1,200 of Mississippi's roughly 8,000 state prisoners are
being held in county jails because of overcrowding at state
facilities.
   ``We know of no ruling or any law that prohibits the use of
inmates, for instance, as jailers,'' Jones said. ``It really falls
back to the sheriff to use his good judgment in the assignment of
inmates to work details.''
   The issue came to Van Slyke's attention after Wiggins Mayor
Ferris O'Neal recently accused Stone County Sheriff Eldon Ladner of
using inmates as jailers and dispatchers, sometimes unsupervised.
   ``I feel it is a threat and danger to the citizens of Wiggins and
Stone County,'' O'Neal said. ``I am 100 percent in favor of inmates
working, but there are a lot of other things they can do than man
the communication system unsupervised.''
   Ladner has declined to comment on O'Neal's accusations, but Van
Slyke said Ladner told him he used inmates as dispatchers, but not
as jailers.
   The legislator said he wasn't aware of any problems in the past
caused by inmates holding such positions of responsibility, but he's
concerned about the potential for tragedy.
   Lauderdale County Chief Deputy Mike Vick said his county is among
several which have used inmates to assist jailers and dispatchers
when the regular staff was stretched tight. Prisoners never have
served on a daily basis in such responsible roles, and do not work
unsupervised, he said.
   ``They have been used in the past to assist dispatchers if there
was a major situation going on like a gasoline spill or train
derailment,'' Vick said.
   ``Basically, if you've got inmate labor there's always a
potential for problems,'' Vick acknowledged. ``But being a trusty is
a privilege, not a right. So if you have problems with an inmate,
you lock him up..''
   East said if any sheriffs use convicted felons in positions of
responsibility, it is only because tight finances have forced them
into a corner.
   ``If they pass any law, they should pass a law saying you have to
have enough deputies and people to run the jails,'' East said. ``The
bottom line is, we don't want state inmates anyway.
   ``No money is why we have state prisoners in county jails
anyway,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
