<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-BootCamp 420   09-14 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Boot Camp, 420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration, ACLU Oppose Federal `Boot Camps'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bush administration official and the American
Civil Liberties Union took a nearly identical stance Thursday
against proposed legislation to establish federal ``boot camp''
prisons for young offenders.
   J. Michael Quinlan, director of the Bureau of Prisons, told a
House Justice subcommittee that the administration supports the
concept on the state level, but contends it wouldn't work on a
federal level.
   ``The success of these programs is yet undetermined,'' he said,
referring to the nine states with special programs for non-violent,
youthful first offenders in which rigorous military discipline and
physical training play a role.
   Claudia Wright, associate director of the ACLU national prison
project, agreed.
   ``A good deal more thought and research should be done before
deciding that the `boot camp' concept will be a viable alternative
form of incarceration for the federal prison system,'' she told the
panel.
   President Bush was often at odds with the ACLU during his 1988
campaign, accusing the group of being out of the mainstream of
American values.
   Subcommittee Chairman Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who introduced the
boot-camp legislation, said the camps could be a ``powerful new
weapon'' in the war on drugs.
   The bill calls for any able-bodied, first-time offender with a
prison term of 12 months to 16 months to be eligible, with each day
in camp counting as four days in prison. The program would be open
to all prisoners, not just drug offenders.
   Quinlan said only 60 of 50,000 federal prisoners would meet the
criteria. However, Quinlan said that could change as a result of the
administration's desire to arrest more drug users and that the
bureau might then reconsider its opposition.
   He also indicated support for sending federal prisoners to state
boot camps under contract.
   Ms. Wright called it ``grossly inappropriate'' to compare the
effects of prison boot camps with those of military basic training.
   ``To serve in the military provides young people with a sense of
pride and achievement which remains with them throughout their
lives,'' she said. ``That sense of pride comes not from having
survived a demeaning experience, but from the patriotism, esprit de
corps and sense of purpose that is instilled by serving one's
country as part of a proud tradition.''
   Commissioner Thomas Coughlin of the New York Department of
Correctional Services said his state's 2-year-old program includes
drug treatment and education, not just military routine.
</TEXT>
