<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     09-14 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurgents Claim to Hit Government Convoys; Afghanistan Frees French
Worker</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Stands for Islamabad-dated story on news advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurgents said Thursday they stopped
two government supply convoys that had tried to run a guerrilla
blockade of the highway that links the capital to the Soviet Union.
   The government released a captured 33-year-old French aid worker
Thursday after keeping him prisoner for a month.
   Masoud Khalili, a spokesman for the Jamiat-i-Islami guerrilla
group, said in Islamabad, Pakistan, that insurgents sent two
government resupply convoys limping back to Charikar, the provincial
capital of Afghanistan's central Parwan province.
   Nine government tanks were destroyed Monday in the first attack
on the Salang Highway, Khalili said.
   ``Smoke and fire could be seen several kilometers away,'' he
said. On Tuesday, two military vehicles and a tank were destroyed
before a second convoy retreated, he said.
   The convoys were moving north to outfit government garrisons
protecting the Salang, Khalili said.
   Details of the attacks, led by guerrilla commander Ahmad Shah
Masoud, were relayed to the guerrilla group's headquarters in
Pakistan, Khalili said.
   There was no confirmation from the Kabul government.
   Khalili said Masoud has mapped out a 30-mile battle zone along
the Salang Highway. This area includes one of the government's
largest military air bases at Bagram, six miles southeast of
Charikar and about 30 miles north of the Afghan capital of Kabul.
   Successive rebel attacks against the Kabul airport have increased
the communist government reliance on Bagram to offload military
supplies from the Soviets. The Soviets have increased arms shipments
to Kabul since the last Red Army troops pulled out of Afghanistan on
Feb. 15.
   In Kabul, Afghan officials released Henri-Xavier Lemire, an
employee of the humanitarian organization Handicap International.
Lemire was captured Aug. 14 while traveling with a guerrilla convoy
from Pakistan.
   Lemire told a news conference that a colleague, Vincent Gernigon,
was killed when government troops fired on the convoy near the
village of Marja, 95 miles west of the southern provincial capital
of Kandahar.
   Lemire was wounded by three pieces of shrapnel and had been held
in a government hospital.
   The aid workers were delivering prosthetic devices, wheelchairs
and other orthopedic equipment, he said. Many Afghans have lost legs
in mine blasts during 11 years of fighting between the U.S.-backed
guerrillas and the pro-Soviet government.
   Lemire, dressed in green-and-white striped hospital pajamas and
carrying a towel, said he was informed that he would be released
just 45 minutes before the news conference.
   ``I want to eat and see my family,'' he said.
   Government spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said President Najib
released Lemire after appeals by President Francois Mitterrand of
France and Javier Perez de Cuellar, secretary-general of the United
Nations.
</TEXT>
