<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Drugs     09-14 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Drugs,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven US Military Teams at Work in Peru, Colombia and Bolivia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said Thursday that seven U.S.
military teams are training local forces in the Andean nations'
anti-drug battle, but insisted the Americans will not be sent
``where there is great risk.''
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams also announced that Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney plans to outline a ``forward leaning'' role
for the Pentagon next week under President Bush's plan for fighting
the nation's drug problem.
   Revealing additional details about the role of U.S. military
forces in Latin America, Williams said there are three U.S. military
training teams in Peru, and two each in Colombia and Bolivia helping
training local forces.
   ``Those are the counter-narcotics training teams under the Andean
strategy,'' Williams said.
   There are no such teams in any other South American nation, he
said.
   Williams described the teams as providing ``specific equipment
training, but they also provide tactical training as well.''
   A secret national security directive signed by Bush last month
has allowed for an expansion of the training role for the U.S.
forces, allowing them to leave their bases and train local forces in
so-called ``secure areas'' in the region.
   Williams declined to offer a definitive number of persons in the
three nations, saying the number would vary depending upon the type
of training mission under way at any given time.
   He would say only that currently, there are fewer than 50 persons
involved.
   ``There's no magic number, no magic ceiling,'' he said, adding
that each team may number anywhere from two to 12 persons each.
   The spokesman emphasized, as he has for weeks, that the teams
have been sent to the nations at their request and that the
``decision to deploy'' is made on a case-by-case basis.
   ``No military training teams are going to be sent into an area in
which they would face great risk. That is part of the assessment
that would be made in these case-by-case judgements,'' Williams said.
   Bush and other top administration officials have repeatedly
denied that the U.S. forces sent to aid the Latin nations would
enter combat.
   Williams said the Pentagon did not want to say where the units
were coming from, or their exact locations in the host countries,
``because of security reasons.''
   The spokesman also said Cheney planned to discuss details of the
Pentagon's role in the president's anti-drug battle on Monday, and
said the secretary has described it as ``a forward leaning'' type of
plan.
   Pentagon sources, who spoke on condition that they not be
identified, said a preliminary draft indicated that the secretary
wants to beef up radar and commications efforts along U.S. borders
to monitor drug traffickers and increase the number of naval and air
patrols in the Caribbean.
   ``There's a lot of holes out there that need to be patched,'' the
official said, speaking on condition he not be identified.
</TEXT>
