<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel     09-14 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Helicopters Attack Palestinian Guerrilla Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli helicopter gunships blasted rockets
at two Palestinian guerrilla bases east of Sidon in a raid Thursday
night, police and witnesses said.
   At least three guerrillas were wounded in the attack on Ein
el-Hilweh camp on the eastern flank of the city 25 miles south of
Beirut, police said.
   Israel's army command in Jerusalem said its air force hit a base
of terrorist mastermind Abu Nidal and that all aircraft returned
safely to base.
   Witnesses requesting anonymity said three Cobra helicopters flew
low from the Mediterranean to attack their targets at 9:30 p.m. The
witnesses said the helicopters fired at least four rockets into the
camp.
   Three of the rockets exploded on a base of the
Fatah-Revolutionary Council, the powerful faction led by Abu Nidal,
who also is called Sabri al-Banna.
   The fourth projectile hit a nearby battery manned by guerrillas
of George Habash's Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine.
   It was not immediately clear which guerrillas were wounded
because their comrades quickly sealed the area.
   It was Israel's 12th air attack on Lebanon this year. By police
count, 17 people have been killed and 98 wounded in previous
strikes, the last Sept. 4 on Majdal Balhis, a tiny village in the
Syrian-policed Bekaa valley.
   That attack was directed against the Libyan-backed Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command. Four guerrillas
were wounded.
   Habash's Damascus-based group, the second-largest Palestine
Liberation Organization faction after Fatah, has claimed
responsibility for at least two recent attacks against Israel.
   Last week it said its guerrillas blasted rockets across the
Jordanian-Israeli border. The projectiles crashed into fields in the
northern Jordan valley, causing no damage or casualties.
   On Sunday, the group said it had a shootout with an Israeli
patrol in Israel's self-designated ``security zone'' in south
Lebanon. One Israeli soldier and a guerrilla were killed in the
gunbattle.
   Israel carved the 6- to 10-mile-wide zone, stretching from the
foothills of Mount Hermon to the Mediterranean, when it withdrew the
bulk of its forces at the end of a three-year invasion of Lebanon.
</TEXT>
