<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1653EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Illiteracy     09-14 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Illiteracy,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Has 220 Million Illiterates, 70 Percent Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More and more children are dropping out of school
in China to work in fields and factories, adding to a literacy
crisis that is an unwelcome spinoff of economic reforms.
   Recent reports say more than one-fifth of China's population, or
220 million people, cannot read.
   Most of the country's 7.15 million dropouts are girls, and 70
percent of the country's illiterates are women, official newspapers
say.
   The illiteracy rate has dropped from 80 percent to 22 percent
since the Communists took over 40 years ago, said a recent series in
the Legal News Daily.
   But the nation's educational level is deteriorating again as more
students abandon their classrooms.
   Legal News Daily said 1,332 middle school and elementary school
pupils dropped out over a two-month period in one county of coastal
Fujian province. About 1 million students have quit in the past year
in Sichuan, China's most populous province.
   The People's Daily reported about 2.5 million village children in
Henan province are not attending school. There are about 180 million
primary and middle school students in China.
   Children leave school to work in the fields, be maids or factory
workers in the city, or help in relatives' private enterprises, the
report said.
   China has compulsory education through the ninth grade, but many
students are defying the regulation, often with encouragement from
parents.
   Economic reforms, including the return of the family farm and the
phenomenal growth of rural industries in the past decade, have
fueled the need for labor.
   In Fujian, authorities found 2,322 children younger than 16 in a
day's raids on factories. Among them, 164 could not read.
   In a textile factory in Bobai County in southern Guangxi
province, all 40 workers were children.
   Legal News quoted a school administrator as commenting on a job
advertisement: ``This is the chance to get a good job. If the kids
cannot advance to high school and they miss this recruitment, we
will be blamed for ruining their future.''
   Teachers, among the lowest paid of Chinese government workers,
also are dropping out.
   In Fujian, the paper said, 853 teachers have resigned and 148
schools have closed since May.
   A survey showed that among 12 occupations in China, teachers are
among the lowest paid and have the worst living and medical
facilities.
   Chinese media have reported some teachers are forced to sell
bread and soft drinks to supplement their income. In Shanghai, many
have stopped teaching and spend all their time as salesmen,
interpreters, even singers.
   China Youth News reported that among 7,000 students entering
universities from northeast China's Jilin province, only six wanted
to go to teacher training college.
   It said a parent pleaded with one college administrator, ``Please
do not accept my child. Enrollment in a teachers university means
committing suicide.''
   This year, in the week leading up to the annual Sept. 10 Teachers
Day, seminars were held throughout the country to boost the status
and morale of teachers. Model teachers were given plaques, flags and
discounts for clothes and haircuts.
   Legal News Daily said such rewards hardly would satisfy most
young Chinese. It cited the case of a university student who
advertised for a wife. A young woman wrote back: ``You cannot eat
culture or spend idealism like money ... If you have a wife,
dissuade your kids from going to college. Studying until the fifth
grade is enough. Tell him to get rich by selling fish.''
</TEXT>
