<FIRST>r w AM-NewDestroyer     09-14 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Destroyer,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dingell Says New Navy Destroyer a `Procurement Nightmare'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction of the Navy's new $1.2 billion
destroyer has become a ``procurement nightmare'' of cost overruns
and schedule delays, a lawmaker charged in a letter released on the
eve of the ship's launching.
   Bath Iron Works, which the Navy contracted to build the DDG-51
destroyer, is 18 months behind schedule on the program and will
launch a ship Saturday that is only 38 percent complete, said Rep.
John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee on oversight and investigations.
   The ship will be named the Arleigh Burke, after the World War II
naval hero and later chief of naval operations.
   ``The ship has suffered huge overruns, with the design costs
increasing by about 120 percent; and construction costs have
increased by more than 60 percent,'' Dingell said in a two-page
letter to Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III.
   The letter, dated Sept. 12, was obtained Thursday by The
Associated Press.
   Design costs have increased from the original contract estimate
of $111 million to $247 million while construction costs have grown
from $157 million to $252 million, Dingell said.
   The Michigan Democrat based his charges on a draft report from
the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress
which is conducting an inquiry into the program. The GAO's final
report is expected later this year.
   ``The acquisition of the DDG-51 has turned into a procurement
nightmare,'' Dingell said in the letter.
   At the Pentagon, Navy Cmdr. Mark Baker said Bath Iron Works ``is
on schedule in accordance with their contractural requirements. The
Navy considers the program well under control in both cost and
schedule.''
   Baker said the production schedule calls for the ship to be
delivered to the Navy in February 1991. The original delivery date
of October 1989 had been changed due to a 99-day strike at Bath Iron
Works in July 1985, a requirement of additional Navy testing of the
combat system and problems with computer-aided design, the Navy
spokesman said.
   William E. Haggett, chairman and chief executive officer of Bath
Iron Works, called Dingell's assessment a ``distortion of the
overall picture on the destroyer program'' as well as ``factually
incorrect.''
   According to the executive at the 105-year-old shipyard which
built 83 destroyers during World War II, the destroyer is ``ready in
every respect for launching.''
   ``It's 47 to 51 percent complete, a higher level than we launched
our previous prototype ship,'' Haggett said in a telephone interview
from Bath, Maine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
