<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1657EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia     09-14 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>SWAPO Leader Returns From Exile, Pledging National Reconciliation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of cheering people lined the
streets Thursday to greet Namibian guerrilla leader Sam Nujoma as he
ended 30 years of exile to compete in pre-independence elections.
   ``We never lost sight of our principal objective _ freedom and
independence for Namibia,'' Nujoma said.
   Supporters of Nujoma's South-West African People's Organization
mobbed his motorcade as it left the airport on the 25-mile drive
through the empty and arid countryside into Windhoek, the capital.
   ``We return in the spirit of peace, love and national
reconciliation,'' said Nujoma, whose fighters waged a 23-year war
against South African rule of Namibia.
   Tight security measures were in force because of threats on
Nujoma's life and the assassination Tuesday of Anton Lubowski, the
only white with a leadership post in Nujoma's movement.
   South Africa, which has controlled Namibia since 1915, agreed to
grant the territory independence under U.N. supervision. Elections
are set for November and independence is expected early next year.
   Nujoma's return will undoubtedly boost the fortunes of his
independence movement, which already is favored to capture the most
votes. Nujoma arrived a day before the deadline to register for
election to the constituent assembly that will write a constitution.
   ``No words may express my happiness at joining my family, friends
and comrades,'' said Nujoma, who kissed the tarmac and hugged his
89-year-old mother when he got off the Ethiopian Airlines jet from
Luanda, Angola.
   Nujoma predicted his organization would win an ``overwhelming
majority'' at the polls. The nationalist movement needs to capture
two-thirds of the seats to draw up the constitution by itself.
   His boisterous supporters, crammed into trucks, vans, station
wagons, and buses, brought traffic to a halt as they followed Nujoma
from the airport through town. They honked horns, sang songs,
chanted slogans gave clenched fist salutes and waved the red, blue
and green movement flag.
   People left their offices and homes to see the parade, and some
joined in. Others shouted obscenities.
   Nujoma, when asked about the death threats, said, ``Whenever I
move about I am concerned about my own safety.''
   He said Lubowski ``will be remembered for for his dedication to
the sacred code of peace, justice and freedom.'' Lubowski, 37, a
civil rights lawyer, was killed by automatic rifle fire outside his
Windhoek home Tuesday night.
   Earlier Thursday, Police Inspector Kierie du Rand said a
50-year-old white man with an Irish passport had been arrested in
the killing. Du Rand said the man reportedly came to Namibia from
Cape Town, South Africa and was arrested Wednesday in Windhoek.
   Du Rand did not identify him and said additional arrests were
expected.
   All the movement leaders have unarmed bodyguards. They said they
have applied for police protection, but they want U.N. forces to
monitor the police guards.
   The guerrilla group has received some bad publicity as some
people said they were captured by the group and tortured. They said
up to 2,000 other detainees were still being held.
   Nujoma denied anyone was still being held.
   Fighting between the guerrillas and the South African-led
security forces ended in April. Since then, there have been only
isolated violent incidents in this territory.
   Nujoma's organization is leftist-leaning and favors a socialist
economy. He is viewed as a shrewd, instinctive politician,
maintaining the presidency of SWAPO since 1960 despite occasional
challenges.
</TEXT>
