<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--Piranhas     09-14 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Piranhas,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illness Believed Linked to Bath Contamination from Aquarium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aside from the obvious, researchers have found
another reason not to bathe with piranhas _ the possibility of
bacterial illness.
   The national Centers for Disease Control reported Thursday the
case of a Missouri toddler who was bathed in a baby sitter's tub
soon after aquarium water had been dumped there; she developed a
bacterial infection believed to have come from the sitter's pet
piranhas.
   The 14-month old girl, who was not identified, developed diarrhea
and a fever. She recovered after five days.
   The CDC said the report is the first time Plesiomonas
shigelloides bacteria has been associated with aquarium water. The
bacteria has been found in surface water, fish and animals,
including dogs and cats.
   After the July 1988 case, Missouri health officials spot-checked
18 fish tanks around the state and found the bacteria in four, all
in pet shop aquariums.
   In its weekly report, the CDC said precautions such as
handwashing after contact with aquarium water and preventing
contamination of bathing or drinking water, should decrease the
transmission of such bacteria.
</TEXT>
