<FIRST>u w AM-Jackson-BlackCaucus     09-14 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson-Black Caucus,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls For War Poverty With War On Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Black Caucus Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Thursday that President
Bush's plan to fight drugs underestimates the power of drug cartels
and should be combined with a war on poverty.
   ``If you woke up tomorrow morning sober and drug free, and rain
falling through your roof, you'd still have another war to fight _
the war on poverty,'' Jackson said.
   Speaking at one of the forums sponsored by the Congressional
Black Caucus during its three-day ``Legislative Weekend,'' the
two-time candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination said
Bush's drug program is insufficient to combat drug suppliers.
   ``The drug plan underestimates the viciousness of the drug lords.
They have better weapons than our state militia. They've got AK-47s,
they've got Uzis (automatic weapons). They're better equipped;
they're willing to kill and be killed,'' Jackson said.
   ``They're more dangerous than the drug plan assesses they are,''
he said. ``The drug plan underestimates their troop strength. The
drug users are more desperate than the plan recognizes.''
   He also said poor people are being exploited on the other end of
the drug-production chain and that a war on drugs should include an
effort to ease poverty in rural South America where drugs are grown.
   ``You've got the very poor on both ends, growing and consuming,
and the very wealthy, wheeling and dealing,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson spoke at a youth forum during the first full day of
events sponsored by the Congessional Black Caucus, the organization
of black members of Congress.
   The events are expected to attract 20,000 people by their
conclusion Saturday night at a $300 black-tie gala dinner and
assorted parties.
   Actor Lou Gossett Jr. also spoke to the black youth group, and
while other workshops and seminars were held on subjects ranging
from blacks in athletics to illiteracy to jazz.
   At a forum on college sports, Grambling University President
Joseph Johnson condemned a proposal before the National Collegiate
Athletic Association to deny automatic invitations to the NCAA
basketball tournaments to conferences made up of predominantly black
colleges.
   ``There is a movement to turn the clock back on black
institutions,'' Johnson said.
   At a forum titled ``The Resurgence of Racism and the Far Right,''
one speaker said that there has been an escalation of racial
violence linked to a ``deepening economic crisis.''
   Leah Wise, executive director of the Southerners for Economic
Justice, a labor-oriented group based in Durham, N.C., said many
racial incidents over the past decade in the South can be linked to
plant closings and other economic threats felt by whites.
   Wise said many blacks continue to face worse working conditions
than whites. She said the civil rights movement must share some of
the blame because ``we spent more time working on affirmative action
for elite sectors than on the day-to-day conditions of our workers.''
</TEXT>
