<HEAD>3 Qualify to Run for Seat of Rep. Larkin Smith</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Democrats _ including Attorney General
Mike Moore _ and a Republican have qualified for the Oct. 3 special
election to fill the unexpired term of the late U.S. Rep. Larkin
Smith.
   Smith, a freshman Republican, died Aug. 13 in a plane crash along
with his pilot.
   Candidates were required to submit petitions by Wednesday
carrying the names of at least 1,000 registered voters to qualify
for the race for the 5th District seat.
   Republican Tom Anderson spent 16 years as chief of staff to U.S.
Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss. Anderson, 43, worked for Lott while Lott
represented the 5th District in Congress and after Lott won election
to the U.S. Senate last fall.
   Anderson also had a stint as ambassador to Barbados.
   Moore, 37, is a former district attorney in Jackson County in the
5th District.
   State Sen. Gene Taylor, 35, of Bay St. Louis was defeated by
Smith in 1988 but captured 46 percent of the vote.
   Smith's widow, Sheila, first said she would run for seat, but
later said she was backing Anderson.
