<FIRST>u w AM-AIDS-DDI     09-14 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-DDI,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Poised To Approve Wider Distribution Of AIDS Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan for wider distribution of a promising
experimental AIDS drug known as DDI is expected to be approved
shortly, Food and Drug Administration sources said Thursday.
   Bristol-Myers Co., which is licensed to manufacture the drug, has
said it will distribute DDI, or dideoxyinosine, at no cost to AIDS
patients when the next round of clinical trials begins later this
month.
   The drug has so far been available only to about 90 patients in
phase one clinical trials, the initial safety studies.
   The company has asked the FDA to approve distribution of the drug
to patients who do not qualify for the upcoming round of research
trials, which will compare DDI to AZT, the only approved anti-AIDS
drug. Patients who cannot tolerate AZT would be ineligible for these
trials.
   FDA officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said no
decision has been made on precisely who would be eligible to receive
the drug, though one source said it would include certain patients
outside clinical trials.
   Researchers say that like AZT, DDI appears to reduce replication
of the human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS, and controls
the disease by enabling the body to recover some ability to fight
infection.
   Scientists say one important advantage DDI has compared with AZT
is that it is less toxic and better tolerated by patients.
</TEXT>
