<FIRST>r w AM-Pickering-Soviets     09-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pickering-Soviets,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Openness Has Eased Diplomacy, U.S. Envoy to U.N. Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dealing with Soviet diplomats has undergone
``kind of a remarkable change'' as a by-product of that country's
new openness and negotiations have become much easier, the U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations said Thursday.
   ``Dealing with Soviet diplomats has become something quite
different than it was 10, 15, 30 years ago,'' Thomas Pickering told
a National Press Club audience. ``You can now begin a process of
sitting down and not only exploring where the issues will go but
also sitting down and trying to put the pieces together.''
   ``While that occurred from time to time in many areas over the
past couple of decades, it was nowhere occurring as universally as
it is now, nor I think nearly as enthusiastically as it is now,'' he
said.
   Pickering was named to the U.N. post by President Bush and is
only the second career officer to hold the job since it was
established 43 years ago.
   Today's Soviets, Pickering said, ``are much more interested in
finding ways to put things together and it's a fascinating
exploration because, indeed, as the Soviet Union has moved it has
moved not away from us but in a direction of what has worked in our
society.
   ``There is a fascinating interest on the part of the Soviets
about how does our society tick, what makes it work, what are the
features of success, where have the failures been and how and in
what way can they possibly incorporate those in the sort of system
they hope to build,'' he said.
</TEXT>
