<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia-King     09-14 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-King,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remains of Former King to be Moved from Italy to Yugolslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist authorities will rebury the
last king of Montenegro, who died in exile in 1921, in the city that
served as capital of his kingdom, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   For many years, officials harshly criticized the Yuguslav
monarchy after it was abolished and Communism proclaimed in 1945.
   The decision to allow reinterment reflects growing liberalization
and swelling nationalist sentiments during economic hardship and
ethnic strife.
   The remains of King Nikola Petrovic and Queen Milena will be
exhumed from their tomb in the Italian Mediterranean resort of San
Remo on Sept. 29, according to the Politika Ekspres daily.
   After being transferred back to Yugoslavia, they will be reburied
on Oct. 1 in an Orthodox church at Cetinje, former capital of the
Kingdom of Montenegro, the daily said. Montenegro is now one of six
Yugoslav republics.
   According to sources close to those organizing the reburial,
Yugoslavia's Crown Prince Aleksandar Karadjordjevic, a businessman
living in London and a distant relative of King Nikola, will be
invited to come to Yugoslavia to attend the ceremony.
   If he accepts, it will be the first time that a direct descendant
of the royal family has gained permission to enter the country since
Communist rule began.
   Montenegro was an independent state for centuries before it was
incorporated into the Kingdom of Yugoslavia in 1918 under the rule
of the rival Serbian Karadjordjevic dynasty.
   King Nikola, who had fled to Italy to escape advancing
Austro-Hungarian troops in 1916, never returned home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
