<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1753EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CleanAir 1stLd-Writethru a0682 09-14 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dingell May Propose Easing Acid Rain Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts first 5 grafs to show Lent still backing administration
proposal, picking up 6th graf pvs, Sulfur dioxide.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. John D. Dingell, the chief House
Democratic sponsor of President Bush's clean air bill, signaled
Thursday he propose relaxing the administration's stringent curbs on
acid rain.
   Dingell, chairman of the Energy and Commerce Committee, said he
had problems with a section of the acid rain plan that Environmental
Protection Agency Administrator William K. Reilly this week called
the most crucial part of the proposal.
   The move would place the Michigan Democrat in the unusual
position of opposing a key provision of the bill he is sponsoring.
It also would change what environmentalists call the strongest
portion of the Bush legislation.
   Reilly said the administration opposed any attempt to weaken the
provision, which would ``cap'' emissions of sulfur dioxide, a key
component of acid rain. The chief Republican sponsor of the
legislation, Rep. Norman F. Lent, R-N.Y., said he favors retaining
the administration's language.
   The ``cap'' would prevent sulfur dioxide emissions from growing
again after they are steadily reduced by a total of 10 million tons
over the next decade.
   Sulfur dioxide combines with nitrogen oxide in the atmosphere and
travels for hundreds of miles before falling to earth, killing
aquatic life in lakes and streams, damaging trees, decreasing
visibility and possibly harming human lungs.
   Speaking before the Energy and Commerce environment subcommittee,
Dingell said keeping the cap would prevent utilities from growing to
serve new customers. It also would harm the high-sulfur coal
industry, which is cheap but fuels the dirtiest-burning utilities,
he told the panel, which will begin considering amendments to the
Bush bill next week.
   But ``loosening ... the cap,'' Dingell said, would reduce sulfur
dioxide emissions ``without a severe impact on growth or on the use
of coal in the next century.''
   Power plants burning high-sulfur coal would bear the brunt of the
sulfur dioxide reductions under the Bush legislation. The United
Mine Workers union fears the utilities would reduce emissions the
cheapest way, by switching to other fuels. The EPA estimates that
could cost 17,000 jobs in the high-sulfur coal industry.
   ``I am ... greatly concerned that unemployment in Appalachia will
rise by enacting this ... bill,'' Dingell said. ``Clearly, that
should not be an environmental, utility industry or federal goal.''
   A Bush administration official, speaking only on condition he not
be named, said, ``We'll defend the president's position. We'll also
work with the sponsors. We'll wait for specific changes and figure
out how we'll react.''
   While the ``cap'' would make it difficult for electric utilities
to serve additional customers after the year 2000, there is a
provision to permit some growth. Utilities could accomplish this by
buying ``credits'' from utilities that exceeded their required
reductions.
   Dingell, a longtime champion of the auto industry, said,
meanwhile, that he would vigorously fight any attempts to toughen
Bush's anti-pollution requirements for motor vehicles.
   ``I would point out that all of the country does not have the air
pollution problems of California,'' Dingell said. ``Yet, some,
particularly in the Northeast, suggest that we should extend the
entire California auto emissions program nationwide.
   ``I would hope that my colleagues resist the temptation to single
out for punishment an industry that with its suppliers from the
glass, steel, aluminum, plastics, rubber and mining industries,
among others, employs millions in all the states.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WhiteHouse-Jobs     09-14 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House-Jobs,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Claims Record In Appointing Women And Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in less than eight months in
office, has chosen more women for top jobs than any previous
president in a full year, his personnel chief said Thursday.
   Chase Untermeyer said Bush recently eclipsed Jimmy Carter's old
record of 72 women appointees in 1980 with his 73rd presidential
appointment, and has already raised that mark to 77.
   ``And we're not stopping there,'' Untermeyer said in a lecture at
the Heritage Foundation. ``We're going to name more and more.''
   Untermeyer said 20 percent of Bush's appointees to the jobs
requiring senatorial confirmation have been women and 13 percent
minorities.
   Untermeyer did not say how those percentages compared with those
of previous presidents.
   While smaller than the percentage of the women and minorities in
the entire population, the Bush administrations figures are about
double the comparable percentage of women and minorities in the top
ranks of the civil service, he claimed.
   Untermeyer, the director of presidential personnel, sought to
rebut criticism from congressional Democrats that the Bush
administration is riddled with vacancies.
   In the Cabinet departments, the vacancy rate for the highest
positions is less than 12 percent _ 36 jobs out of 312, he said.
   A few of the 36 are ``important jobs,'' including the
undersecretary of commerce for technology, ``but most of those 36
are positions that are clearly of lower priority,'' said Untermeyer.
   ``I'm not trying to ridicule these positions or the industries or
sectors of the American economy that they are involved with, but
among those vacancies that we don't have a candidate in process yet
is to be the deputy commissioner of patents and the deputy
commissioner of trademarks,'' said Untermeyer.
   ``The federal grain inspector is also one of those positions.
Many of these jobs make me wonder why they are presidential
appointments at all. But the Congress has decreed that they should
be presidential appointments, so they are,'' he said.
   ``Elsewhere, we have 88 percent of the positions that count''
either on the job or awaiting confirmation, he said.
   The Democratic Study Group, in a blistering report released Aug.
29, charged that 160 of 394 senior positions _ more than 40 percent
_ had been left vacant by Bush as of early August. It said it
appeared ``a significant portion of the government is on automatic
pilot.''
   The Democratic Study Group said the vacancies include five
assistant secretaries of education, a deputy attorney general, and
an undersecretary of state as well as the commerce post.
   The White House has complained that its nominees were facing
slow-going in the Democratic-controlled Senate.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine last week said
Bush had no grounds to complain because he ``has failed to make
nominations for nearly half of the full-time positions in executive
departments and independent agencies which require Senate
confirmation.''
   Untermeyer said there is ``always'' about a 12 percent at the top
of the executive branch as people resign, retire, move on or out of
their office for other reasons.
   ``I describe (my) job as rather like painting the Golden Gate
Bridge: once you finish it, you have to start in at the other end
and start painting it again,'' said Untermeyer.
   He scoffed at the impression left by the critics ``that the Bush
administration (is) somehow still in the starting blocks, that it
was Gulliver tied down by strings of red tapes. This is not true.
   ``This administration has been enormously, even historically
successful in establishing itself. And when faced with a Congress
that is in the hands of the opposition, it is most impressive,'' the
Bush assistant said.
   The 73rd female presidential appointee was Margaret Machol, who
Bush said he will nominate to be a commissioner of the Commodity
Futures Trading Corporation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1801EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-OaklandSchools     09-14 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oakland Schools,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Rocked by Fiscal Crisis, Mismanagement, Theft Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oakland's school district has been plagued
by charges of corruption and thievery and faces a fiscal crisis that
could force it to accept a $10 million bailout and a state-appointed
overseer.
   The California Assembly on Thursday approved the bailout measure
and sent it to the governor for signing. If approved, Oakland would
become the state's first district taken over by the state without
the school board's approval.
   In the past six months, police have arrested eight school
employees on charges ranging from grand theft to forgery; the entire
seven-member school board has been subpoenaed by a county grand
jury; and a three-month newspaper investigation uncovered a
Mafia-style patronage system allegedly run by top officials known as
``the family.''
   In addition, the district has been unable to hire a
superintendent to take over stewardship of California's
fifth-largest school district since the previous chief administrator
left in December.
   Angry residents, responding to the turmoil, have launched a
recall drive to oust school board members.
   The district, with a $14 million deficit in the current $228
million budget, is teetering on the verge of bankruptcy. The school
board on Wednesday approved a financing plan that uses school
property as collateral, but state schools chief Bill Honig and
Alameda County schools Superintendent William Berck oppose the
arrangement as fiscally unstable.
   Honig called the budget plan ``hokey,'' and said district
mismanagement has created problems that are now ``bursting out all
over.''
   ``Nobody's running the show,'' he said. ``They have no long-term
plan to get out of the problems. They need fiscal policies, they
need personnel policies and they need management policies.''
   State Assemblyman Elihu Harris sponsored the legislation to
provide a $10 million loan and put in place a state monitor to
oversee the district's financial operations and make sure they
develop and adhere to a long-term plan.
   ``These are not problems that just surfaced in Oakland,'' Harris
said Thursday. ``Some have been around for 15 or 16 years. If the
problems were new, I'd suggest they could be solved internally, but
they're not new.''
   More than 50,000 residents signed a petition in support of
Harris' proposed law, now awaiting Gov. George Deukmejian's
signature.
   As the crisis grows _ police estimate as many as 50 district
employees may be arrested before their investigation is completed _
worried parents are enrolling their children in private schools in
record numbers.
   Critics blame top leaders for the crisis in the 50,000-student
district. They say a loose-knit system of close friends working to
protect each other's jobs has eroded authority and cleared the way
for illegal activity.
   Several school officials, many of whom will speak only on the
condition of anonymity, say senior School Board member Darlene
Lawson is at the center of the alleged patronage system.
   Lawson, who did not return telephone calls seeking comment
Thursday, has denied that she heads ``the family'' and has accused
critics of launching a racist drive to purge the district of many
black administrators.
   The first-ever grand jury probe of the schools began in 1984, one
year after a black majority was elected to the board for the first
time, Lawson wrote in The Tribune of Oakland following the
newspaper's two-day report.
   Lawson, who is black, said educational problems have been ignored
as politicians pursue ``an elitist and undemocratic political
agenda.''
   Honig described the district's crisis as ``just a sick
situation,'' and rejected the charge of racism.
   ``The last refuge of scoundrels ... is the false claim of
racism,'' he said. ``Nobody wants to take over Oakland. We've got
enough to do. They should do their jobs. ... Eventually the people
there who are claiming a plot are going to have to realize that they
are the problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NORAD     09-14 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NORAD,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Fixing NORAD Problems, GAO Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has moved toward correcting
communications problems in the system responsible for alerting the
United States and Canada if North America is under attack, but
deficiencies still remain, says a report released Thursday.
   The General Accounting Office last November reported on five of
29 serious problems that if ignored, could affect the Communications
System Segment Replacement Program, which relays messages from
various missile, air and space sensor systems to mission centers at
the Cheyenne Mountain Air Force Station.
   The station, located in Colorado Springs, Colo., is a data
processing and communications center designed to monitor about
10,000 man-made objects in space, provide warnings of any military
attack in space and protect satellites from attack.
   According to the GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, the Air
Force has taken steps to correct three of the deficiencies, delayed
action on a fourth and is in the process of obtaining information on
the fifth problem before resolving the issue.
   ``The lack of uniform wiring standards, cabling congestion and
the need for a standardized message set are being resolved,'' the
GAO said. ``However, selection and implementation of a standard
communication protocol and use of consistent message loading
assumptions have not been resolved.''
   A message set is the form in which data is transmitted from the
sensors, or radars, to computer subsystems. A communication protocol
is a set of rules that govern communications among computer systems.
Message loading assumptions involve the number of messages a
subsystem is capable of processing.
   The system is part of the North American Aerospace Defense
Command, or NORAD, which is responsible for alerting the United
States and Canada if North America is under air, missile or space
attack.
   The GAO is recommending that if the Defense Acquisition Board
advises Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to continue development of the
program despite the absence of ``sound technical approach ... for
correcting critical deficiencies, the board should clearly justify
its rationale.''
   The GAO also said that Cheney should not obligate fiscal 1990
appropriations for the program until the board completes its review
and submits a report.
   Officials at NORAD had no immediate comment on the report.
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee on defense, requested the GAO study.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-SovietJews     09-14 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Jews,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Leaders Press for Release of 400 Soviet Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of five American Jewish groups urged
the State Department Thursday to press the Soviet Union for the
release of some 400 Jewish families who have been denied exit
permits.
   The delegation gave Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger lists of Jewish ``refuseniks'' who were turned down more
than 10 years ago and those who were denied permits over the last
decade.
   Shoshana S. Cardin, chairman of the National Conference on Soviet
Jewry, said Eagleburger gave assurances the issue would be high on
the agenda when Secretary of State James A. Baker III meets in
Jackson Hole, Wyo., Sept. 22-23 with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze.
   ``It was a very productive meeting,'' Cardin said of the
45-minute session with Eagleburger. Officials of the Conference of
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations, B'nai B'rith, the
Anti-Defamation League and the National Jewish Community Relations
Advisory Council also attended.
   Cardin said that, of 12 Jewish cases raised by Baker at a meeting
with Shevardnadze in May, four were subsequently allowed to leave
the country. She called that number ``very disturbing.''
