<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1811EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-DavisCancer     09-14 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Davis Cancer,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sammy Davis Jr. Diagnosed With Throat Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Sammy Davis Jr. has been diagnosed
with throat cancer and will begin radiation therapy next week, his
publicist said Thursday.
   An abnormality was detected during Davis' annual medical
examination and was diagnosed by Dr. Joseph Sugerman as a carcinoma
of the throat, Arnold Lipsman, a Davis spokesman, said in a
statement.
   Davis, 63, underwent reconstructive hip surgery in November 1985,
and has been on tour for more than a year with Frank Sinatra and
Liza Minnelli in concerts billed as ``the ultimate event.''
   Lipsman quoted Dr. Sugerman as saying, ``Mr. Davis' condition is
localized and a full and complete recovery following treatment is
expected.''
   Davis is expected to complete his current engagement at Harrah's
Tahoe hotel and casino Sunday, but he will not appear with Sinatra
and Miss Minnelli at concerts scheduled for October in Toronto, the
Washington, D.C., area and Charlotte, N.C.
   ``Liza and Frank will continue the tour, except for one
concert,'' said Susan Reynolds, a Los Angeles publicist for the
``Frank, Liza &amp; Sammy'' tour. An Oct. 3 benefit concert set at the
Boston Garden has been canceled.
   She said Sinatra and Minnelli were unavailable for comment, ``but
their hearts are with Sammy. They speak frequently together by
telephone.''
   Davis, a singer, dancer and actor, was born to vaudevillians
Elvera and Sammy Davis in 1925, appeared on stage as a youngster and
braved bigotry for decades as he toured the country.
   For years he was a familiar member of Hollywood's ``Rat Pack'' of
entertainers, which included Dean Martin, Peter Lawford and Sinatra.
   Beginning in the 1950s, he released a series of hit songs,
including duets with Sinatra and Martin, that culminated in ``The
Candy Man'' in 1972. He also recorded ``Something's Gotta Give'' in
1955 and ``I've Gotta Be Me'' in 1969.
</TEXT>
