<FIRST>r w AM-ElectedHispanics     09-14 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elected Hispanics,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Number of Elected Hispanics Jumps 12.6 Percent From 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hispanics continue to make impressive electoral
gains at every level of government, according to the president of an
organization that found the number of elected Latinos nationwide
jumped 12.6 percent from 1988.
   In a study released Thursday, the National Association of Latino
Elected and Appointed Officials said 3,783 Hispanic elected
officials hold office in 37 states.
   Texas leads the country, with 1,693 elected officials who account
for 44.75 percent of the total, followed by New Mexico, with 647
Hispanic elected officials who account for 17.1 percent of the total.
   Despite their gains, however, elected Hispanic officials still
account for less than 1 percent of all elected officials nationwide,
the organization said, while Latinos account for 8 percent of the
population.
   ``Civic participation is the key to economic and political
advancement in the Latino community,'' said Rep. Solomon Ortiz,
D-Texas., a board member of the group. ``The 1990 census and the
reapportionment that follows will play a vital role in Latino
electoral representation for the next decade.''
   The Hispanic group found there are 10 Hispanic members of
Congress _ four from Texas, three from California, and one each from
New York, Florida and New Mexico.
   The study said there are 128 state legislators, 1,340 school
board members, 1,178 municipal officials, 246 mayors, and one
governor _ Bob Martinez of Florida.
   ``Hispanics continue to make impressive electoral gains at every
level of office,'' said Rep. Edward Roybal, D-Calif., the group's
board president. ``A barometer of an ethnic group's integration into
the political system and society can be measured through their
number of elected officials.''
   National Director Harry Pachon said that while growth continues
in such traditionally Hispanic states as Texas, California and
Florida, Latinos are also making gains elsewhere, including
Illinois, New Jersey and Washington.
   Elected Hispanic women account for 19.7 percent of the Hispanic
office holders, the study said.
</TEXT>
