<FIRST>u w AM-SmokingBan     09-14 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoking Ban,1st Ld-Writethru,a0660,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate All But Approves Wider Airline Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs `On Aug. 3 ...' to UPDATE
with comment from industry, lobbyist. Picks up 7th graf pvs `The Senate...'
Vote possible, time uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate tentatively approved a ban on
cigarette smoking on all domestic airline flights on Thursday as
outnumbered tobacco-state lawmakers abandoned their fight against
the broadened restrictions.
   On a showdown 77-21 vote, senators forced a halt to delaying
tactics their pro-smoking colleagues had hoped would wear out
advocates of the ban and lead to a compromise. The Senate then
formally adopted the restrictions on a unanimous voice vote.
   ``We didn't undertake that vote in the belief we could defeat''
the proposed ban, Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., who fought the proposal,
conceded afterward.
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., who sponsored the ban proposal and
who cited health concerns about lingering cigarette smoke in airline
cabins, said, ``The issue itself carried the day.''
   The measure was part of an $11.9 billion spending bill for next
year's transportation programs that was nearing final passage.
   On Aug. 3, the House approved legislation making permanent the
current smoking ban on flights of two hours or less. The two
chambers will have to hammer out a compromise before sending it to
President Bush for his signature.
   Spokesman Gary Miller of the Tobacco Institute, the cigarette
industry trade group, predicted that the two chambers would produce
``a less extreme piece of legislation.''
   But Jo Ellen Deutsch, who as lobbyist for the Association of
Flight Attendants worked for the restrictions, said she thought the
total ban would get final congressional approval.
   ``The Senate showed very clearly that they do worry about the
health of people who come in contact with cigarette smoke,'' she
said.
   The Senate version would extend the ban to all U.S. routes 95
days after the bill becomes law. The current restrictions, which
cover four-fifths of all flights, will otherwise expire next April.
   As under current law, passengers caught smoking would be subject
to $1,000 fines and people found to have disabled smoke detectors in
aircraft restrooms would face penalties of up to $2,000. Paper
stored in lavatories makes that part of an airliner the riskiest
spot for a fire.
   Tobacco-state senators, seeing the numbers were against them, had
said Wednesday that they would accept a permanent smoking ban on
routes of two hours or less. When Lautenberg and his supporters
refused to make the concession, ban opponents threatened to use
procedural delays to slow the Senate's work to a crawl.
   That effort was ended by the 77-21 vote. Shortly afterward,
another procedural vote went 65-34 for ban supporters and the battle
was over.
   Opponents of the ban had argued that there is no scientific proof
that cigarette fumes harm the health of non-smokers, and that the
smoke is merely one of many chemicals adrift in the recirculated air
inside airliners. They called on supporters to await a
Transportation Department study on airliner air quality expected by
early next year.
   They also said the restriction would hurt tobacco growers.
   But supporters cited several studies concluding that non-smokers
risk cancer and other diseases by inhaling cigarette smoke, and said
there was no reason to wait for a total prohibition.
   ``The American people are overwhelmingly in support of this
suspension of smoking on airliners,'' Lautenberg said.
   The bill allows $11.9 billion in new spending for transportation,
and the expenditure of $15.9 billion in previously collected fuel
and passenger taxes.
   The measure includes $12.2 billion for highway projects, $7.3
billion for aviation programs and $3 billion for mass transit
assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
