<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Shooting 1stLd-Writethru a0714 09-14 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman Kills Unarmed Policeman, Wounds Another Near Manchester</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details of police not at station
to arrest Hughes, attribution on suicide reports. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman shot and killed an unarmed
policeman and wounded another at a highway service station Thursday,
and hours later the attacker was found dead with a single gunshot in
the head, police said.
   News reports said the gunman committed suicide.
   The attack came after the police apparently made a routine stop
at a gas station near Manchester, 164 miles northwest of London.
   The gunman, identified as Anthony Kenneth Hughes, walked over to
police Inspector Raymond Codling, 49, and shot him twice at close
range in the head and chest, police said. The other officer, Sgt.
James Bowden, 45, was shot in the leg, but was recovering in the
hospital.
   There was no immediate report on the motive for the attack.
   Manchester police said the officers were checking the station
because it had been used in the past as a resting place for
fugitives. However, the officers had not been seeking to arrest
Hughes, police said.
   The officers were not carrying weapons, like most British police
officers.
   The Police Federation rejected calls for police to carry guns.
   ``The British police force are proud of being unarmed, and we
would not want to be armed,'' said chairman Alan Eastwood.
   The killing brought to 21 the number of police officers slain
while on duty in England, Scotland and Wales since 1980.
   Immediately after the attack, police began a nationwide hunt for
the killer, who escaped by motorcycle from the station's parking lot.
   The suspect, dressed in a black leather motorcycle suit, appeared
at Barnsley, 30 miles east of Manchester, and asked to see a Roman
Catholic priest who was away at a funeral, police said. He then went
inside a garage at the priest's home, they said.
   Superintendent Terry Swann of Barnsley police said the headmaster
of a neighboring primary school, who had heard of the shootings and
was approached by the gunman, became suspicious and called the
police.
   Barnsley police were issued with guns and evacuated the school.
As they surrounded the garage, a single shot was heard and the man
was found dead inside with a handgun nearby, Swann said.
   Manchester police said Hughes, 42, had served 15 years in prison
for robbery, burglary and rape convictions. He had lived with his
stepfather in Manchester.
</TEXT>
