<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-14 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain, Rain Everywhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms fell Thursday over the eastern
two-thirds of the nation, and unseasonably cool weather in the
Midwest and the Southwest broke or tied temperature records up to 44
years old in seven cities.
   Southern Texas had locally heavy overnight and morning rain,
including 6 inches west of Rio Grande City, that caused local
flooding.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell in southern New England, New
York, Pennsylvania, from New Jersey to eastern Florida, Ohio,
Indiana, Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi and Louisiana, Kansas and
Missouri.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 2{
inches in Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio, and 1 1-3 inch in Jackson,
Tenn., and more than an inch in Dyersburg, Tenn.
   The cold front that brought rain to the nation's midsection also
dropped temperatures to record levels.
   In Raton, N.M., the mercury dipped to 30 degrees, 4 degrees lower
than the record set in 1945. Records also were set in Norfolk, Neb.
(35 degrees, 36 in 1945); Goodland, Kan. (38, 39 in 1961); Amarillo,
Texas (40, 44 in 1945); and Midland, Texas (51, 52 in 1975). Records
were tied in Pueblo, Colo. (36 degrees, 1945) and Albuquerque (46,
1967).
   The low temperature for the lower 48 states was 19 degrees in
Gunnison, Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged
from 50 degrees in Houlton, Maine, to 104 degrees in Palm Springs,
Calif.
   The forecast for Friday called for showers and thunderstorms from
Maine to Georgia, the Appalachians, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys,
Alabama, Mississippi, the Florida Panhandle and southeast Louisiana.
   Temperatures were expected to remain unseasonably low from
Illinois to northwest Texas and along the northern Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 60s from northern New
England to inland New York and in central Oklahoma, near 90 degrees
in Florida, in the 90s to near 105 degrees through the desert
Southwest and in the 70s and 80s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
