<FIRST>r w AM-WorldSugar     09-14 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Sugar,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Sugar Forecast Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World sugar production is estimated at 106.75
million metric tons in 1989-90, down 504,000 tons from a previous
forecast in June, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Despite the decline from earlier prospects, the new crop is
expected to be at a record level and nearly 1.3 million tons more
than in 1988-89, the department's Economic Research Service said in
its report.
   However, global sugar consumption is expected to rise 1 percent
to 108.72 million tons, exceeding production for the fifth straight
year. That would put world stockpiles at their lowest level since
1980-81, the report said.
   World raw sugar prices, Contract No. 11, delivered to ships at
Caribbean ports, rose from an average of 9.7 cents per pound in
January to 14 cents in August, the report said. World prices of
refined sugar, Contract No. 5 at European ports, increased from 12.6
cents in Janurary to 22.5 cents in August.
   ``The run-up reflects unexpected purchases by the Soviets,
prospects of heavy buying from India, and delays in Brazil's
exports,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
