<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     09-14 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa May Tour Poland to Drum Up Gov't Support; U.S. Aid Doubled</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Thursday
he will likely tour Poland in an effort to persuade Poles to give
the new non-Communist government the time it needs to combat
economic ills.
   In Washington, President Bush announced he will double to $100
million next year's U.S. food aid to Poland. Bush has been under
congressional pressure to increase aid in order to bolster Polish
reforms.
   The food aid is separate from a $119 million package of economic
assistance to Poland previously announced by the White House.
   In his remarks, Walesa rejected a suggestion that Poles might
prove unwilling to accept the hardships imposed by radical economic
reform.
   ``There is nothing to be given up, for the market is already
empty,'' he said in a reference to Poland's severe shortages of food
and other basic supplies. Long lines for many commodities are common.
   However, Walesa said there is a need to repeat his appeal for a
six-month moratorium on strikes to give the new government a chance
to put its policies to work.
   ``There is a need to talk and give arguments,'' he said during a
news conference at Solidarity headquarters in the Baltic port of
Gdansk.
   ``That is why I will probably now make a tour around Poland,
meeting with people ... talking directly,'' Walesa said. ``Polish
society is bright and if issues are explained well ... it will
understand what Poland needs.''
   Thursday was the second day in office for the ministers of the
new Solidarity-controlled government.
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a Solidarity newspaper editor
until he took on his historic mission Aug. 24, held only one
publicly reported meeting Thursday. It was a session with Austrian
vice-chancellor Josef Riegler.
   Mazowiecki, who had been an adviser to Walesa, is leading the
East bloc's first non-Communist government since the Communists
consolidated power after World War II.
   Many of the new government's plans to introduce Western-style
economic reform to combat triple-digit inflation, its $39 billion
foreign debt and other economic ills are likely to further undermine
a lagging standard of living, Mazowiecki has said.
   The new political leadership has declared that the sacrifices
will be needed for long-term gains, but they are clearly worried
about public patience and support.
   No details were offered on the trip suggested by Walesa.
   On two previous occasions this year, he has used his tremendous
personal influence with Poles.
   He traveled around Poland to urge workers not to strike while
talks were under way last spring that resulted in the
re-legalization of his labor movement.
   He also made stops around the country to advocate support for
Solidarity campaigns during the unprecedented democratic
parliamentary elections in June. Solidarity won a sweeping victory
and then successfully bargained to lead the government.
   In his comments Thursday, Walesa also looked ahead, saying
political divisions between Solidarity and the Communist Party are
now following ``a new confrontational model ... not by means of
force but a peaceful confrontation.''
   ``After pluralism's victory, there will not be a need for a
confrontational structure,'' he said, predicting the advent of other
political parties and other trade unions.
   The official PAP news agency reported Thursday that Communist
parliament deputies have put forward a proposal to revise the law on
political parties to create the legal conditions for founding
parties and establishing their equal rights.
   In his remarks, Walesa also said he wants to ``internationalize''
the Polish economy, turning to countries like France and the
Scandinavian nations as economic allies.
   U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher will begin a
three-day visit to Poland on Tuesday as part of a trip that also
includes stops in Hungary, Western Europe and Asia.
</TEXT>
