<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     09-14 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Criticize Administration Silence On Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several lawmakers accused the Bush
administration Thursday of failing to take a strong enough position
against the Khmer Rouge faction in Cambodia, with one declaring:
``I'm angry as hell about this.''
   When the Khmer Rouge, headed by Pol Pot, controlled Cambodia in
the early 1970s, their forces killed as many as 2 million people, a
devastation portrayed in the well-known movie, ``The Killing
Fields.''
   Rep. Chester G. Atkins, D-Mass., told a top State Department
official that the United States was not vocal enough about opposing
the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge at an international conference on
Cambodia held in Paris over the summer.
   The conference, held to work out a political solution for the
future of Cambodia, foundered because various factions could not
agree.
   In the United States, there is increasing concern about the
prospect of continuing conflict in Cambodia if the Vietnamese
occupation troops withdraw _ as Hanoi has pledged _ from the
neighboring country at the end of the month.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs subcommittee on Asian and Pacific Affairs, said the failure
of the conference and the withdrawal of troops ``creates the very
real possibility that the genocidal Khmer Rouge could battle its way
back to power in Phnom Penh.''
   Richard Solomon, the assistant secretary of State for East Asian
and Pacific Affairs, told the hearing that the Bush administration
wants ``no role for the Khmer Rouge in a future Cambodian
government.''
   The Unites States would like to see an interim Cambodian
government headed by its ally, former Cambodian leader Prince
Sihanouk. Washington provides open and secret aid to Sihanouk.
   Despite the U.S. position on the Khmer Rouge, the United States
agreed with Sihanouk, China and Asian allies that the changes for
long-term peace in Cambodia would be enhanced if the Khmer Rouge
were part of a coalition government, Solomon said.
   ``In other words, total exclusiion of the Khmer Rouge is seen by
those most directly involved as a sure formula for civil warfare,
while their inclusion holds out some prospect that the struggle can
be contained within a political process monitored by the
international community,'' he said.
   Atkins and other attacked the administration for not being tough
enough on the Khmer Rouge. ``I'm angry as hell about this,'' Atkins
said, complaining of the U.S. position.
   He accused the Bush administration of remaining silent about the
Khmer Rouge's past activities in conference working sessions, and
said it was ``part of a pattern'' in the administration of publicly
professing distrust of the Khmer Rouge, but not carrying through
with actions.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, the subcommittee's ranking Republican,
said the United States ``does not have the luxury of recusing
itself'' on moral issues, such as the past genocidal practices of
the Khmer Rouge.
   Leach suggested Pol Pot be bought before an international court
charged with war crimes.
   At Solarz' request, the hearing was moved behind closed doors so
Solomon could explain the U.S. position on the Khmer Rouge.
   Solarz acknowledged the United States sometimes had to make
alliances with unsavory groups, such as the U.S.-Soviet pact with
Joseph Stalin in World War II. The two were allied against Adolf
Hilter.
   At the same time, he pressed Solomon on whether the United States
characterized the Khmer Rouge as having practiced genocide under the
Senate-ratified genocide treaty. The Khmer Rouge object to the word.
   Solomon said that at the Paris conference, the United States
supported language referring to the group's ``genocidal practices.''
</TEXT>
