<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-IMFIncrease     09-14 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF Increase,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of IMF Asks Doubling of Fund's Assets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the International Monetary Fund
said Thursday that IMF resources need to be doubled so that the
multinational lending agency can provide more help to poor countries.
   The request by IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus will likely
be the main topic of discussion when finance officials from 151
nations gather in Washington later this month for the annual
meetings of the IMF and its sister organization, the World Bank.
   The IMF is owned by the 151 countries with the largest share,
$23.6 billion, coming from the United States. The U.S. share is out
of total IMF resources of $118 billion.
   The IMF resources, called quotas, are provided by member
countries, which pledge to keep a certain level of their financial
reserves with the IMF.
   In making his request, Camdessus said that 19 of the 22 members
of the IMF board had indicated that they supported an increase of at
least 66 percent, but he said a boost in resources of at least 80
percent was needed to keep the IMF from being forced to ``limit the
access of member countries to our help.''
   The IMF and the World Bank have been key players in the Bush
administration's new debt reduction strategy unveiled by Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady on March 10.
   The Brady plan seeks to reduce the $1.3 trillion Third World debt
burden by getting commercial banks to voluntarily write off a
portion of the debt in exchange from guarantees from the two lending
agencies that a portion of the reduced debt will be repaid.
   In another development Wednesday, John Reed, chairman of
Citicorp, the country's largest bank, said that he was concerned
that the Brady debt plan was being viewed solely as an effort reduce
debt at the exclusion of new loans from commercial banks.
   ``Our purpose, after all, is to restore economic and financial
health to these economies _ which are important markets for the
United States _ not to cut them off totally from the banking
system,'' Reed said at a news conference in Washington.
   Some countries have already endorsed a doubling of IMF resources,
but some U.S. officials have said they are not yet convinced that
any increase is needed.
   In recent years the fund's money has gone for new loans to Third
World countries, many of them heavily in debt, in return for pledges
of policy changes to put them in better financial condition.
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., said on Wednesday that Congress would
likely give a cool reception to any request from the president
unless the administration agreed to boost government resources by
raising raxes.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, said that while Congress would initially
be reluctant, it would eventually go along with the administration.
   Critics of the IMF have been questioning the value of its efforts.
   Jeffrey D. Sachs, professor of international trade at Harvard
University, said that the IMF has a record of failure in debtor
countries.
   He said that of 39 or so countries that have been wrestling with
debt problems, few have been able to meet their obligations without
undermining their national prosperity.
   The World Bank announced, meanwhile, that Afghanistan has
restored itself to good standing with a payment of $755,000.
   It was made ineligible for new loans in June because it was
overdue on about $26 million worth of debt. Afghanistan owes the
bank about $79 million on 20 low-interest loans amounting to $230
million that it received in past years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1901EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     09-14 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike by Azerbaijani Rail Workers Hits Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pravda reported on Thursday that a walkout by
Azerbaijani rail workers to back up nationalist and ethnic demands
has cut fuel supplies to adjacent Armenia and left ambulances,
trucks and cars without gas.
   It said the lack of fuel and supplies posed a particular threat
in northern Armenia, where reconstruction is under way of cities
wrecked by the Dec. 7 earthquake that killed 25,000 people.
   ``The coming winter is putting people under the real threat of
being without shelter,'' Pravda said.
   The party newspaper quoted Armenia's deputy premier, Y.
Khodzhamiryan, as saying, ``Because of the halt on the Azerbaijan
railroad, Armenia is practically in a state of economic blockade.''
   He told the paper that the southern republic of Armenia gets 87
percent of its freight, including fuel supplies, from Azerbaijan.
   The two Caucasus mountain republics have been in a fierce dispute
since February over who should control Nagorno-Karabakh region,
which lies in Azerbaijan but has a population that is 75 percent
ethnic Armenian.
   The Azerbaijani People's Front political movement listed as one
demand in calling a general strike last week that Azerbaijan
reassert control over Nagorno-Karabakh in place of direct rule from
Moscow.
   The strike was called off last Monday. It was not among any
stated aim of the walkout that supplies to Armenia be cut.
   The Armenian-Azerbaijani dispute has led to violence that killed
about 100 people since last year and forced hundreds of thousands to
flee their homes.
   Soviet newspapers say the situation remains tense and that the
region is a powder keg.
   Pravda said the 19-mile road from Goris in Armenia to the
Nagorno-Karabakh boundary is so dangerous it is ``impossible to pass
even with a military escort.''
   On Wednesday, the national youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda
said few cars were operating on even the main streets of Yerevan,
the Armenian capital, and large gaps intervened in public transport
service.
   Pravda said even ambulances could not fill up at service stations.
</TEXT>
