<FIRST>r w AM-DC-Police     09-14 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-Police,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate OKs Bill for More DC Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, responding to a growing wave of
drug-related violence in the nation's capital, Thursday approved a
bill to finance the hiring of 700 additional District of Columbia
police officers.
   The $23 million package, already approved by the House, comes on
top of the city's plan to hire 300 extra officers. The two measures
will bring the force to about 5,000 officers.
   ``We need to send a signal that we are retaking the streets of
Washington,'' Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., said after an
appropriations committee hearing Tuesday. ``This will not solve the
drug problem, but we certainly hope that it will help.''
   The move, which passed without debate on a voice vote, likely
will provide some relief to officers who have been working 12-hour
shifts since August to help combat drug-related violence.
   In March, most officers were assigned to six-day weeks, with
officers from all parts of the city assigned to patrol drug-infested
neighborhoods on their sixth tour of duty. That plan was abandoned
when the crime rate slowed, but the 12-hour shift plan was created
when the crime wave rose again.
   Police have blamed crack cocaine for an explosion of drug-related
violence in Washington.
   Through Thursday, 318 people had been killed in the District of
Columbia in 1989, compared with 228 at the same time last year. A
record 372 people were killed in the district in 1988.
   The money to hire extra officers will come from special use of a
lump-sum water and sewer payment the federal government provides the
city. The city will be reimbursed for those funds by directly
billing federal agencies in the city.
</TEXT>
