<FIRST>r w AM-Farmers-Deduction     09-14 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farmers-Deduction,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Saves Health Insurance Deduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee reversed
itself Thursday, voting to keep for at least two years a tax
deduction for health insurance premiums paid by farmers and other
self-employed people.
   The committee voted to kill the 25 percent deduction earlier this
year because of the cost of the 3-year-old tax break, $2.3 billion
for the next five years.
   However, Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., won approval of an amendment
Thursday to extend the deduction for two years and make up for the
lost revenue by limiting a tax break used by companies bought
through leveraged buyouts.
   ``The 25 percent tax deduction is very important to farmers and
others on Main Street who are unincorporated,'' Dorgan said.
   The amendment to a budget reconciliation bill was approved on a
voice vote.
   Dorgan had originally proposed increasing the health-insurance
deduction to 100 percent.
   A coalition of organizations as diverse as the American Farm
Bureau Federation, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and Amway contended
it was unfair to allow corporations to deduct all their health
insurance costs while self-employed people can write off only a
portion.
   Administration officials argued against extending the tax break,
saying it represented ``a significant revenue loss'' and doesn't
provide sufficient incentive for uninsured self-employed people to
buy health policies.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., dropped his opposition to the tax
break when Dorgan came up with a way to make up for the lost
revenue, about $600,000 over the next two years.
   Dorgan's amendment would prevent companies acquired in a
leveraged buyout from going back to previous years and claiming
operating losses because of their new, higher interest payments.
   Dorgan says he expects the Senate to approve extending the tax
break.
   Sen. Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., is sponsoring a similar proposal
in the Senate.
</TEXT>
