<FIRST>r a AM-RacialAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0636 09-14 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifth Suspect Indicted on Murder Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with demonstration, details, comments
from suspect's lawyer. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Four other...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fifth young white man was indicted on murder
charges Thursday for his alleged role in the fatal attack on a black
teen-ager, as about 150 black youths gathered outside the court and
angrily shouted epithets.
   James Patino, 24, of the borough of Brooklyn was charged in the
19-count indictment with one count of second-degree murder, one
count of fifth degree manslaughter and several counts of riot,
assault, unlawful imprisonment, menacing, aggravated harassment, and
criminal possession of a deadly weapon.
   Patino, who remained free on $75,000 bail, said nothing during
his brief appearance before Criminal Court Judge Seymour Gerschwer
and walked quickly out of the court room with his lawyer.
   A short time later, about 150 black youths, many of them students
on lunch break from a high school next to the courthouse, pursued
another of the suspects in the attack and his lawyer as they left
the courthouse.
   The crowd chanted ``Fight the Power'' _ the title of a rap song
from ``Do The Right Thing,'' Spike Lee's recent movie about racial
tension in Brooklyn _ and yelled obscenities at police as the pair
climbed into a police car and sped away.
   Several rocks were hurled, striking a police officer and a
television reporter. No one was seriously hurt and there were no
arrests, the police said.
   Patino was charged with murder because he exhibited ``a depraved
indifference to human life'' and ``recklessly engaged in conduct
which created a grave risk of death,'' the indictment said.
   His lawyer, Abraham Jaros, disputed the charges, saying ``It's
difficult to understand how a young man, simply because he was
present on the street, can be charged with murder.''
   The suspect targeted by the demonstrators, Charles Stressler, 21,
was arrested but has not been indicted in the Aug. 23 attack and
also appeared at Thursday's hearing. Gerschwer warned prosecutors he
would dismiss the cases against Stressler and another suspect,
Steven Curreri, 18, if indictments were not returned by Oct. 16.
   Four other young men have been previously indicted on murder
charges. All but one remain free on bail. Two other young men have
been arrested but have not been indicted.
   The victim, 16-year-old Yusuf Hawkins, was shot when he and three
friends went to the predominantly white Bensonhurst section of
Brooklyn to look at an advertised car.
