<FIRST>r a AM-OralRoberts     09-14 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oral Roberts,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oral Roberts' Hospital Closes Emergency Room</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The emergency room at Oral Roberts' City of
Faith hospital closed Thursday, marking the first step in the
ministry's plans to shutter the hospital and a medical school to
help pay $25 million in debts.
   Roberts announced Wednesday the hospital will be closed by the
end of the year and the Oral Roberts University School of Medicine
will close after the current school year. He also said his home,
four other ministry-owned homes and an 832-unit student housing
complex would be sold.
   The action is necessary to help pay $25 million in debt, Roberts
said, so that ministry officials can concentrate on keeping his
4,300-student university financially secure.
   Dr. Larry Edwards, vice president for health affairs at the
ministry, said closing the emergency room at the City of Faith
Medical and Research Center will be the first of many steps taken to
shut the 777-bed hospital.
   The city's five other medical centers will have no problem
handling the patient load from the City of Faith, which has never
reached its state-approved capacity of 294, and in absorbing its 600
employees, Tulsa hospital officials said.
   ``There is a need for qualified medical personnel, such as nurses
and physical therapists, in Tulsa,'' said Steve Reynolds, spokesman
for St. John Medical Center in Tulsa.
   Harry Salem, vice president of the ministry and brother-in-law of
Roberts' evangelist son Richard, said it was business as usual
Thursday at the ministry's 400-acre south Tulsa complex.
   ``They all got up this morning and went to work,'' Salem said.
``Oral went to the office. Richard got on television (for his daily
religious show) to pray for the people. They're going to keep on
ministering.''
   Few people familiar with recent events at the ministry were
surprised by the plan to eliminate the core of the 71-year-old
faith-healer's medical ministry.
   At least one ORU medical student voiced frustration after hearing
of Roberts' plan to close the medical school.
   ``Yeah, I feel like they jerked me around a little bit, but
they're doing what they can,'' said third-year student Joseph
Scoggins.
   Scoggins and other juniors at the medical school will be hit the
hardest by the closing. Edwards said the 27 seniors at the school
will graduate in May and the remaining 120 students will be allowed
to transfer to other medical schools.
   Freshmen and sophomores should be able to transfer to continue
their basic science curriculum, but third-year students typically in
the middle of their clinical rotations could have more problems
transferring, Edwards said.
   ``We will do our best to help them,'' Edwards said.
   Mark Swadener, chief fiscal officer for the Oral Roberts
Evangelical Association, said the ministry's for-profit real estate
company will search for a tenant for the 60-story City of Faith and
the two adjacent buildings.
   ``We'd like to find a tenant, a lead tenant _ a hospital _ to
move into the City of Faith,'' he said.
   Swadener said Bethany Real Estate Inc. also will be searching for
a buyer for the homes of Roberts, his son, and his daughter Roberta,
who also works for the ministry. Two other homes used by ministry
officials also will be sold, he said.
   As for where Oral and Richard Roberts will live if their homes
are sold, the elder evangelist said he really hasn't given that much
thought.
   ``I don't know. The building hasn't sold yet. All I know is I
slept in my bed last night,'' he said.
</TEXT>
