<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     09-14 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinista Foe Tells of Offer to Have Chamorro Slayers Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MGA1</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DORALISA PILARTE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main opposition presidential
candidate, Violetta Barrios de Chamorro, said Thursday that a
Sandinista Cabinet member once offered to have her husband's
suspected killers assassinated.
   She told foreign reporters the incident involved Interior
Minister Tomas Borge and took place while she was a member of the
junta that took power after dictator Anastasio Somoza was overthrown
in 1979.
   The 1978 killing of La Prensa newspaper publisher Pedro Joaquin
Chamorro by gunmen believed to be in Somoza's pay helped ignite the
Sandinista revolution.
   ``Tomas Borge came to my house ... when I became part of the
junta,'' said Mrs. Chamorro, the presidential nominee of an
opposition coalition of 14 parties taking part in elections next
February.
   ``He told me, `Why don't you give me permission to assassinate
all those boys?''' referring to the suspects in Chamorro's killing.
   ``I said, `Look Tomas, I am not an assassin,''' Mrs. Chamorro
said.
   No immediate response came to Mrs. Chamorro's accusation.
Thursday was Independence Day in Nicaragua. People who answered the
telephone at the Interior Ministry press office said Capt. Nelba
Blandon was the only person authorized to talk and was not in.
   On other subjects, Mrs. Chamorro denied she was merely a front
candidate for the opposition or that her newspaper publishes
CIA-inspired articles. She said demobilization of rebels fighting
the government should be made ``along with democratization.''
   Central America's five presidents signed a peace accord on Aug. 7
that calls for the 12,000-man rebel force now in southern Honduras,
near the Nicaraguan border, to be dismantled by mid-December. The
rebels are known as Contras.
   In exchange, President Daniel Ortega moved national elections up
to Feb. 25 and promised that campaigning and voting will be free and
fair, with no restrictions on the press.
   Ortega will probably be the Sandinista National Liberation Front
candidate to face Mrs. Chamorro, publisher of the opposition
newspaper La Prensa.
   Mrs. Chamorro denied Sandinista accusations that her newspaper
recently published articles generated by the Central Intelligence
Agency. ``We don't publish articles by the CIA or by employees of
the CIA,'' she said.
   ``On the other hand, I do see articles in Barricada from the
Soviet Union,'' she added, referring to the official Sandinista
party newspaper.
   Carlos Fernando Chamorro, Mrs. Chamorro's son and director of
Barricada, did not return repeated telephone calls from The
Associated Press.
   Asked if she has forgiven her husband's killers, she replied,
``Of course I do. I am a Catholic, I don't hate, I forgive.''
   Three men and one women are serving prison terms for the
assassination.
</TEXT>
