<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Abortion-D.C.     09-14 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-D.C.,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Money Approved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, ignoring an abortion-related veto
threat, voted 56-43 Wednesday to provide more money to help the
District of Columbia fight a growing army of drug pushers and
drug-related violence.
   The chamber acted after being told the overall $3.5 billion
appropriations bill in which the money is contained is certain to be
vetoed by President Bush because it permits abortions.
   ``This bill is dead,'' Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., one of the
chamber's leading opponents of abortion, told the Senate. ``It may
be warm, but it's not breathing; it's done for.''
   Humphrey acknowleged that an amendment to deny the district the
authority to use its own money for abortions likely would be
rejected as it was when the House considered the appropriations
measure in June.
   He said he had decided not to try to remove abortion language
from the bill in the belief that Bush will veto the measure, and
that Congress would not be able to muster the two-thirds majorities
needed to override it.
   He predicted a new bill would be drafted with the offending
language removed and would ``zip right through.''
   As it stands, both House and Senate versions of the bill for the
fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 permit the district government to use
local funds to pay for abortions. The measures permit federal funds
to be used when the life of the mother is threatened or in cases of
rape or incest.
   The bill includes $23 million to hire 700 new policemen, $4.8
million to help the district courts deal with a flood of
drug-related cases, $1.3 million to expand after-school programs in
high-risk neighborhoods and $2 million to set up a program to
provide treatment on demand for pregnant drug addicts.
   The bill also included a controversial amendment that authorizes
Congress to permit religious institutions in the city to deny funds
and recognition to homosexual student groups.
   A similar amendment was included in last year's budget. However,
it was ruled unconstitutional by a federal judge.
   The two houses still must reconcile differences between their
versions of the bill.
</TEXT>
