<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Documents,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>List of Suspects Disappears from Belfast Police Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday a
confidential list of IRA suspects had disappeared, and a police
official came from England to find out how such papers slip through
the hands of provincial authorities.
   In an earlier case involving missing documents, three men were
charged on Monday with the murder of Loughlin Maginn, a 38-year-old
Roman Catholic.
   An outlawed Protestant group, the Ulster Freedom Fighters, said
Maginn was identified as a suspected member of the Irish Republican
Army in documents it claimed were leaked by security forces. The
claim was made in an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp.
   Police said the latest missing list contained names and pictures
of 12 IRA suspects and appeared to have been forcibly removed from a
locked cabinet in a Belfast police station.
   John Stevens, deputy chief constable of Cambridgeshire, was
ordered to Northern Ireland to investigate at the request of Hugh
Annesley, chief constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary. The
constabulary polices this Protestant-dominated British province.
   The police said Stevens will also look into the disappearance of
confidential information from the Ballykinlar army base in County
Down.
   The mainly Catholic IRA, outlawed on both sides of the border, is
fighting to end British rule and unite Northern Ireland with the
Irish Republic.
   Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, said the police service may be involved in the disappearances
of the papers.
   His party speaks for most of the province's Catholic minority.
