<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     09-14 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Minister Says Differences with India Ending; 19 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lanka said Thursday its differences
with India will be solved in days and Indian peacekeeping soldiers
on the island will soon declare an indefinite cease-fire in the
fight against Tamil rebels.
   Foreign Minister Ramjan Wijeratne's announcement came as
officials reported at least 19 more people dead, including a young
TV announcer, in violence connected with the radical Sinhalese
uprising against the government.
   Wijeratne, who is also deputy defense minister, said one issue
remained in Sri Lanka's 3-month-old standoff with India over
withdrawing the 40,000 Indian soldiers.
   ``Negotiations by telephone between the two countries will
resolve it, maybe in a day or two,'' he said, without identifying
the issue.
   On Thursday, joggers found the body of Sagarika Gomase, 27, of
the state Independent Television Network, on a beach in Mount
Lavinia, 10 miles south of Colombo, military officials said. They
blamed Sinhalese extremists.
   Ms. Gomase was abducted from her home in nearby Dehiwela
Wednesday night by six gunmen, they said.
   Elsewhere, six suspected Sinhalese radicals were killed fighting
security forces Wednesday in southern Sri Lanka, the Sinhalese
heartland, a government communique said.
   It said Sinhalese militants shot to death three Sinhalese
civilians and a retired solder.
   In central Kandy district, about 60 miles northeast of Colombo,
security forces found seven unidentified bodies, the communique
said. Soldiers found another body in a Colombo suburb.
   India signed a peace pact with Sri Lanka in July 1987 and sent
soldiers to this island nation to supervise the surrender of weapons
by Tamil militants, who agreed to give up fighting for an
independent homeland in exchange for limited autonomy.
   Die-hard Tamil rebels rejected the plan and turned their guns on
the Indian soldiers. The move also triggered an uprising by radicals
from the dominant Sinhalese community, who complained about
concessions made to the Tamils and described the Indians as an
invading force.
   Indian-Sri Lankan relations eroded after President Ranasinghe
Premadasa unilaterally set a withdrawal deadline of July 29. Indian
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi refused, saying a hasty pullout might
lead to greater bloodshed.
   A compromise now reportedly provides for Indian troops to leave
by Dec. 31.
   Wijeratne said Premadasa was confident the agreement and
cease-fire will be honored by the most militant Tamil rebel group,
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, who this year began peace
talks with the government.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. They
claim they are denied jobs and education by the Sinhalese, who make
up 75 percent of the population and dominate the government and
military.
   The Tamil insurgency began in 1983.
   India became involved in part because of political pressure from
its own 60 million Tamils. Sri Lanka lies 18 miles off India's
southernmost tip.
</TEXT>
