<DOCNO> AP890914-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0747 09-14 0936</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0747,0967</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombia to Extradite Two More Reputed Drug Traffickers to U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with state of emergency, minister
denying reports of U.S. troops in Colombia, details. No pickup. Edits to
trim and conform</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BOG3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia announced on Thursday the arrest
of two men wanted in the United States as cocaine traffickers and
said they were in a high-security prison awaiting extradition.
   The government also decreed a new state of emergency in two
cities believed under the influence of drug lords, sending an
undisclosed number of ``military advisers.'' Officials say the area
around Puerto Boyaca and Pacho is a haven for cocaine-processing
laboratories and drug cartel terrorism.
   Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez, head of the Administrative Security
Department and the man in charge of Colombia's anti-drug war,
earlier described one of arrested men, Bernardo Pelaez Roldan, as
among the major drug figures in the Medellin cartel.
   Maza said Pelaez Roldan ``was much bigger'' than Eduardo Martinez
Romero, an economist who was flown to Atlanta Sept. 6. Martinez is
charged there with money laundering for the Medellin cartel, one of
the world's largest cocaine organizations.
   Pelaez Roldan and Guillermo Bueno Delgado were paraded before
news photographers Thursday at the Administrative Security
Department, Colombia's equivalent of the FBI, where officials said
they had been held since their arrests this week.
   A department communique said Pelaez Roldan would be extradited to
Detroit, where he is wanted for ``conspiracy and distribution of
cocaine.''
   The Justice Department in Washington said Pelaez Roldan was
convicted of drug trafficking charges five years ago in Detroit and
faces 15 years in prison.
   He was not, however, on the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration's list of the 12 most-wanted Colombian cocaine
traffickers.
   The Associated Press has learned that the Justice Department has
a wanted list of 82 lesser Colombian drug figures that has never
been made public.
   Authorities said Bueno Delgado is wanted in Tallahassee, Fla.,
and San Francisco for ``introducing 5,740 kilos of cocaine (12,628
pounds) and money laundering.''
   The communique said Pelaez Roldan was arrested Wednesday north of
Bogota and Bueno Delgado was captured in Cali on Monday. It gave no
arrest details.
   The department said the two were ``in a high security prison
while legal extradition proceedings are under way,'' and said U.S.
officials were notified of the arrests.
   Only photographers and no other members of the news media were
allowed to view the men. Photographers said Pelaez Roldan's forehead
was gashed and that he threatened them with a walking stick.
   Diva Rojas, the department's press officer, said reporters could
not see the two ``for human rights reasons.''
   ``They don't want to talk, and we have to respect that,'' she
said.
   Pelaez Roldan was indicted in November 1983 on U.S. charges of
conspiracy to possess with intent to distribute cocaine, Justice
Department spokesman David Runkel said in Washington. He was
arrested in Florida and taken before a U.S. magistrate in Detroit in
January 1984.
   The trial was set to begin that March, but Pelaez Roldan was
released on bond and ``never seen again,'' said Runkel.
   Pelaez Roldan was tried in absentia and convicted in April 1984
and a warrant for his arrest was issued a month later, said Frank
Shults of the DEA.
   U.S. Attorney Stephen J. Markman in Detroit said Thursday that
Pelaez Roldan skipped bail of $200,000.
   The case against Pelaez Roldan and more than two dozen
co-defendants involved a conspiracy that distributed 50 to 200 kilos
(110 to 440 pounds) of cocaine per month in the Detroit area from
1975 to 1983, Markman said.
   He was the middleman for the Medellin cartel and his part of the
conspiracy involved more than 300 kilos (660 pounds) of cocaine, the
prosecutor said.
   ``In the process, he earned over $6 million,'' Markman said.
   President Virgilio Barco launched a major crackdown on Colombia's
drug traffickers after Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, the leading
presidential candidate, was assassinated on Aug. 18, allegedly by
drug-backed terrorists.
   Under special emergency powers, Barco announced he would
extradite traffickers wanted in the United States by the
``administrative method.'' This bypasses the courts, traditionally
slow-moving and subject to bribes and intimidation.
   On Thursday, the Minister of Defense, Gen. Oscar Botero Restrepo,
called a news conference to deny recent reports of American troops
in Colombia to help in the drug war.
   ``There are no foreign troops in Colombia, and we don't plan on
having any,'' the minister said.
   He said there were 17 ``North American technicians'' helping
Colombians operate U.S. military equipment, including helicopters
and planes, that the Bush administration donated in a $65 million
aid package.
   Botero was responding to an open letter from former Presidents
Misael Pastana Borrero and Belisario Betancourt published in
Colombian newspapers Thursday. It asked Barco to respond to reports
of U.S. troops in the country.
   The Pentagon has said up to 200 military advisers could come to
Colombia to train and help operate the U.S. equipment.
   In another part of the crackdown, Barco evoked the state of
emergency Thursday in Puerto Boyaca and Pacha, cities in the
Magdalena Medio region. The measure allows him to send military
personnel.
   During the crackdown, thousands of people were rounded up and
millions of dollars worth of properties said to belong to drug
dealers were confisccated.
   The top-echelon drug lords have escaped so far, however. They are
apparently in hiding and authorities do not seem close to finding
them. A bounty of $250,000 is out for Pablo Escobar and Gonzalo
Rodriguez Gacha, said to be the top two bosses of the Medellin
cartel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 3rdLd-Writethru a0758 09-14 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0758,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Seek Financing Compromise; Fireworks Erupt in Bennett Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEDES with 4 grafs with fresh talks set; pick up 6th graf pvs,
now 5th graf: ``Elsewhere, the''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders, split over money for the war on
drugs, agreed Thursday to fresh negotiations and drug coordinator
William J. Bennett came under intensified fire from Democrats upset
with details of the plan.
   ``The president's plan is wholly inadequate,'' Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said. He agreed to talks Friday by
a task force of nine members from each party in an effort to reach a
compromise.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., threatened to freeze
floor action on a dozen money bills unless fresh talks produced
funds for the drug war.
   In the House, a Democratic caucus broke up with a number of
members cool toward a proposal to get an additional $2.2 billion for
the $7.9 billion drug war by making a half-percent, across-the-board
cut in federal programs. But party leaders said they were ruling out
nothing except a tax increase.
   Elsewhere, the head of the Federal Bureau of Prisons backed the
concept of sending youthful drug offenders to boot camp-style
``shock incarceration'' but said more study was needed before
carrying out the idea on the federal level.
   Dole met for much of Thursday afternoon with Bennett and the
White House budget director, Richard Darman. Dole told reporters
afterward that Republicans ``don't believe we should proceed with
appropriations until this is done.''
   Only one of the 13 annual money bills has gone to President
Bush's desk for his signature with the start of fiscal 1990 two
weeks away. Republicans are in the minority in the Senate but could
still conceivably use Senate rules to block action on the
appropriations measures.
   Dole said Republicans also would like to expand the negotiations
to include such matters as Bush administration anti-crime
legislation, which he said has been ``resting in peace in the
Judiciary Committee for months.''
   He named nine Republican senators to take part in negotiations
and said administration officials also would be available. Mitchell
was attending a funeral and not immediately available for comment.
   Following a House Democratic caucus, Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.,
told reporters the concept of an across-the-board cut was being
opposed because domestic programs ``have already been cut to the
bone.''
   He said Democrats would seek to find savings in other programs,
such as defense.
   ``My constituents believe the drug war is more important than,
say, the mission to Mars or a couple of extra stealth bombers,''
added Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
   Bennett's fireworks with lawmakers at a House Government
Operations Committee session were the first such eruption since he
began lobbying lawmakers last week.
   The explosion came as Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., was preparing
to ask about the administration's plan to finance the drug war by
cutting existing programs, such as juvenile justice grants.
   ``If we're critical,'' she said, ``it's because there are some
problem areas here that have to be discussed, and I think if its
healthy dialogue and debate today, maybe we can resolve some of the
problems.''
   ``It hasn't been healthy so far,'' Bennett said. ``It has been
petty and micromanagement. I don't appreciate it.''
   ``In this committee, Sir, or do you mean generally?'' interrupted
Chairman John Conyers, D-Mich. Bennett sai he was referring to
repeated questioning of his chief of staff, John Walters, by Rep.
Glenn English, D-Okla., about the possible use of P-3 radar planes
in the skies over Colombia to scout for airborne cocaine cargoes.
   ``I'm sorry you feel that way about it, Mr. Bennett,'' English
said, adding that he had been within his rights to question Walters.
   ``It's the public's right,'' English said. ``It's public
information.''
   Under repeated questioning from English, Walters said he could
not now say whether he would recommend using the P-3s. He offered to
brief English in private.
   English told reporters the Customs Service has two of the
radar-equipped planes. He said that a source he declined to name had
told him the Colombian government wants the planes used in the fight
against the cartels.
   He acknowledged that he had discussed the matter with a
representative of a company involved in the P-3 program but declined
to name the company. He said he understood sending the planes was
being held up by a ``turf fight'' in the federal bureaucracy.
   Minutes after the exchange over the P-3s, Bennett became
embroiled in a sharply worded dispute with Mrs. Boxer after she said
California would face drastic cuts in its federal aid under the
administration finaning plan.
   ``I think this is the phoniest war that I've ever seen
launched,'' she said.
   Meanwhile, Bureau of Prisons Director J. Michael Quinlan told a
House Judiciary subcommittee that more study is needed before
implementing boot camp-type punishment for youthful drug offenders
at the federal level.
   ``The success of these programs is yet undetermined,'' Quinlan
said. He did say that the administration backs the general concept
but added that under a boot camp bill sponsored by Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., only 60 of the 50,000 inmates in federal prisons
would be eligible.
   The bill calls for any able-bodied, first-time offender with a
prison term of 12 to 16 months to be eligibile for the program. Each
day in camp would count as four days in regular prison.
</TEXT>
