<FIRST>u a AM-DowntownShooting-Profile     09-14 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Downtown Shooting-Profile,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbors Say Man Who Went on Rampage a Quiet, Family Man</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Downtown Shooting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE GIBSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who shot seven people to death and
wounded 13 before killing himself at a printing plant Thursday was a
quiet, hard worker whose forced leave for mental problems led to
dreams of revenge, former co-workers said.
   ``He said before he left, he would get even. I remember that,''
former co-worker George Oswine said after 47-year-old Joseph
Wesbecker's rampage at the Standard Gravure Corp. plant.
   Although friends and former co-workers who described him as quiet
and hard-working, police said Wesbecker had been argumentative and
confrontational for years and was being treated for mental disorders.
   Some people at Standard Gravure said he'd become obsessed with
guns over the past year. He was carrying several semiautomatic
weapons and thousands of rounds of ammunition when the killing began
Thursday.
   Wesbecker's friend, John Tingle, worked with him for 17 years at
Standard Gravure before Wesbecker was put on permanent disability
two years ago.
   ``He was always level-headed, fun-loving, thrifty. I've never
known him to carry a gun or use a gun,'' said Tingle. ``We always
usually had a good laugh at work.''
   Tingle said Wesbecker became upset when management at Standard
Gravure, which prints magazines and newspaper inserts, refused to
accept a doctor's recommendation that Wesbecker stop operating
machines that had caused him stress.
   ``They forced him back to work, but the doctor said he couldn't
work the folder anymore, that was too much stress and tension,''
Tingle said. After a week's hiatus, Wesbecker returned to work, but
management again told him he must continue in his former job.
   ``That's when his mental problems began,'' Tingle said. ``It's
terrible ... that they could push a man that far.''
   The episode left Wesbecker with ``a big grudge,'' Oswine said.
   Standard Gravure President Michael Shea said he did not know the
reason Wesbecker left the company, and said personnel information on
the man was unavailable.
   After he went on disability, Wesbecker began collecting guns,
Oswine said.
   Another former co-worker, Joe White, said conversations with
Wesbecker centered on guns and Soldier of Fortune magazine. White
said Wesbecker thought of himself as a soldier and seemed obsessed
with guns.
   ``This guy's been talking about this for a year,'' White said.
   ``I guess nobody believed him,'' said Don Frazier, president of
the graphics union at the printing plant.
   Frazier said Wesbecker had become more upset recently because he
thought his disability benefits were about to be cut off.
   Police Sgt. Carl Yates said police knew little about Wesbecker or
where he obtained his guns: a 9mm handgun, an AK-47 assault rifle,
two MAC-11 semiautomatic machine pistols, a .38-caliber revolver and
a bayonet, as well as the ammunition.
   ``I wouldn't think it would be real difficult to obtain'' an
AK-47, Yates said. Wesbecker did not have a police record or any
record of military service, Yates said.
   Lt. Jeff Moody said Wesbecker had been treated for ``apparent
mental disorders'' but did not have any specifics.
   Yates said Wesbecker and his second wife, Brenda, had two boys in
their 20s, but he did not know their names. Mrs. Wesbecker works at
a Louisville beauty school.
   Employees of Roy's Academy of Beauty Inc. declined to comment on
the shootings or Mrs. Wesbecker. The phone at the Wesbecker's
residence has been disconnected, and the family did not return home
Thursday night.
   Neighbors said Wesbecker purchased the small split-level house in
south Louisville about three years ago for $56,000. They said
Wesbecker kept to himself.
   A neighbor, Paul Danahy, said he did not know Wesbecker's name
until he heard about the shootings, and said he had only seen him
``once or twice while he was mowing the yard.'' He described him as
``cocky and standoffish ... a hard guy to approach.''
</TEXT>
