<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Ship 1stLd-Writethru a0630 09-14 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Ship, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phosphates-Carrying Ship Refloated Off Scenic Coral Reef</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with damage done, cause of grounding.
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egyptian tugboat crews and rescue teams on
Thursday refloated a cargo ship that ran aground and ended the
danger of polluting the Red Sea or fragile coral reefs with oil or
phosphate spills, authorities said.
   A small area of reefs was reported damaged.
   Red Sea coral lines the shores of the Sinai Peninsula along the
gulfs of Aqaba and Suez, creating spectacular reefs that harbor
rainbow-colored fish and attract tourists and divers.
   The Panamanian-registered Sapphire Glory was transporting 14,700
tons of phosphates from Aqaba, Jordan, to India when it rammed a
reef early Wednesday. The crash tore a hole in an empty tank and
partially submerged the 19,279-ton freighter.
   No injuries were reported among the ship's 24 crew, most from
South Korea.
   The Friday edition of el-Akhbar newspaper said a minor phosphate
spill caused slight damage to the corals and that the vessel damaged
around 240 square yards of coral reef when it ran aground. It was
not immediately clear if rescue work did further damage.
   An officer at the Committee for Oil Pollution, an environmental
agency responsible for preserving Egypt's waters, had said the reef
was damaged in the accident but no phosphates or fuel leaked because
the punctured tank was empty.
   He spoke anonymously under agency regulations.
   Crewmen were taken ashore at Sharm el-Sheikh at the southern tip
of Sinai, near where the accident occurred. The South Korean captain
said his ship grounded after its radar failed, newspapers said.
   The Sapphire Glory will be towed by tug to Suez, the nearest
repair facility, 200 miles northwest of Sharm el-Sheikh.
</TEXT>
