<FIRST>u w AM-OilSpills     09-14 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Spill Legislation Approved by Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee on Thursday approved
legislation aimed at improving the prevention of oil and chemical
spills and their handling when they do occur in coastal and inland
waters.
   The measure endorsed by the Merchant Marine and Fisheries
Committee requires the maintenance of seven cleanup response teams
around the country, and makes it easier for the federal government
to take over cleanups.
   It would also mandate the establishment of a computerized
inventory of cleanup resources around the world.
   The legislation was written as a response to the Exxon Valdez
disaster in Alaska's Prince William Sound six months ago and was
approved one day before Exxon is supposed to wind up its cleanup
efforts in Alaska.
   Environmentalists complained that the bill did not go far enough.
The Sierra Club said it hoped backers could add a provision on the
House floor giving states the right to impose tougher standards than
the federal government.
   The Exxon Valdez disaster in which 11 million gallons of crude
oil were spilled prompted many members to introduce bills of various
kinds, and the measure sent to the House floor on Thursday was a
distillation of many of them.
   The Senate has approved its own version of oil spill legislation,
and if the House passes a bill the two versions will have to be
reconciled.
   The Merchant Marine committee earlier this year approved a bill
that would, among other things, give the federal government power to
determine damages to be paid by those responsible for spills.
   Thursday's bill has provisions aimed at:
   _Increasing the ability of the Coast Guard to uncover alcohol and
drug abuse by permitting the use of information in the National
Driver Register in licensing mariners. The captain of the Exxon
Valdez had been drinking and was not on the bridge when his ship ran
aground.
   _States could require the use of their own pilots in state waters
if the federally licensed pilot aboard were not specifically
qualified for those waters.
   _Evaluating the staffing, training, qualification and
watch-keeping standards of foreign tankers.
   _Requiring vessels to maintain cleanup plans that are consistent
with the current national cleanup plan.
   _Increasing penalties for spills.
   The Coast Guard receives reports on about 7,500 oil spills every
year, most of them small but about 200 requiring a federal takeover
of the cleanup effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
