<DOCNO> AP890914-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Lebanon     09-14 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Lebanon,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Says US Inaction In Lebanon Gives Syria A Green Light</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's ambassador said Thursday night U.S.
diplomatic inaction is giving Syria a green light to occupy his
country completely.
   He said U.S. assertions of support for Lebanon's independence and
calls for the departure of foreign troops are no substitute for a
vigorous policy.
   ``Syria is enforcing its hegemony over Lebanon,'' Ambassador
Abdallah Bouhabib said in a speech. ``It's very clear.''
   Lebanon is torn by 14 years of civil war between Christian forces
and Moslems backed by neighboring Syria. Earlier this month, calling
the situation in Beirut too dangerous, U.S. ambassador John McCarthy
and his entire American staff departed.
   Abandonment of the U.S. embassy was described by the State
Department as temporary. But the American diplomats already are
being reassigned to other posts.
   Syria, whose troops have been in Lebanon since 1975, controls the
Bekka Valley and parts of Beirut. Iranian-controlled allies,
believed to be holding American hostages, are strong in other areas
while Israeli forces occupy a security buffer in the south.
   ``The lack of a concerted effort to solve the situation has made
everyone concerned believe that the United States has no policy at
all,'' Bouhabib said.
   He contrasted U.S. inaction in Lebanon with U.S. emphasis on
human rights in other countries and assertions by President Bush he
will try to end the country's suffering.
   ``In Lebanon it seems we have even less, no rights,'' Bouhabib
said.
   More than 150,000 Lebanese have died in the war and 250,000 have
been wounded.
   ``In the case of Lebanon what is U.S. policy?,'' the ambassador
asked. ``U.S. policy means at the present time a green light that
the Syrians can do whatever they want in Lebanon.''
   He stressed he was not asking for U.S. military intervention or
assistance. ``We are simply calling for concentrated diplomatic
action by the administraion and Congress to bring pressure on the
parties to end the destruction and tragedy _ the end the
strangulation of the Lebanese people,'' the ambassador said.
   Bouhabib said U.S. inaction could establish a dangerous precedent
for small and defenseless nations elsewhere.
</TEXT>
