<DOCNO> AP890914-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0817EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Soviet-SpaceCity Adv20   09-14 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Space City, Adv 20,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs Sept. 20 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Spaceport Is No Cape Canaveral but Better than Average</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Shuttle, b0200</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the shadow of the launch pad from
which man first entered the cosmos, meat and butter are rationed and
concrete crumbles from prefabricated buildings.
   ``This is not Cape Canaveral,'' said Vladimir A. Shatalov, head
of Soviet cosmonaut training who has visited the U.S. spaceport in
Florida.
   While Leninsk may not by up to Cape Canaveral's standards and
food now is rationed, the people who live here and work at the
nearby Baikonur Cosmodrome are generally better off than most other
Soviets.
   Leninsk was built in 1955 on the Kazakhstan desert in Soviet Asia
1,560 miles southeast of Moscow as the bedroom for the cosmodrome
from which the Soviet Union launches satellites, interplantetary
space probes, manned space ships and its new space shuttle.
   The land is flat and dry with little vegetation. Strong desert
winds blow sand off the hard earth, spewing dust on everything.
Residents say temperatures can reach 115 degrees in the shade.
   But the region is ideal for a spaceport. The sky is generally
cloudless and there's nothing for hundreds of miles around, making
it ideal for safety and security.
   Leninsk's population of 75,000 is growing steadily as more
specialists arrive to work on the fledgling Buran space shuttle,
which was tested in an unmanned flight last November. Most live in
nine-story prefabricated apartment buildings like those found
throughout the country.
   The theme in Leninsk is space.
   The sole movie theater is the ``Saturn.'' Children climb through
miniature rockets in playgrounds and space-related banners and
monuments are scattered throughout the city. One colorful tile
mosaic on the main road leading into the city features the orbiting
space station Mir and boasts, ``The U.S.S.R. is the Homeland of
Cosmonautics.''
   But Larisa I. Konovalenko, a local TV commentator, had a question
for Lt. Gen. Igor I. Kurinny, the head of the Leninsk political
department, at a news conference.
   ``Why is there such a big gulf between the high technology used
for space and the social conditions of the city of Leninsk?''
   Kurunny replied: ``It cannot be denied that such differences
truly exist between the social aspects of the city and the
technology with which we're conquering space.''
   But he added that the Communist Party and government approved a
plan early last year to build new housing, schools, a hospital,
maternity home, and cultural and recreational facilities.
   A modern pedestrian mall downtown was built this year and 11 new
apartment buildings have been put up. But, Kurinny said, things are
going slowly because of a shortage of construction workers.
   A group of teen-agers, sitting on a park bench near a monument to
Baikonur workers killed in a 1960 accident, said rationing of meat,
sugar, butter and laundry detergent began in the city two months
ago, later than most of the country. Even so, they added, it came as
a blow to Leninsk's people because they were so accustomed to buying
food and consumer goods without difficulty.
   One of the teen-agers, identifying himself as Vitaly, said
residents now joke that Leninsk's trademark had become ``lines in
stores, open pipes and puddles.'' Indeed, steam pipes line the
sidewalks and puddles seem to appear from nowhere despite the arid
climate.
   Vitaly and his friends Artur and Natasha even talked about their
fathers' work, once a taboo subject.
   Salaries in Leninsk run 300 to 600 rubles ($480 to $960) a month,
compared to about 230 rubles ($370) for the average worker
nationwide.
   Vitaly, Artur and Natasha said they attend technical schools and
hope to stay in Leninsk even though they are often bored.
   Then they headed off to a disco in a local park.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Sept. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
