<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-PersonalFile-Gardner Adv17   09-14 0975</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Gardner, Adv 17,1003</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stephen Gardner Having Fun Protecting Consumers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer champion Stephen Gardner is one of the
lucky ones, living out his high school idealism 20 years later in
professional life.
   ``I'm having so much fun. It's a lot of work, but this is what I
wanted to do in high school,'' said the 38-year-old Gardner, an
assistant Texas attorney general.
   Gardner's fun frequently gives manufacturers fits, especially if
he believes their advertising or other trade practices violate
Texas' consumer protection law.
   His targets come from his own observations _ ``I drive my wife
crazy, I watch (television) commercials'' _ or from complaints
culled from the hundreds his office receives monthly or from
suggestions by consumer protection groups.
   Beyond Texas, Gardner has pulled together attorney general
offices from nine other states to fill in what he says are gaps in
federal enforcement of consumer protection or truth-in-advertising
laws.
   The confederation is ``back-door national regulation,'' he said.
``It's a federal chore, but the feds aren't doing it.''
   ``The Federal Trade Commission is looking for a way not to''
protect consumers, he said in an interview at his Dallas office,
which includes a corner bookcase filled with memorabilia from past
cases: cereal boxes, baby formula, an auto parts guide.
   The 18-month-old collaboration has led to lawsuits or
investigations involving Quaker Oats Co., Sara Lee Corp., Kellogg
Co., Chrysler Corp., credit reporter Chilton Corp. and Citicorp,
among others.
   In Texas, there also have been cases made against a man selling
weedkiller in pill form as a weight-loss aid and an anti-abortion
group advertising its services as an abortion clinic.
   All the companies have denied the charges, but Gardner says
``we've got what we wanted'' in almost every instance.
   The latest action came Sept. 7 when Texas Attorney General Jim
Mattox filed suit against Quaker Oats, charging the company with
making false claims in advertising its hot cereal. The move came
just days after Sara Lee had agreed to settle a lawsuit brought by
the confederation over claims its ``light'' products actually had
more calories that regular products.
   Although the Quaker suit is filed under Mattox' name, it will be
Gardner handling the case, just as he has previous high-profile
lawsuits.
   ``He (Gardner) just loves getting after these big companies,''
said Mattox spokesman Ron Dusek. ``He likes to play it real low key,
when in fact he's a real hot shot.''
   ``This is a case I developed, and I believe in, and I sold
(Mattox) on,'' Gardner said of the Quaker suit. Mattox ``encourages
us to do what we need to do to protect the public, (requiring only)
`If you think the law is on your side, do it.'''
   Gardner agrees there are political overtones to his work _ Mattox
is a likely Democratic gubernatorial candidate _ but says those
issues do not affect his decisions.
   In the Quaker case, there was some discussion about the impact on
Mattox's political plans, he said, but ``we decided that shouldn't
be the basis of enforcing the law.''
   Although he lived in a middle class north Dallas suburb,
Gardner's father and grandfather both were police chiefs in the
high-tone Dallas enclave of Highland Park.
   ``We were `help,''' he said, and his father ``raised me not to
believe that making money was the thing to do.''
   While still in high school, he decided to be a lawyer to help
``empower the people.'' After graduating from the University of
Texas law school in 1975, he remained in Austin until 1982, first as
a legal services lawyer and then the students' attorney for the
university.
   In 1982, he left Texas for New York City, where he honed his
interest in consumer cases as an assistant attorney general. He
returned to Texas in 1984 to head Mattox's Dallas office.
   Then last year he instigated the cooperation of states on
consumer protection issues during a meeting of the National
Association of Attorneys General. The group began with seven or
eight states, and now has 10 on board. Besides Texas, they are
California, Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Missouri, Illinois, Florida,
New York and Massachusetts.
   The attorneys general who support the collaboration ``are
everywhere across the political spectrum,'' he said, from Reagan
conservatives to liberal Democrats.
   There is no leader of the group, Gardner said, with different
states taking the lead on different issues. In the Quaker case, for
example, the investigation began last year with a letter from the
Minnesota attorney general.
   The cooperation allows for greater efficiency, he said, while at
the same time ``it is a bigger hammer.''
   Gardner's logic is not necessarily accepted by manufacturers.
   ``We feel that the actions of Mr. Gardner and his group ... are
most inappropriate,'' said Thomas Howell Jr., vice president and
general counsel of Quaker Oats, the group's latest target.
   ``A recent blue-ribbon task force of attorneys ... observed that
state attorneys general do not belong in national advertising
matters,'' Howell said, adding that the lawsuit appeared to be
``primarily motivated by the personal ambitions of Mattox and
Gardner.''
   Gardner is sensitive to the possible criticism he is using the
law to impose his own personal agenda, but said, ``I have the duty
as a state official to enforce the law.''
   Plus, he said, any actions by the Texas attorney general or the
other nine states are not the work of one person, but are shaped by
various officials at many levels.
   There are investigations that are begun, but are ended when the
advertising claims hold up to closer scrutiny.
   As for the future, Gardner said, ``It'd be fun to run for office,
but I don't have the money to run for any office I'd have.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Sept. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
