<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-Accutane Adv18   09-14 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Accutane, Adv 18,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Sept. 18, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Acne Drug Linked To Birth Defects Still Over-Prescribed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. physicians continue to over-prescribe the
acne-fighting drug Accutane to women of child-bearing age despite
pervasive warnings about its potential for causing birth defects, a
government regulator says.
   ``There is a vast number of instances in which the drug is being
prescribed for people who don't need it,'' said Robert Nelson,
chairman of the Accutane Monitoring Group of the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration.
   Of an estimated 50,000 to 70,000 new female users of the drug
each year, fewer than 20,000 and perhaps as few as 5,000 have an
acne problem that merits using it, Nelson told an international
conference on drug effects.
   James LaBraico of Hoffman-La Roche Inc., the maker of Accutane,
said Nelson's estimate of excessive use is high, but he agreed that
it is clear some doctors prescribe the drug to women who don't need
it. ``I don't think there is a lot of frivolous use. But we need to
define severe acne better.''
   The drug's effectiveness is a powerful argument for its
prescription. A single 20-week treatment usually puts severe acne _
which is five times more common in women than men _ into remission
for up to two years, said Dr. Robert Stern of Harvard Medical School
and Boston-based Beth Israel Hospital.
   As of July 31, La Roche had documented 78 cases of birth defects
among infants delivered by woman exposed to Accutane during
pregnancy. Since the drug was introduced in 1982, the survey has
detected 433 pregnant users, about half of whom chose to have
abortions, said Dr. Wanju Dai, a company researcher.
   The birth defects have centered on the ears, nervous and
cardiovascular systems, Dai said. About 70 of the 433 women who
reported being pregnant while taking the drug gave birth to healthy
babies, she said.
   The link to birth defects in the company survey and other surveys
prompted the FDA to intervene. Besides over-prescribing, the FDA
found that some doctors weren't warning women of the dangers of
becoming pregnant while on the drug.
   At the FDA's urging, La Roche in May opened a new assembly line
to package Accutane exclusively in 10-pill ``blister packs'' with
warnings. Also included is a questionnaire inviting users to
participate in the tracking study.
   Because the study relies on doctors to urge users to participate,
there is a fear that only patients of ``good doctors'' who give
adequate warnings will take part, Nelson said. Patients of doctors
who are lax in giving warnings may be less inclined to join, which
could skew the results in the company's favor.
   LaBraico said the Nutley, N.J.-based drug company knows of the
shortcomings and is considering ways to make the sample more
representative.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
