<FIRST>r f PM-WorkplacePrivacy     09-14 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Workplace Privacy,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Juries Favor Workers in Lawsuits: Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Shepard in 3rd graf and Sheppard in 4th graf are cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers who sued employers for invasion of
privacy, sexual harassment or slander won an average jury award of
$375,000 in 1988, according to a report.
   A survey included in the report, released Wednesday, also found
that juries decided heavily in favor of employees, returning
verdicts for the workers in 72 percent of cases between 1985 and
1988.
   ``Employee privacy issues are destined to be the labor law issue
of the 1990s as they continue to be fueled by controversies over
workplace drug testing, AIDS, workplace monitoring of job functions
and management responses to family issues,'' said the authors of the
Bureau of National Affairs report, lawyers Ira Michael Shepard,
Robert L. Duston and Karen S. Russell.
   Their Washington employment law firm of Schmeltzer, Aptaker &amp;
Sheppard conducted the 50-state survey of employee lawsuits.
   Duston said the 1988 invasion of privacy verdicts included cases
involving drug and alcohol abuse, unlawful surveillance by employers
and use of lie-detector tests. The average award was $375,307.
   ``A substantial new array of complex and novel legal theories
have developed under which employees are attempting to redress what
they see as a decline in their privacy rights,'' the report said.
``The United States is forging the cutting edge of employee privacy
rights.''
   The Bureau of National Affairs Inc. is a major publisher of print
and electronic information services dealing with labor relations,
business, law, taxation and other areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
