<FIRST>r f PM-TexasAir-Non-Strikers     09-14 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Air-Non-Strikers,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Tells Shareholders Why He Crossed Picket Line</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texas Air, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines pilot who recently crossed the
picket line in the 6{-month strike against the carrier said he came
back because of the severe financial hardship the walkout caused him.
   ``It was very cold days for myself,'' Peter Clements told Texas
Air Corp.'s annual meeting here Wednesday. ``I realized that
cardboard doesn't keep you warm. It doesn't pay the bills, either.''
   Clements, an 18-year Eastern veteran, went on strike with the
airline's pilots, flight attendants and Machinists union members on
March 4 but decided to return to work last month. Several hundred
Eastern pilots are estimated to have crossed the picket line at the
same time, after the now-ousted leader of the airline's pilots union
urged them to do so.
   Clements said Eastern now is ``a wonderful place to work.''
   Miami-based Eastern, a subsidiary of Texas Air, has been under
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since March 9. Texas Air Chairman
Frank Lorenzo told shareholders at the meeting that Eastern ``has
made an astonishing rebound from the devastation caused by the
strike of its three unions, and is recovering much faster than
expected.''
   Lorenzo was visibly moved by the remarks by Clements and other
non-striking Eastern employees at the meeting, and several
bystanders noticed tears in his eyes as he left the room when the
session ended.
   Another veteran pilot, Frank Barber, said he has been on the job
since the strike started.
   ``We had some very dark days early on ... but with the 600-plus
flights a day now, we're very excited,'' he told the shareholders.
</TEXT>
