<DOCNO> AP890914-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TexasAir Bjt   09-14 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Air, Bjt,0807</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Lorenzo Says He's Not Quitting Business</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo insists
that he plans to remain in the airline business, countering
speculation that he might quit.
   A defiant Lorenzo also said Wednesday that Texas Air's Eastern
Airlines subsidiary will start turning a profit next year, despite
the strikebound carrier's enormous debts and bankruptcy proceeding.
   While about 100 Eastern strikers chanted anti-Lorenzo slogans
outside the long-delayed Texas Air annual meeting, the chairman of
the nation's biggest airline company told shareholders he has no
plans to quit the business, won't sell Eastern and likely will have
Texas Air assume some of Eastern's financial obligations.
   ``I have no intentions of leaving the airline business,'' Lorenzo
said at a news conference after the meeting. ``I plan to be around
for plenty of years to come, God willing.''
   Speculation that Lorenzo might quit was fueled by his surprise
announcement Aug. 24 that he was considering selling all or part of
Houston-based Continental Airlines, Texas Air's other main
subsidiary. He had no comment on a statement Wednesday by Jan
Carlzon, managing director of Scandinavian Airlines System, that SAS
has no ``immediate interest'' in buying part of Continental.
   SAS, which owns a 9.9 percent stake in Texas Air, has been in
talks with Texas Air officials about possibly buying part of
Continental. Under U.S. law, foreign airlines are allowed to own up
to 25 percent of an American carrier.
   Security was tight at the hotel where the shareholders meeting
took place, largely because of Lorenzo's unpopularity among Eastern
strikers. Stockholders had to pass through metal detectors,
television cameras were banned from the meeting room and Houston
uniformed and plainclothes police as well as private security guards
were present.
   Lorenzo's remarks about Miami-based Eastern came as the airline
is mired in the seventh month of a strike that has become a national
symbol of labor resistance and has left thousands of pilots, flight
attendants and Machinists union members walking picket lines
demanding Lorenzo's resignation.
   Eastern has been replacing the strikers with picket-line crossers
and non-union hires and is flying a limited operation, but it is
doing business under the protection of federal bankruptcy court _
where it sought protection from creditors five days after the strike
began March 4.
   If Continental were sold, some observers believe Lorenzo might
liquidate Eastern and quit the business.
   But the airline chief told about 300 shareholders at the meeting
that Eastern ``is projecting profitable operations beginning next
year.'' The stockholders responded with applause.
   Eastern has made an ``astonishing rebound from the devastation
caused by the strike of its three unions, and is recovering much
faster than expected,'' Lorenzo said during the hourlong meeting.
   He said Eastern's proposed reorganization plan, submitted to
bankruptcy court July 21, likely will receive final court approval
by year end or early next year, clearing the way for the airline to
emerge from bankruptcy at about two-thirds its pre-strike size.
   ``Texas Air is standing behind Eastern Airlines, and the
possibility is excellent that Texas Air will assist Eastern,'' said
Lorenzo, who aggressively built the parent company from a small
intrastate carrier into an airline empire.
   The annual meeting coincided with a hearing in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court in New York at which a judge approved a plan for payment of
$98.3 million Eastern owes to employee pension plans. Texas Air is
lending Eastern $45 million toward the payment, Eastern is paying
$27 million with the proceeds of asset sales, and the rest has been
deferred until July 1990.
   Eastern's proposed reorganization calls for repaying all
creditors in full, including refunding the price of tickets that
weren't used because of the walkout.
   The strikers have been pushing for a sale of Eastern in its
entirety and have allied themselves in that effort with Joseph
Ritchie, a Chicago businessman. Eastern, meanwhile, has been selling
aircraft, routes and airport gates to raise money toward paying off
its $2.3 billion debt.
   The Air Line Pilots Association, which represents pilots at
nearly all the nation's major carriers, has spent $69.5 million _
about 57 percent of its contingency fund _ on the battle with
Eastern. Pilots at the other airlines have provided strike benefits
to Eastern pilots averaging about $2,400 a month per pilot, said
John Mazor, an ALPA spokesman in Washington.
   But the number of pilots paying those assessments to their
colleagues at Eastern has decreased as the strike has worn on, Mazor
said in a telephone interview.
   ``That's typical for any (strike) assessment, for any labor
union,'' he said. ``It goes through a predictable cycle.''
   ALPA members are being balloted on whether to continue strike
benefits to their Eastern colleagues, he said.
</TEXT>
