<DOCNO> AP890914-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CurrencyTrading Bjt   09-14 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Currency Trading, Bjt,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worldwide Currency Trading More Than Doubled Since 1986</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain continues to lead the world as a center
for currency trading, but the United States and Japan are catching
up as trading volume continues to mushroom, central bank surveys
show.
   Daily trading in currencies totaled $187 billion in London,
$128.9 billion in New York and $115.2 billion in Tokyo, according to
April surveys released by the central banks Wednesday.
   Currency trading worldwide has more than doubled since 1986, the
last time surveys were done. Figures for different countries cannot
simply be added up because cross-border trades are counted twice, in
the buyer's country and the seller's.
   The growth in currency trading far exceeds the expansion of
international trade in goods and services, which is the underlying
reason for currency trading.
   Although businesses need to trade currencies to do business
abroad, the vast majority of currency trading today is speculation
by banks and other dealers, statistics indicate.
   Big banks devote large staffs to playing the market, buying and
selling currencies by the minute in hopes of pocketing profits by
guessing short-term price trends.
   In the United States, only about 12 percent of banks' dealings
are with industrial companies and other institutions that need
currencies for purposes other than speculation, according to
Gretchen Greene, a senior vice president at the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York.
   The rapid growth in currency trading reflects the closer
connections among stock and bond markets around the world and the
attractiveness of dealing in currencies for speculation and hedging,
among other factors, Greene said.
   In London, average daily currency trading rose 107 percent to
$187 billion from $90 billion in 1986.
   In New York, trading rose 120 percent to $128.9 billion a day
from $58.5 billion three years earlier.
   The Tokyo market showed the fastest growth, up 140 percent to
$115.2 billion from $48 billion.
   In comparison, world exports rose by about a third from 1986 to
1988, according to United Nations figures. Estimates for 1989 are
not yet available.
   After the big three trading centers came Switzerland, $57
billion; Hong Kong, $49 billion; France, $26 billion; the
Netherlands, $16 billion; and Canada, $15 billion, up 57 percent.
Canada was the only one of the smaller markets surveyed in 1986.
   More than $300 billion worth of dollars, marks, yen, pounds,
francs and other currencies change hands daily, surveys by the banks
reveal.
   The total is probably more than $400 billion a day, although
estimates are difficult because of the double-counting problem.
   Central bankers plan to share information in order to eliminate
double-counting of cross-border trades and come up with a net figure
for worldwide currency trading, possibly later this year or early in
1990, Greene said.
   The central banks surveyed banks, other financial institutions
and brokers over 20 business days in April. The Federal Reserve has
surveyed currency trading every three years since 1977 and was
joined in 1986 by a few other central banks.
   The volume of trading is so huge that it often overwhelms efforts
by central banks to stabilize currency rates, such as by selling
dollars on the open market when the dollar is getting too high.
   For example, Federal Reserve dollar sales of $130 million in the
U.S. market would equal only one-tenth of 1 percent of total trading
on an average day, the new statistics show.
   But Greene said central banks still can be effective because
although total trading volume is huge, the imbalances between supply
and demand that cause prices to move are much narrower. In other
words, supplying a small sum of dollars to the market could soak up
the excess demand and halt a price rise.
   The greatest concentration of trading continued to be in the
dollar against the West German mark, Japanese yen and British pound,
the surveys showed.
   Trades that didn't involve the dollar, such as selling marks for
yen, grew in importance. They rose to 11 percent of total volume
from 4 percent in London. They totaled about 4 percent in New York.
No New York comparison for 1986 was available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Visa-Bankruptcy Bjt   09-14 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Visa-Bankruptcy, Bjt,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Visa, Major Banks Fighting Bankruptcy Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Personal bankruptcy filings have doubled
since 1980 and account for one half the annual fees paid by bank
credit card holders, said the president of Visa U.S.A. in announcing
a nationwide crackdown on fraudulent filers.
   Jon Cristoffersen said Wednesday that efforts are under way in
Los Angeles, Dallas, Houston and Chicago and will reach most major
areas by year end.
   ``Bankruptcy can be an appropriate way for honest people to deal
with a financial problem,'' he said. ``But our concern is with the
fraudulent filing, which can be as many as one in three.''
   Personal bankruptcy filings have increased since 1980 to about
600,000 last year, or one in 178 households. Cristoffersen said that
socked the bank card industry with total losses of $1.5 billion in
1988 as bankrupt cardholders simply wrote off their credit card debt.
   ``About half of everyone's annual fees for bank cards comes from
bankruptcy,'' he said. ``If we're able to deal with even 20 to 30
percent of the fraud, the payback to the public will be
substantial.''
   Most people who file for bankruptcy fraudulently have been able
to get away with it, Cristoffersen said, because two-thirds of the
banks with assets over $1 billion haven't been challenging them.
   Visa's new program encourages member banks to screen for fraud
and abuse of the federal bankruptcy law, challenge filings in court
and seek criminal prosecution.
   Bankruptcy frauds include those who don't declare all their
assets, such as real estate in other states or inheritances. They
also include those who sell assets below their true market value or
transfer ownership to a third party or relative. Abusers also
include those who have the ability to pay back their debts but
choose not to.
   ``The stories are legend, like the man who wanted to spread out
payments for his Jaguar, or the chap who lost $350,000 on a single
roll of the dice after he took out 30 bank cards,'' Cristoffersen
said.
   Cristoffersen, speaking at a convention of the National
Foundation For Consumer Credit Inc., outlined a tough program that
so far has enlisted 70 member banks. Those banks, including
Citibank, Bank of America and Chase Manhattan, issue 60 percent of
Visa's 118 million cards in the country and are victims of 75
percent of all bankruptcies.
   When member banks in the program receive bankruptcy notices, they
will immediately review the account and, if they suspect fraud or
abuse, notify all other members listed on the bankruptcy petition.
   The other members will do a similar search, and when two or more
believe they have found fraud or abuse they will collectively use a
single local law firm to represent them.
   ``By multiple members reviewing bankruptcies they can put
together a clearer picture of fraud and abuse and make it
economically feasible to go after the abusers,'' said Kenneth R.
Crone, who heads the bankruptcy recovery program for Visa.
   The program also includes pursuit of criminal prosecution. Visa
has hired a former FBI agent who will investigate cases, prepare
them for review by the FBI and seek prosecution by the U.S. attorney
on a fast-track basis under a special arrangement with the Justice
Department.
   In Los Angeles, the number of accounts showing up with fraud or
abuse that are being challenged under the pilot program has doubled
to more than 300 in the past three months, Crone said.
   That represents a small percentage of the more than 30,000
fraudulent or abusive bankruptcies among the 51,000 declared each
year in Los Angeles. But Crone believes the program is sending the
message that ``there's a darn good chance they'll get caught, that
the bankruptcy petition will be thrown out of court and they'll have
to pay attorney fees and face criminal prosecution.''
   The Bankruptcy Reform Act, which was rewritten in 1978, was
designed to encourage Chapter 11 or Chapter 13 personal
``reorganization'' filings, wherein the debtor pays back creditors
as much as possible over three to five years, Crone said.
   ``But we've seen an incredible boom of Chapter 7 bankruptcies,
where there are no assets and people get their entire unsecured debt
discharged,'' Crone said. ``Credit cards are unsecured so they're
the first to get written off.''
   Of the nearly 600,000 personal bankruptcy filings in 1988, about
95 percent were Chapter 7 filings, Visa said.
   The National Foundation for Consumer Credit is the parent
organization for more than 400 consumer credit counseling offices
and offers free counseling services.
   Visa, the world's largest consumer payment system, has more than
19,000 U.S. bank members with $120 billion in payment volume a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
