<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Mexico-Debt     09-14 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Debt,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Group, Mexico Announce Agreement on Terms of Debt Reduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican government and a committee of banks
have announced an agreement on detailed language covering the
historic debt-reduction plan reached between that nation and the
bank group in July.
   The language, called a term sheet, will be sent to the more than
500 banks owed money by Mexico, officials said Wednesday. The term
sheet provides a list of options the banks may exercise to reduce
the amount of Mexican debt on their books.
   ``The agreement on the term sheet concludes the second stage of
the process,'' said Angel Gurria, undersecretary of the Mexican
Ministry of Finance.
   ``As expected, it has taken several weeks since we reached
agreement in principle in July, but the issues we confronted were
new, extremely complex and economically of great importance, both to
Mexico and the banks,'' he said in a statement released in New York,
where the bank committee and Mexican officials met.
   ``After a period for review, we will visit financial centers
around the world to explain the package and answer the banks'
questions,'' Gurria said.
   The term sheet covers the period of 1989-92.
   Mexico's agreement in principle with the steering committee of 15
creditor banks, reached July 24, was seen as a test of Bush
administration policy for reducing Third World debt and as a
milestone for other debtor countries waiting to renegotiate.
   It represents the first significant reduction in a government's
debt to commercial banks.
   Under the agreement, each bank has three options: a 35 percent
reduction in principle, reduction of the interest rate on its loans
to 6\ percent from the current average of about 10 percent, or
providing new loans equal to 25 percent of what Mexico owes the bank.
   The deal applies to about $53 billion of Mexico's foreign debt,
which totals about $107 billion, second in the developing world only
to the $120 billion owed by Brazil.
   In a statement, U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady praised
the agreement on the term sheet.
   ``This agreement represents an important step forward in
implementing the strengthened debt strategy and in Mexico's efforts
to obtain needed debt reduction and new financing to support its
economic reform program,'' Brady said.
   Mexican Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe has said that Mexico's goal
in reaching a debt agreement is to decrease the amount of the
nation's gross national product paid to the banks for debt service
from the 6.3 percent of recent years to 2.7 percent.
   He said that paying as much as Mexico has been paying for its
debt service is ``incompatible'' with economic growth.
   After the agreement was reached in July, Aspe said Mexico had
achieved all its main goals: a real reduction in its debt, a
reduction in the transfer of assets abroad to pay the debt, a
long-term debt agreement, and breathing room for the nation to renew
economic growth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
