<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PanAm Bjt   09-14 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am, Bjt,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman Says Pan Am May Need Foreign Infusion to Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texas Air, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. became the first U.S. airline to run
a permanent foreign service 62 years ago and gained a reputation as
America's flag carrier, but survival may dictate that it find a
foreign bankroller.
   Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Thomas G. Plaskett disclosed
this possibility Wednesday and seemed to suggest Pan Am viewed
partial foreign ownership as the most realistic way to escape an era
of staggering losses that has left its future in doubt.
   Plaskett said in February that Pan Am would need to find a merger
partner or attract new investment to survive, but he did not
emphasize the foreign ownership option.
   Pan Am unsucessfully bid for Northwest Airlines parent NWA Inc. a
few months later and has been said to be weighing a bid for United
Airlines parent UAL Corp.
   Plaskett's remarks came against a background of growing overseas
airline investment in U.S. carriers, a trend that is reshaping the
commercial aviation industry and raising speculation that some day
foreign airlines might freely fly domestic U.S. routes, which they
currently aren't allowed to do.
   Since 1988, Scandinavian Airlines System has acquired a small
stake in Texas Air Corp., owner of Continental and Eastern; Dutch
airline KLM joined a group of investors buying NWA; and most
recently, British Airways joined a group seeking to buy UAL.
   Although U.S. law limits foreigners to 25 percent ownership of a
U.S. airline, these minority ownership arrangements have given the
foreign partners enormous influence over U.S. airline strategies.
   Moreover, they could create what amounts to a new breed of
super-airline with tremendous global reach by linking schedules and
ticketing services.
   Plaskett said the British Airways involvement with United, for
example, would create an operation that offers passengers nearly
half the world's existing air routes, more than any other airline or
alliance of airlines.
   ``Pan Am is determined to be a major player in the evolving
world-wide mega-carrier system,'' Plaskett told a luncheon of
aviation industry executives in New York. ``If it takes the form of
an infusion of capital from a foreign entity, we want to be free to
do it openly and without subterfuge...Our government needs to tell
us what the rules are in very clear terms.
   ``Certainly, it's time for our government to consider whether
there is still any valid national interest, other than the national
defense interest, which can be protected in retaining these foreign
ownership restrictions,'' Plaskett said.
   He declined to identify any possible foreign partners for Pan Am
or say whether the company still is actively pursuing other
strategies, including a possible bid for UAL or Texas Air's
Continental, which also may be sold.
   New York-based Pan Am is one of the oldest U.S. airlines and
became the first to operate a permanent international air service in
1927. It also helped pioneer routes to Europe, Asia and Latin
America, giving it the reputation as America's unofficial
flag-carrier overseas.
   But Pan Am has been battered over the past several years by tough
competition, labor tensions and other problem while competitors have
been aggressively expanding. It financial woes forced it to sell its
Latin American and Pacific routes, greatly shrinking its size.
   The airline lost $462 million in 1986, $265 million in 1987 and
$72.7 million in 1988. It has lost $158.8 million so far this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
