<DOCNO> AP890914-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0745EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     09-14 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Down 0.6 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-MI--Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supply problems, expired incentives and patient
consumers combined to torpedo early September sales of two
Japan-based companies' U.S. plants and drop car and truck sales 0.6
percent, the companies say.
   The eight major U.S. automakers on Wednesday reported that their
vehicle sales for Sept. 1-10 dropped to an average daily rate of
30,333 this year, compared with a rate of 30,522 during the same
time last year.
   Pulling down the year-to-year comparison were sluggish car sales
by Honda Motor Co. and car and light truck sales by Nissan Motor
Corp.
   Sales of Civics and Accords made at Honda's Marysville, Ohio,
plant sold at a rate 36 percent below last year's during the period.
And Nissan pickup truck and Sentra car sales fell 72.1 percent and
79.1 percent, respectively.
   Honda spokesman Jeff Leestma said few Civics were available
during the period because of a model changeover at the factory. He
also speculated consumers may be waiting to see the redesigned 1990
Honda Accord.
   Nissan spokesman E.C. Mueller said early September sales were
damaged by an incentive program that expired Sept. 5.
   ``There was a run on the vehicles at the end of August,'' he said.
   Auto dealers, as they do every year around this time, hold ``fire
sales'' to rid their lots of unsold cars to make way for the new
models rolling off assembly lines.
   Manufacturers also want to get rid of the cars, so they have
offered incentives to customers and their dealers, which drop the
price of the vehicle. Also, analysts have said some consumers appear
to be buying cars now rather than waiting for the new models and the
higher price tags they will carry.
   Ford Motor Co. was the only one of the Big Three to show declines
in car and truck sales during early September. The nation's No. 2
automaker reported vehicle sales at an average daily rate of 8,867
during the period this year, 8.3 percent behind last year's pace of
9,671. Car sales were off 6.6 percent and truck sales dropped 10.8
percent.
   For the year, Ford's car and truck sales were running 0.8 percent
behind last year's rate.
   General Motors Corp. reported a 1.7 percent increase in
early-September car sales and a 30.5 percent rise in truck sales for
a vehicle sales rate 10.8 percent higher during the period this year
than last year.
   So far this year, GM reported its car and truck sales were 4.6
percent behind last year's.
   Chrysler's early-September vehicle sales were mixed, with car
sales rising 6.7 percent and truck sales falling 8.3 percent.
Combined, Chrysler's vehicle sales were 0.6 percent below the
early-September rate last year.
   Chrysler car and truck sales through Sept. 10 of this year were
6.1 percent behind last year's rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0749EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TexasInstruments     09-14 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Instruments,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Instruments Reduces Group's Work Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Texas Instruments Inc. say 700
employees in the Defense Systems &amp; Electronics Group have
voluntarily chosen to leave the company.
   Because of the job reductions, severance pay and other costs, the
Dallas-based electronics giant will take a $10 million charge in its
current fiscal quarter, said TI spokesman Stan Victor.
   He said Wednesday the departures are in addition to 230 jobs
eliminated in the defense electronics group announced in August.
   Cuts were made to control expenses and to adjust to changes in
the defense group's business, Victor had said earlier. Older defense
programs are being replaced with newer programs that require less
metal, he said.
   Although Texas Instruments takes the multimillion-dollar charge
against profits in the current quarter, ``this reduction will lower
costs in this group on a look-forward basis,'' the company said in a
statement.
   By this month's end, the combination of voluntary and involuntary
job cuts will reduce employment in the Defense Systems &amp; Electronics
Group to roughly 23,000 workers.
   The company said in January it planned to cut its nationwide work
force by up to 1,000, including up to 700 employees in North Texas
in a voluntary termination and retirement program.
   Demand from makers of electronic equipment is slowing for memory
chips, at the same time competitors are increasing their production
of such chips, the company said.
</TEXT>
