<DOCNO> AP890914-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BankerCharged     09-14 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Banker Charged,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Director of NY Fed Sentenced to Six Months for Data Leak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert A. Rough's banking career started at
age 14, when he worked as a runner for a bank in Paterson, N.J.
   After college came a stint as an auditor at the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York, where he returned 20 years later _ president of
his own bank _ to join the board of directors at the institution,
where many of his young colleagues from the 1960s were now senior
officials.
   On Wednesday, Rough was sent to jail, his career finished, his
money gone.
   U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise sentenced him to six
months in prison Wednesday for leaking secret interest rate data
while on the New York Fed's board. Debevoise also ordered the
50-year-old ex-banker to perform 200 hours of community service
during two years of probation.
   ``I am an outcast in the banking community and my own
community,'' Rough told the judge in emotionally choked tones.
``These past few years have been truly a living hell.''
   Debevoise called the case ``particularly sad'' and said he was
convinced that Rough's anguished remorse ``came from the heart.''
   But he said jail time for Rough was ``essential for the public
perception of the fairness of the system'' _ that white collar
criminals, and those with advantaged backgrounds, be properly
punished.
   ``I breached a trust placed in me, and in doing so, blemished the
reputation of the institution I still revere,'' said Rough, his
voice quavering.
   He said a picture of former Federal Reserve Bank chairman Paul
Volker remains hanging on his wall. The Federal Reserve Bank of New
York is part of the Fed's regional system.
   Rough sat on the New York Fed's board from 1982 to 1984 while
president of the National Bank of Sussex County in Branchville, N.J.
While there, Rough admitted in a plea bargain, he regularly
disclosed advance word regarding the Fed's discount rate to a
now-defunct Livingston, N.J.-based brokerage firm, Bevill, Bresler &amp;
Schulman Inc.
   Bevill, Bresler traded in government securities, part of a market
that is powerfully affected by the discount rate.
   The case was the first to involve insider trading of government
securities, and marked the first such charges against a director in
the Fed system, federal officials said.
   Rough could have received up to five years in prison. But in an
unusual move, the U.S. attorney's office recommended that if Rough
was sent to prison, it should be for less than a year.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Paul Weissman, in a pre-sentencing memo,
said Rough expected no financial gain.
   Debevoise agreed to recommend that Rough serve his sentence,
beginning Oct. 16, at Eglin Air Force Base in Florida, a minimum
security prison camp. Rough's attorney, Michael Himmel, who had
asked for probation, said his client would probably serve about 4{
months, gaining early release for good time.
   Rough's career as a prosperous ``country banker'' who once
aspired to be chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation
began to unravel in the spring of 1987, when witnesses at the trial
of Bevill, Bresler president Gilbert C. Schulman disclosed the
allegations.
   Rough usually leaked the data to Schulman, and blamed his actions
on a misguided friendship with the Bevill, Bresler official.
Schulman and four other top executives of the firm were sent to
prison in connection with its April 1985 collapse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0816EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GasolinePrices     09-14 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gasoline Prices,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaskan Spill Exonerated in Gas Pricing Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto YM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Skyrocketing gasoline prices that followed
the Exxon Valdex oil spill in Alaska can't be pinned on that
disaster, a Washington state probe has concluded.
   As 11 million gallons of Alaskan crude from the supertanker that
ran aground on March 24 coated Alaska's Prince William Sound, gas
prices were soaring by 20 cents or more per gallon at service
stations across the nation.
   But the price hikes already were in the works before the spill
because of a complicated series of production and market factors,
Attorney General Ken Eikenberry said Wednesday.
   America's worst oil spill had a brief impact on U.S. refinery
supplies, particularly in the West, but not enough to be considered
a major factor in the price hikes, Eikenberry's anti-trust division
said in a detailed report on its six-month probe.
   Investigators said they discovered no evidence of collusion among
the Big Oil companies but neither could they disprove such a
possibility. Any further investigation should be done at the federal
level, said Eikenberry.
   As chairman of the Task Force on Gasoline Over-Pricing of the
nation's attorneys general, he has asked the Justice Department and
the Federal Trade Commission to investigate.
   Washington, Oregon, California and Arizona already are in federal
court over alleged gasoline price-fixing and contrived shortages in
the early 1970s.
   ``Already angered about the environmental consequences of the oil
spill, consumers demanded explanations for the price increases,''
the report said.
   ``Many felt that the increases added insult to injury and that
the spill was being used as an excuse to raise prices. Additionally
some were concerned that by paying higher prices, consumers would be
paying for the cost of cleaning up the spill.''
   The investigators, who grilled the oil industry, conducted
hearings and did their own analysis of economic information,
concluded that the oil spill had only ``minimal and temporary''
impact on gasoline supply.
   ``The Exxon Valdez did not cause the price increase,'' Assistant
Attorney General Tina Kondo told a news conference. ``Prices went up
all over the country, even in places that don't depend on Alaskan
crude.''
   The spill caused ``a sharp one-week dip in gasoline production on
the West Coast (but) it was quickly rectified and should have had
little long-term impact,'' the report said.
   Other factors ``already had created a volatile supply
situation,'' said the report prepared by Kondo and investigator
Larry Little:
   _ Crude oil prices had been surging, squeezing refineries'
profits and adding to pressure to boost prices. Between last
November and May, OPEC boosted prices between $7 and $8 a barrel _
or between 16 and 19 cents a gallon of gas. Initially, retailers
absorbed some of the cost, with refiners getting the lion's share of
the higher pump prices, the report said.
   _ West Coast refineries had both scheduled and unexpected
shutdowns. ARCO's Ferndale, Wash., refinery was down between April 5
and mid-May. Chevron's fire at its Richmond Beach, Calif., refinery
on April 10 cut production by 25 percent for more than a month.
Exxon's Benicia, Calif., scheduled maintenance, losing half its
production. Texaco had an emergency shutdown at its Anacortes,
Wash., refinery on Feb. 2, curtailing production until the end of
March.
   _ Demand for gas was increasing but inventories were abnormally
low. Texaco and ARCO customers reported outages before the spill.
Chevron and ARCO bought expensive oil on the spot market to try to
fill the gap.
   _ Uncertainly over the long-term effects of the spill and a major
explosion at Shell's Cormorant Alpha oil platform in the North Sea
boosted prices on the world crude and spot markets.
   _ Stricter environmental regulations took effect on June 1, 1989.
Oil companies have estimated that anti-air pollution laws will cost
an extra 1 to 3 cents per gallon.
   The Alaska spill may have had an indirect ``catalyst'' effect,
the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
