<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0849EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Popeyes-Church's-Aliens     09-14 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Popeyes-Church's-Aliens,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fast Foord Firm, Immigration Authorities Reach Agreement on Aliens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unprecedented accord will require Church's
Fried Chicken Inc. to pay immigration authorities $80,700 in fines
for hiring unauthorized aliens, the U.S. Justice Department said.
   In return, the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service will
not pursue a nationwide investigation and will give Popeyes Famous
Fried Chicken Inc. a chance to correct improper hiring practices by
the fast-food rival it acquired last February.
   The Justice Department said it was the first agreement of its
kind since the November 1986 enactment of federal legislation
prohibiting the hiring of unauthorized aliens. It said the agreement
was signed Wednesday in Washington, D.C.
   All of Church's 798 company-owned outlets and the company's
corporate office in San Antonio, Texas, is covered by the agreement,
the Justice Department said.
   Under its terms, the INS' New Orleans district will fine the
corporate headquarters and each outlet $500, but will accept a
settlement of $100 from each, the Justice Department said. That
amounts to a total fine of $403,000 and a settlement payment of
$80,700, it said.
   The acquisition of Church's by Popeyes was a consideration in the
settlement, said INS District Director John B.Z. Caplinger.
   ``Popeyes is an international, New Orleans-based firm which has
strongly supported the legislation prohibiting the employment of
unauthorized alien labor,'' Caplinger said.
   ``The positive support provided by us by Popeyes during our
investigation, and our trust in the ability of Popeyes to correct
the problems at its new Church's outlets, led to this nationwide
agreement,'' he said.
   The apprehension of some unauthorized alien workers at Church's
outlets in Baton Rouge last fall triggered an investigation into
whether Church's was complying with the Immigration Reform and
Control Act of 1986, the Justice Department said.
   The act forbids U.S. employers to hire unauthorized alien
workers, and also requires them to complete am I-9 form verifying
the identities and employment eligibility of all employees, even
U.S. citizens, the Justice Department said.
   Numerous record-keeping violations, including missing and
improperly completed i-9 forms, were found in a subsequent
investigation of 97 Church's outlets and 2,900 employees in
Louisiana, Mississippi and Texas, the Justice Department said.
   As a result of those violations, it said, the INS proposed a fine
of more than $620,000 but accepted payment of $50,000 from Church's
last July.
   ``The investigation indicated the Church's problem was nationwide
in scope but, by the time of the first settlement covering those 97
stores, Popeyes had bought Church's,'' Caplinger said.
   ``In light of the positive support by Popeyes Human Resources
Director Charles Dilapi and his staff, we felt that, rather than
initiating a nationwide investigation of Church's, we would initiate
a nationwide settlement which gives Popeyes the opportunity to
install new procedures and provide training which will, we are
confident, correct the problem,'' he said.
   He said the agreement covers violations which occurred prior to
June 1, 1989. It gives Church's a 120-period, from Aug. 1 to Nov.
28, to correct those violations, Caplinger said.
   Also, he said, the INS agreed not to issue any new fines during
the 120-day period and Church's agreed to terminate any unauthorized
workers it might find in the process of correcting violations.
   Church's also would be subject to fines for any uncorrected or
new violations after Nov. 28, Caplinger said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
