<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ford     09-14 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Escort and Tracer Program Costing Ford $1.5 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next generation of Ford Escort and
Mercury Tracer subcompact cars will cost Ford Motor Co. $1.5 billion
to develop, more than half of it going into two plants, one in
Mexico.
   The investment is part of a production switch scheduled for next
year to clear the way for a new sport-utility truck.
   Escorts and Tracers will be made in the Detroit suburb of Wayne
and in Hermosillo, Mexico, where they currently are assembled,
company executives said Wednesday. The Escort plant in Edison, N.J.,
will be switched to making Ranger light pickup trucks, which now are
assembled in Louisville, Ky.
   The Louisville plant will be the source of the Explorer, a
two-and four-door sport utility vehicle that replaces the Bronco II.
   All the new vehicles will be introduced in the spring and in
dealer showrooms later.
   ``With an investment of this size, Ford is making a clear
commitment to maintain small car production and sales leadership in
North America,'' Alex Trotman, Ford's executive vice president for
North American Automotive Operations, said during the introduction
of Ford's 1990 lineup of cars and light trucks.
   He said about $600 million will be invested at the Wayne plant
and about $260 million at the Mexican plant. The remaining $640
million will be spent at Ford component plants, for retooling
suppliers and in other Ford divisions linked to the new Escort and
Tracer program.
   The company also said it will spend about $285 million at the
Edison factory to prepare for truck production.
   The subcompact market for much of this year has been weaker than
last year. Through August, sales of subcompacts have slipped 6.2
percent from last year's level to 649,311 cars.
   To avoid swelling dealer inventories too much, Ford shut down its
Wayne and Edison plants for a week or two several times in the last
four months. The Escort was the best-selling car last year, with
387,815 of the cars driven off dealer lots.
   Cars have been assembled at the Edison plant since 1948, and
about 119,000 Escorts were made there last year. The plant has an
assembly line rate of 37{ cars an hour on two shifts.
   By contrast, Ford assembled about 296,000 Escorts at the Wayne
plant west of Detroit last year. Its line speed is 68{ cars an hour,
also on two shifts.
   Ranger pickups currently are made at Ford's Louisville assembly
plant at a rate of 37{ an hour, coincidentally the same rate as the
Edison plant. That factory will begin producing the Ford Explorer
sport-utility vehicle, which will replace the Bronco II, when Ranger
production is moved to New Jersey.
   Ford spokesman Jay Meisenhelder said he didn't know when the
Edison plant would stop production to retool and to retrain workers
to make the pickup. About 1,600 people work there.
   The new generation of Escort and Tracer will be introduced in the
spring as a 1991 model. Ford executives declined to talk about
details of the car at the 1990 models' introduction Wednesday.
   Ford is making few large-scale changes for the 1990 model year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
