<FIRST>r f PM-Jackson-LAGear     09-14 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-LA Gear,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pop Singer to Plug Sportswear Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA9 of Sept. 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Michael Jackson joined the ranks of
celebrities promoting signature-model sneakers in a deal reportedly
worth about $20 million.
   Beside plugging shoes, apparel and accessories for L.A. Gear, the
pop superstar will also design a line of sporty products bearing his
name, it was announced Wednesday.
   ``I'm very happy to be a part of the L.A. Gear magic, and I hope
we have a very rewarding, successful career,'' the singer said at a
news conference.
   The deal slated to last about two years will pay Jackson more
than $20 million, according to a source close to the negotiations
who asked not to be identified.
   Jackson accepted a new pair of sneakers from an L.A. Gear
representative and smiled at a horde of photographers at the news
conference staged at the Hollywood Palladium to resemble a rock 'n'
roll concert.
   He refused to answer any questions.
   The superstar performer who announced earlier this year that he
wouldn't perform in concert again, will have a very ``hands-on''
relationship with the shoe manufacturer, according L.A. Gear
executive vice president Sandy Saemann.
   Saemann said Jackson will ``create, design and market a signature
line of fashionable and technical athletic footwear.''
   ``In the five or six times I've been with Michael, he's given us
two to three phenomenal ideas for footwear,'' Saemann said.
   The first of the Jackson-inspired shoes, clothing and watches is
set to debut in 1990.
   Saemann said that the agreement is ``probably the largest
corporate association ever reached between a company and a
celebrity.'' He would only say that it exceeded $10 million, the
amount Pepsi paid Jackson to promote the soft drink for the past
three years.
   While refusing to release specifics, Saemann said that Jackson's
arrangement also included an undisclosed share of L.A. Gear's
profits.
   Jackson becomes the latest in a series of celebrities to plug
athletic footwear. Nike Inc. already uses baseball and football star
Bo Jackson, tennis player John McEnroe and hockey's Wayne Gretzky to
hawk sneakers; Reebok International Inc. has sponsored rock concerts.
   With sales estimated by L.A. Gear to reach $1 billion in 1990,
the suburban Mar Vista-based company is the nation's No. 3 athletic
shoe maker, trailing Reebok and Nike. The company reported sales of
$235.6 million for the first six months of 1989.
   L.A. Gear's current celebrity spokesman is Kareem Abdul-Jabbar,
the retired center of the Los Angeles Lakers.
</TEXT>
