<FIRST>r f BC-Adidas-Ueberroth     09-14 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Adidas-Ueberroth,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ueberroth to Take Stake in Adidas USA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Ueberroth, former U.S.
baseball commissioner and organizer of the 1984 Los Angeles
Olympics, will take a stake in Adidas USA, the American subsidiary
of the West German sports shoe and clothing company, Adidas says.
   Adidas AG supervisory board chairman, Rene C. Jaeggi, said the
company was planning a new strategy to overcome losses on the
important U.S. market.
   Jaeggi said in a statement released Wednesday that Adidas USA
sales for 1989 were expected to top $400 million, about 4 percent to
5 percent down from 1988.
   Ueberroth has an option for a ``substantial'' stake in Adidas
USA, but it remains under 50 percent, Jaeggi said.
   He also holds an option for a stake in Adidas AG, the parent
company, but this remains ``well below 25 percent.'' The Dassler
family will retain its majority holding in Adidas AG, the company
said. Adidas AG is based in Herzogenaurach.
   Ueberroth will also become a board member of both Adidas USA and
Adidas AG, but will not take part in day-to-day running of the
companies, Jaeggi said.
   Ueberroth has already taken a stake in Le Coq Sportif, Pony and
Arena, three Adidas subsidiaries in the United States.
   Adidas was planning to raise its capital, now at about $60
million, by the end of the year, but had no plans to go to the stock
market, the company said.
   Jaeggi attributed the projected 1989 losses in the United States
primarily to distribution problems, as well as greater competition
from American and Japanese sports goods companies.
</TEXT>
