<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-14 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Rebound In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade, struggling to
recover from the steep losses of the previous session.
   Prices had fallen sharply Wednesday amid speculation that the
Agriculture Department would take measures to increase wheat acreage
and boost supplies.
   Today's early gains were underpinned in part by confirmation of a
sale of 140,000 metric tons of wheat Wednesday to the Philippines at
subsidized prices, and by a report that poor yields would force the
Soviet Union to buy 40 million metric tons of grain from the world
market in the coming year.
   That report was offset, though by another report quoting Oleg
Klimov, head of the Soviet grain-buying agency, as saying the
Soviets had completed their grain buying for this year.
   Further buying was linked to a pair of National Weather Service
forecasts _ a six-to-10 day outlook and 30-day outlook _ predicting
continued wet weather for the western Corn Belt through mid-October,
which could hamper the corn and soybean harvest.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1 cent to 2 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.87 a bushel; corn
was \ cent lower to } cent higher with September at $2.33{ a bushel;
oats were unchanged to } cent higher with September at $1.34 a
bushel; and soybeans were 2 cents lower to { cent higher with
September at $5.87 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, with frozen pork belly futures locked
up the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit following Wednesday's statement
by a Bush administration official that the odds were very good that
the United States would include pork bellies in a food-aid package
to Poland.
   Live cattle futures were .18 cent to .65 cent higher with October
at 72.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .28 cent
higher with September at 83.15 cents a pound; hogs were .13 cent to
.70 cent higher with October at 40.45 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were 2 cents higher across the board with February at 48.05
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Wednesday while pork futures
were mixed.
</TEXT>
