<FIRST>u f PM-Campeau 2ndLd-Writethru f0066 09-14 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campeau, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0066,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clouds Still Hanging Over Campeau's Financial Outlook</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with Campeau second quarter loss, SUBS 3rd graf pvs,
`Meanwhile, trading ...' with 2 grafs. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Campeau's
Allied ...' DELETES grafs 17-22 to tighten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Retail and real estate holding company Campeau Corp. remained in
an uncertain financial position today as discussions continued on a
definitive plan to borrow money from a major stockholder.
   Campeau spokeswoman Carol Sanger declined to comment on the
status of the talks.
   Meanwhile, trading in Campeau stock remained halted today on the
Toronto Stock Exchange pending an announcement from the company.
Sanger couldn't say when the company would issue any news, besides
its second-quarter financial results which were released today. The
stock had been halted Wednesday.
   Campeau reported it lost $124 million in the three months ended
July 31 on revenue of $2.26 billion, compared to a loss of $109
million and revenue of $2.21 billion a year earlier.
   Campeau's Allied Stores Corp. and Federated Department Stores
Inc. units _ both facing credit squeezes as they stock up inventory
ahead of Christmas _ said Wednesday there was no guarantee that
Campeau could obtain financing in time to meet debt repayment
deadlines.
   The news sent Allied and Federated high-yield junk bonds
plummeting Wednesday by as much as 15 points, or $150 per $1,000 in
face value. The bonds were moderately lower in early trading today,
slipping another $10 to $20 per $1,000 to yield in excess of 20
percent, although few bonds were changing hands.
   Allied and Federated also indicated that control of their
corporate parent could change hands after a definitive agreement is
reached with Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd., which has agreed in
principle to lend Campeau $250 million.
   ``Certain elements of the agreement in principle with Olympia &amp;
York might be deemed to constitute a change in control of Campeau
...,'' Allied and Federated said in quarterly documents submitted to
the Securities and Exchange Commission that were made public
Wednesday.
   A Campeau spokeswoman said discussions were in progress and
details of the loan agreement with Olympia &amp; York wouldn't be
released until it was definitive.
   It has been widely assumed that Olympia &amp; York, which has a 24.5
stake in Campeau, would gain a larger interest in Campeau in
exchange for granting the loan. There has been speculation that
Chairman Robert Campeau, who owns nearly 54 percent of the
Toronto-based company, would relinquish controlling interest.
   Campeau, trying to cope with a debt load approaching $10 billion,
late Tuesday said its board of directors approved a plan, in
principle, under which Olympia &amp; York would loan it $250 million to
cover working capital needs at Allied and Federated.
   The board also authorized Campeau's intention to sell the
16-store Bloomingdale's department store chain, which is part of
Federated.
   Two potential bidders have confirmed their interest in
Bloomingdale's: Marvin S. Traub, the chain's chairman and chief
executive officer; and Crown American Corp., one of the country's
leading developers of shopping malls.
   Certain unspecified lender and creditor concurrences are required
before Campeau enters a definitive pact with Olympia &amp; York, Campeau
said Tuesday, noting that there was no assurance of getting the
concurrences.
   Campeau is facing a Friday deadline to secure financing
arrangements that Federated needs to buy back $400 million of notes
held by three underwriters.
   The lenders, First Boston Corp., PaineWebber Inc. and Dillon Read
&amp; Co., had agreed to hold the notes until Dec. 1 provided certain
conditions were met, including a condition that the financing
commitments to repurchase the notes were obtained by Friday.
   If Campeau fails to get these commitments by Friday, the
underwriters have the right to up to 6.96 percent of Federated's
common stock, which is being held in an escrow account.
</TEXT>
