<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SmokingBan 2ndLd-Writethru f0078 09-14 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smoking Ban, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0078,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Smoking Ban Showdown Looms in Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 4 grafs new with effort dropped to block ban; picks up 3rd
graf pvs, Supporters of ... Final vote on the ban possible later today.
After cloture is invoked, the Senate is permitted an additional 30 hours
of debate, which may or may not be taken. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today moved toward final passage of
a total ban on smoking aboard airliners after voting to halt
delaying tactics by tobacco-state lawmakers.
   After losing a pair of procedural votes by substantial margins,
senators from cigarette-industry states accepted the inevitable and
abandoned their efforts to dilute the proposed tougher restrictions.
   The provision _ banning cigarette smoking aboard all domestic
airline flights _ was then formally adopted by the Senate on a voice
vote. Final passage of a spending bill containing the language was
possible later in the day.
   On the key vote, the Senate voted 77-21 to prevent a filibuster
by cigarette industry supporters who had promised to bring
legislative action to a standstill unless the smoking ban was
limited to short flights. Tobacco lawmakers then lost a second
procedural vote 65-34.
   Supporters of the measure to prohibit smoking aboard all U.S.
airline flights had said in advance that they had the 60 votes
needed to invoke cloture and halt the filibuster.
   ``No doubt about it,'' the chief sponsor, Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J., said Wednesday.
   Smoking-ban opponents served notice that even if they lost, they
would keep trying to block the proposal, which is part of an $11.9
billion transportation spending bill for next year. Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., promised to try to quash the smoking measure on
procedural grounds.
   ``I've got 25,000 or 30,000 tobacco farmers in North Carolina to
whom I have made a commitment that I'd protect their interests as
long as I'm in the U.S. Senate,'' said Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
``And I'm going to do that.''
   elms said Lautenberg ``may end up rolling us, but he will know
that he has been in a fight.''
   Tobacco state lawmakers, sensing the fight was not going their
way, said they would settle for a permanent extension of the current
smoking ban on flights of two hours or less.
   That restriction, which covers 80 percent of all U.S. routes,
will otherwise expire next April. The House on Aug. 3 adopted a
provision making the two-hour rule permanent.
   In offering to accept the permanent ban on short flights, Sen.
Wendell Ford, D-Ky., said he and his allies would slow the Senate's
work on other matters if the other side persisted in seeking broader
restrictions. Congressional leaders want to finish 13 spending bills
by the Oct. 1 start of fiscal 1990.
   ``There's more at stake here I think than just the question of
smoking on airliners,'' Ford said. ``It's a question of the budget
so the rest of world can work.''
   Airline employees and health groups have pressed for a total
smoking ban on aircraft, claiming that cigarette fumes can cause a
risk of cancer and other diseases for everyone aboard a flight.
   Tobacco interests say there is no proof that cigarette smoke
endangers non-smokers and argue that there are plenty of other
chemicals in recirculated aircraft cabin air.
   Meanwhile, Surgeon General C. Everett Koop on Wednesday
criticized U.S. tobacco marketing at home and abroad, saying America
is not respected overseas ``because of the manner in which we export
disease and death.''
   Koop said the epithet ``ugly American'' will ``indeed come home
to roost in a decade or two when the developing countries of today
realize what we did to them.''
   He also told a House subcommittee the wide availability of
cigarette vending machines in the United States makes a mockery of
laws forbidding minors to buy cigarettes.
   He supported a bill sponsored by Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, that
would forbid the placement of cigarette vending machines in any
location accessible to people under 18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0258 </DOCNO>
