<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower in Europe, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined in European trading
Thursday as dealers awaited the release of U.S. trade figures for
July.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers sold dollars ahead of Friday's trade report to hedge
against a worsening U.S. deficit. A widening deficit would depress
the currency.
   The U.S. trade deficit fell $8.2 billion in June, but forecasters
have predicted it will be up somewhat in July.
   Dollar sales by the Bank of Japan also helped to push exchange
rates lower.
   Traders said a report showing U.S. retail sales rose 0.7 percent
in August did not help the dollar much as an upturn of 1 percent had
been expected.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 145.85 Japanese yen, down
from 146.70. Later in London, the dollar traded lower at 146.60 yen.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5582 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.5530.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's late
rates included: 1.9705 West German marks, down from 1.9800; 1.7000
Swiss francs, down from 1.7095; 6.6485 French francs, down from
6.6805; 2.2185 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2300; 1,413.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,419.00, and 1.1849 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1855.
   Gold closed in London at a bid price of $362.00 a troy ounce, up
from $358.50. The late bid price in Zurich was $361.75, up from
$358.25.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $359.85, up from $359.60.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.12 a troy ounce,
up from $5.08.
</TEXT>
