<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Aid Bill Boosts Corn Futures; Most Markets Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, boosted by a proposal
to send 500,000 metric tons of corn to Poland as part of a food-aid
package.
   Rumors of Soviet buying interest prompted further buying of corn
futures but the rally was weak with most contracts gaining less than
3 cents a bushel.
   ``This was a pretty thin, tight market and it had a difficult
time recovering from yesterday's debacle,'' said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Grain and soybean prices had fallen sharply across the board
Wednesday on perceptions of weakening export demand for wheat and
speculation that the Agriculture Department was planning moves to
increase 1989-90 wheat acreage.
   The $2.25 billion Polish food aid package proposed Thursday by
Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy also includes
500,000 metric tons of sorghum, 100,000 metric tons of wheat, 20
million to 30 million pounds of pork and 10,000 metric tons of
butter.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.85} a bushel; corn
futures were 1} cents lower to 3} cents higher with September at
$2.37{ a bushel; oats were { cent to 1\ cents higher with September
at $1.34{ a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 3} cents higher
with September at $5.85 a bushel.
