<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 1553EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-JunkBonds Bjt   09-14 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Junk Bonds, Bjt,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yields Jump, But Some Junk Bonds Look Worse Than Ever Amid Campeau
Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Junk bond trading slowed Thursday as the cash
crunch at Campeau Corp. weighed heavily on the market, with traders
considering whether the company's problems were a forerunner of
trouble in a wide variety of the high-risk securities.
   Admissions that Campeau's Allied Stores Corp. and Federated
Department Stores Inc. units could default on their debt payments
triggered a broad junk bond selloff Wednesday that included issues
regarded as among the most stable and attractive.
   Critics long have contended that junk bonds, high-interest
securities frequently used to finance corporate buyouts, were ripe
for a fall, especially in a slow economy. The notion is that many
companies loaded with junk bond debt would default on interest
payments either because they would be unable to raise as much money
as expected from their cash flows or the sale of divisions.
   Several companies with major junk bond debts, such as the Revco
D.S. drug store chain, this year have sought bankruptcy protection
or encountered serious financial troubles.
   Market experts considered Wednesday's selloff significant because
it affected a broad range of junk bonds, including issues regarded
as relatively less risky.
   ``There are so many different tiers in the junk bond market,''
said John Moran, a trader at Advest Inc. ``For the first time the
whole market got weak.''
   Moran pointed to Colt Industries' 12{ percent bonds due in the
year 2001 as one ``quality'' junk issue that tumbled when Campeau
disclosed its troubles. The bonds were down as much as $20 per
$1,000 in face value Wednesday and lost another $10 early Thursday.
   But Robert Levine, president of Kidder Peabody High Yield Asset
Management, said the decline was more of a ``technical correction''
because prices had been on the upswing recently. Furthermore, there
has been no change in the credit quality of most companies, he said.
   By Thursday, trading had slowed to a trickle as dealers took a
wait-and-see approach and awaited the pricing of new issues coming
to market.
   Yields on the Colt Industries issue hovered around 12 percent. In
comparison, yields quoted on some Allied and Federated issues soared
well above 25 percent as prices plummeted $150 per $1,000 in face
value on Wednesday and dropped as much as an additional $20 on
Thursday. Yields, which rise to compensate for higher risk, move in
the opposite direction of prices.
   ``When a bond is trading at a 25 percent yield, it means they're
not going to pay,'' said Anthony Naylor, a senior vice president at
Rodman &amp; Renshaw Inc.
   Campeau used billions of dollars from the sale of junk bonds to
finance its $8.8 billion takeover of Federated last year. Not only
did he pay top dollar for the retail chain, but a stagnant consumer
market dashed his plans for relying on cash flow to pay down the
debt.
   Federated is scheduled to make an interest payment Friday
reported by some to be $50 million.
   Campeau, meanwhile, was scrambling to line up financing from
Toronto-based Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd. to pay the debt. Any
success in getting more financing for Allied and Federated, which
are in dire need of credit so they can stock up on inventory ahead
of the Christmas shopping season, would help not only to prop up
those precarious issues but the market in general.
   Last week, Campeau put its flagship Bloomingdale's department
store chain on the auction block in an effort to raise cash.
   Traders said they had not yet detected any significant selling by
mutual funds that invest in junk bonds, a trend that could severely
hit the market if it materialized.
   Moran said managers ``are studying the situation'' and are not
likely to act hastily. ``Besides, the whole thing is up in the
air,'' he said, noting that Campeau could succeed in its
restructuring plans.
   The market's latest woes come less than five months after the
indictment of junk bond king Michael Milken, the former Drexel
Burham Lambert Inc. executive who virtually created the current $200
billion arena for high-risk securities.
   Shortly Milken was indicted on racketeering and other charges,
the market took a major hit, with some issues falling as much as $50
per $1,000 in face value. A heavy supply of new bonds, fears of a
recession and rumors of massive mutual fund sales also worked to
weaken the securities at that time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890914-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-StateGrowth 1stLd-Writethru f0122 09-14 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Growth, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0122,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Population Growth Resumes in Industrial States</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: CORRECTS 1988 population figure for Maine in state-by-state
list. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The industrial states of the Midwest and
Northeast are pulling out of the population doldrums and adding
people once again, the Census Bureau reported Thursday.
   ``The industrial-based states of Indiana, Michigan and Ohio
continue to recover from the early 1980s population losses,'' the
bureau said. ``These three states added more population between 1986
and 1988 than in the previous five years combined.''
   In addition, the Northeast's population growth between 1985 and
1988 was the highest since the late 1960s, the Bureau said.
   And the report came just one day after the bureau and the
Department of Agriculture reported that the nation's rural
population had halted its long-term decline.
   Growth was sluggish in states with energy-based economies, the
bureau added, particularly Alaska, Louisiana, Oklahoma, Texas, West
Virginia and Wyoming.
   But the other trends notwithstanding, the bureau noted that the
nation's overall growth pattern continues to favor Sun Belt states
like California and Florida.
   At least since 1970, the Western region has remained the fastest
growing section of the nation, with the South second, the bureau
noted in the study ``State Population and Household Estimates, With
Age, Sex and Components of Change: 1981-88.''
   ``The East North Central states increased by 443,000 from 1985 to
1988 after population losses during the 1980-85 period,'' the report
said. ``Indiana, Michigan and Ohio added more population in the
three-year period between 1986 and 1988 than in the previous
six-year period.''
   The Northeast lost population between 1975 and 1980 but has since
recovered, the report said, and annual growth of 0.5 percent between
1985 and 1988 is the highest since 1970. Indeed, half of New
England's growth between 1980 and 1988 has occurred just since 1985.
   Slowed growth and population losses have plagued several
farm-oriented states in recent years. But, the bureau concluded,
``the downward slide seems to have reversed last year.'' Iowa showed
a slight new immigration, as did Nebraska, and South Dakota has
slowed its outmigration enough to experience population growth for
two consecutive years.
   The sluggish population growth in energy-dependent states is a
continuing problem, with West Virginia losing people every year in
this decade and even Texas, which added 59,000 people in the year
ending July 30, 1988, far below its peak growth of 1981-82, when it
agined 609,000.
   In fact, Texas experienced net outmigration last year, for the
second year in a row, the report said.
   Here is a state-by-state list showing the population of the
states according to the 1980 census and the estimates for 1985 and
1988, in thousands.
</TEXT>
