<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Italy-AtlantaBank     09-14 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Italy-Atlanta Bank,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Minister Says BNL Exposure is $3 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Minister Guido Carli on Thursday blamed top
officials of Banca Nazionale del Lavoro for a scandal at its
Atlanta, Ga., branch and said the bank's credit exposure to Iraq had
reached about $3 billion.
   Carli's declaration, made before the Senate Finance and Treasury
Committee, was his first public statement about the scandal that has
shaken Italy's largest commercial bank, which is 74-percent owned by
the Treasury.
   The exposure is the result of credit extensions by the Atlanta
branch that the bank says weren't authorized by either the BNL North
American management or the head office in Rome.
   Carli's assessment of the bank's credit exposure was well above
BNL's own asssessment. The bank said last week that it had extended
up to $2.64 billion in credits, of which $920 million hadn't yet
been disbursed.
   Carli held former management responsible for the scandal, saying
officials had failed to establish proper procedures for checking
operations at the Atlanta branch.
   ``The investigations have allowed us to reconstruct some of the
techniques used to hide the irregular operations ... despite the
falsifications perpetrated, traces were left in the official records
and therefore should not have been able to escape accurate internal
controls,'' he said.
   The bank's Atlanta branch extended the credits to Iraq without
reporting them on the official books.
   Carli said that following the Atlanta affair, Banca Nazionale
will need ``no less'' than 1.4 trillion lire, or $1 billion, in
fresh capital funds to meet the capital adequacy ratios set by the
Bank of Italy, the country's central bank.
   He said he would proceed with a previously announced plan to
raise Banca Nazionale's capital through the creation of an alliance
between BNL and the state insurance agency INA and the state pension
fund INPS.
   A further step could come from a partial privatization of the
bank, Carli suggested.
   Carli indicated he intends to enlarge the role of the private
sector in the Italian banking business. Currently about 80 percent
of the Italian banking system is government-owned.
   Banca Nazionale has said it doesn't expect to incur losses from
the Atlanta affair because all transactions were guaranteed either
by the U.S. Commodity Credit Corporation or by the central bank of
Iraq.
   Carli and Bank of Italy Governor Carlo A. Ciampi last week
pressured BNL Chairman Nerio Nesi and General Manager Giacomo Pedde
into assuming responsibility for the affair and forced them to
resign.
   Carli said an investigation by the Bank of Italy in the wake of
the affair showed that Banca Nazionale did not have sufficient
internal controls.
   He also confirmed that the Bank of England has asked Banca
Nazionale to limit its activities at its London investment banking
unit to trading until BNL's internal system of controls was
improved. BNL has denied the Bank of England had found any
irresgularities at the BNL investment bank in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
