<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     09-14 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $2.42 Billion in Latest Week to New All-Time High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 463 money market mutual
funds rose by $2.42 billion to a record $347.07 billion in the
latest week, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   It was the 11th straight week that the assets hit an all-time
high and reflected the growing popularity of money market mutual
funds as an alternative to other types of investments.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday followed a $1.26
billion rise the previous week, the Washington-based mutual trade
fund group said.
   In the latest week, assets of 227 general purpose funds rose
$805.20 million to $111.48 billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds
rose $1.53 billion to $150.74 billion, and assets of 141
institutional funds rose $79.9 million to $84.85 billion, the
institute said.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.27 percent from 8.24 percent the
previous week, said Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.28 percent from 8.30 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 36
days, down from 37 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts fell to 6.44 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.45 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, fell to 5.10 percent from 5.11 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.25
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.26 the
previous week. Yields were 8.30 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.31 percent; 8.22 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.23 percent;
and 8.21 percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged from a week earlier.
</TEXT>
