<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed Worldwide; Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rebounded to finish higher in choppy
U.S. dealings Thursday after closing lower overseas.
   Gold prices rose.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $360.50 a troy ounce, up 60 cents from
Wednesday. Republic National Bank quoted a late bid for gold of
$359.35 an ounce, up from $358.70.
   Traders said the Bank of Japan entered the market overnight to
sell a large amount of dollars, which pushed the U.S. currency lower
overseas. Further, dealers in Europe moved to trim their dollar
holdings ahead of Friday's release of U.S. merchandise trade figures
for July.
   But dealers at home used the impending Commerce Department report
as a reason to buy dollars, pushing the currency higher in a seesaw
session.
   ``This summer the dollar has tended to drift higher closer to the
(trade) number because we don't want to be stuck short of dollars if
it's a good number,'' said Michael McDonald, a trader at Harris
Trust and Savings Bank in Chicago.
   Economists are projecting a trade deficit of between $7 billion
and $9 billion for July.
   In addition to the trade data, the government also is scheduled
to release the Producer Price Index for August, a figure that
typcially moves the credit markets, which in turn influence the
dollar.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 145.85 Japanese yen, down
from 146.70 yen. Later in London, the dollar traded lower at 146.60
yen. In New York, the dollar rose to close at 146.85 yen, from
146.40 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5582 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.5530. But in New York,
one pound cost $1.5540, cheaper than $1.5585 on Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Wednesday, included: 1.9750 West German marks, up from 1.9725;
1.7040 Swiss francs, up from 1.6990; 6.6605 French francs, up from
6.6525; 1,418.50 Italian lire, up from 1,415.00, and 1.1850 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1841.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Wednesday, included: 1.9705 West German marks, down from 1.9800;
1.7000 Swiss francs, down from 1.7095; 6.6485 French francs, down
from 6.6805; 2.2185 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2300; 1,413.00
Italian lire, down from 1,419.00, and 1.1849 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1855.
   Gold closed in London at a bid price of $362.00 a troy ounce, up
from $358.50. The late bid price in Zurich was $361.75, up from
$358.25. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $359.85, up from
$359.60.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery slipped to $5.055 from $5.067 Wednesday. Silver
bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.12 a troy ounce, up from
$5.08.
</TEXT>
