<TEXT>
   The stock market extended its September slump
Thursday in selling blamed on takeover-debt worries and caution in
advance of the quarterly ``triple witching hour.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 27.74 points
Wednesday, dropped another 14.63 to 2,664.89.
   In the eight sessions since Labor Day the average has fallen
87.20 points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by close to 3 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
396 up, 1,108 down and 479 unchanged.
   Analysts said the market remained unsettled by recent pressure on
the market for high-yield ``junk'' bonds of companies carrying large
debt loads.
   The worries focused on the problems of Campeau Corp., which is in
the process of trying to restructure its retailing empire to keep up
with its debt obligations.
   Whatever the outcome of Campeau's efforts, observers said, its
problems clouded prospects for new debt-financed acquisitions by
other bidders in the immediate future.
   Woolworth Corp., a retailer that has been widely rumored as a
buyout candidate, fell 3\ to 64}.
   Airline stocks, a hot takeover group for most of the summer, also
declined broadly. AMR lost 4[ to 77|; Delta Air Lines 2~ to 71|, and
UAL 2} to 280{.
   Among other prominent issues recently talked up as potential
takeover targets, Honeywell fell 2} to 82{ and Eastman Kodak lost |
to 48[.
   Some money evidently flowed out of those stocks into blue chips
so big they presumably had no takeover premiums built into their
prices. American Telephone &amp; Telegraph rose \ to 40\; International
Business Machines ] to 115}, and General Electric ] to 55~.
   Brokers also noted that traders were proceeding cautiously in
advance of the quarterly ``witching hour'' Friday involving a series
of expiring stock-index options and futures.
   The government reported Thursday morning that retail sales
increased 0.7 percent in August, slightly below most advance
estimates. The news provided some support for U.S. Treasury
securities, nudging interest rates a bit lower in that sector of the
credit markets.
   But stocks got little benefit from those developments.
   Circle K Corp. led the active list, down ] at 7]. The stock fell
1} Wednesday, when the company said it had ended efforts to solicit
takeover offers and suspended its dividend.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 149.25 million
shares, down from 175.33 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 177.83 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $23.78 billion, or 0.70
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 1.34 to 190.95.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 2.74 to 392.64, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down 2.30 at 343.16.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 3.05 to 468.78. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
