<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-14 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Fall on Profit-taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices, which have marched higher
in recent weeks on increased demand, declined Thursday amid a spate
of profit-taking.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 14 cents to $19.72 a 42-gallon barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange after rising 16 cents on
Wednesday.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the October
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline skidded 1.08 cents to close
at 56.67 cents a gallon after rising 0.86 cent the previous session.
   Home heating oil for October delivery, which picked up 0.09 cent
a gallon on Wednesday, was off 0.42 cent and settled at 55.04 cents
a gallon.
   The energy futures market has rallied in recent weeks on
increased demand for gasoline and heating oil. But on Thusday,
profit-takers moved into the products market.
   ``When people saw products weakening, they took that opportunity
to sell off'' in the crude market as well, said Jack Unger, an oil
trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   West Texas Intermediate went as high as $20.09 a barrel, but at
that price, he said professional traders tend to sell to take
profits. Buyers at the $20 a barrel level generally need the oil,
Unger said.
</TEXT>
