<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-14 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Regain Strength On Supply Jitters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper for spot delivery on New York's Commodity Exchange surged
to a 4{-month high Thursday as the market ignored a mining strike
settlement in Chile and focused on continuing supply disruptions in
other parts of the world.
   On other markets, pork bellies rose the limit and grain futures
rallied on news of a food-aid package to Poland; energy futures fell
and precious metals were mixed.
   Copper futures settled 1.5 cents to 4.9 cents higher with the
spot contract, for delivery in September, at $1.373 a pound, the
highest settlement for spot copper contract on the Comex since April
28.
   The settlement of a 2-week-old strike at the Chilean Copper Co.'s
El Salvador mine had been expected and caused little market reaction.
   The Chilean mine, which produces about 100,000 tons of copper
annually, is the smallest of six major copper mines worldwide that
have suffered recent supply disruptions, and at least three of those
remain shut down.
   Those are the Bouganville mine in Papua New Guinea, closed since
mid-July by terrorism; Mexico's Cananea mine, which went bankrupt on
Aug. 20; and a Highland Valley Copper Co. mine in British Columbia
that has been shut down by a strike since July 6.
   Weather-related problems at another mine in Papua New Guinea and
a recent strike by Zambian copper miners have also contributed to
the supply jitters, analysts said.
   ``There's still about 600,000 tons of capacity shut down ... and
that's a substantial tonnage,'' said Fred Demler, a metals economist
in New York with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   ``I think the market realizes that even if all the problems were
resolved today, there would still be tightness in refined supply for
several months,'' he said.
   Analyst Stephen Platt of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago,
said the shutdowns of the Bouganville and Highland Valley mines have
cut off two of the Far East's major sources of copper.
   Platt said buying by Chinese interests was a key factor in
Thursday's rally.
   New reports regarding U.S. food aid to Poland boosted meat and
grain futures in Chicago.
   President Bush announced a $50 million increase in food aid to
Poland and Sen. Patrick Leahy, chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee, proposed a Polish food-aid package that includes 500,000
metric tons of corn, 100,000 metric tons of wheat and 20 million to
30 million pounds of pork.
   Frozen pork-belly futures have been rising for the past two weeks
on expectations that the government will donate some of the
burgeoning U.S. pork-belly surplus to the Poles.
   The Agriculture Department reported on Aug. 23 that 96.4 million
pounds of pork bellies were in cold storage as of July 31,
second-highest stockpile on record.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, frozen pork bellies settled
1.93 cents to 2 cents higher with February at 48.25 cents a pound;
hog futures were .23 cent to .85 cent higher with October at 40.57
cents a pound; live cattle were .07 cent lower to .50 cent higher
with October at 72.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to
.50 cent higher with September at 83.32 cents a pound.
   On the Chicago Board of Trade, wheat futures settled } cent lower
to 1{ cents higher with September at $3.85} a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to 3{ cents higher with September at $2.37\ a bushel;
oats were { cent to 1\ cents higher with September at $1.34{ a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 3\ cents higher with September
at $5.85{ a bushel.
   Energy futures succumbed to a spate of profit-taking on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents to 15 cents
lower with October at $19.72 a barrel; heating oil was .33 cent to
.74 cent lower with October at 55.04 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .53 cent to 1.08 cents lower with October at 56.67
cents a gallon.
   Gold advanced slightly while silver continued its slow downward
slide on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold futures settled 40 cents to 50 cents higher with October at
$361.80 a troy ounce; silver was 1.2 cents to 1.5 cents lower with
September at $5.055 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
