<FIRST>r f BC-Hungary-Murdoch     09-14 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hungary-Murdoch,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Media Magnate Buys Half Interest in Two Hungarian Dailies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International media magnate Rupert
Murdoch has reached a tentative agreement with the publisher of two
independent newspapers to buy half interest in the dailies, the
official MTI news agency reported Thursday.
   MTI quoted Istvan Horvath, executive editor of Mai Nap, as saying
there was agreement in principle to sell Murdoch 50 percent of the
shares of his paper and of the Reform daily.
   Horvath said the signing of a final agreement would likely take
place in October. He said financial terms had not been agreed on.
   The West German Springer media conglomerate brought a minority
interest in Reform earlier this year, the first foreign company to
own shares of a Hungarian newspaper since the communists
consolidated power in 1947.
   Both tabloid newspapers were founded this year and combine
irreverent style with occasionally racy photos. Private newspapers
are a recent phenomenon tied to an end to most constraints on
reporting.
   Murdoch heads News Corp. Ltd., an Australian-based media giant
with newspaper, film and broadcast interests in Australia, North
America and Europe.
</TEXT>
