<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-SecuritiesLink     09-14 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Securities Link,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>State-Provincial Computer Link on Stock Fraud Proposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer network linking state-level
securities regulators in the United States and Canada is among the
goals for the 1990s proposed by the incoming head of the North
American Securities Administrators Association.
   In remarks prepared for delivery Thursday night in Quebec at the
72nd annual fall conference of the state-level regulators group,
Susan Bryant said the ``most significant issue'' in the next decade
will be the internationalization of the securities markets.
   ``I intend to see to it that the states emerge as major players
in international securities regulation,'' said Ms. Bryant, who heads
the Oklahoma Department of Securities.
   Toward that goal, she proposed extending an existing computer
linkup among securities regulators in the 50 states to all the
Canadian provinces and territories.
   The National Association of Securities Dealers, a self-regulatory
group, and the Securities and Exchange Commission, the federal
agency that regulates the stock and bond markets, created the
national computer network.
   The system helps regulators keep tabs on individuals offering
securities who have violated state or federal regulations.
   ``To fight international securities fraud, we will need a truly
global system for spotting and tracking violators,'' said Ms. Bryant.
   ``This will make North America the first continent in the world
in which grass-roots securities regulators will be wired together in
order to fight securities fraud and abuse,'' said Ms. Bryant.
</TEXT>
