<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-Japan 1stLd-Writethru f0309 09-14 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0309,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telecommunications Agreement Reached</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT spelling of ``Haruo'' and to fix
name of telephone company and its diminutive. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``We
are ...''.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Japan announced an
agreement Thursday by which the two nations will cooperate in
telecommunications research and development.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, who was traveling in Japan
this week, and Haruo Yamaguchi, president of Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone Corp., signed an agreement to establish a framework for
cooperation in the research and development of certain
semiconductors, telecommunications, computers and computer
networking, time and frequency measurement and related fields, the
department said.
   The agreement is an extension of research cooperation that began
in 1984 between the National Institute of Standards and Technology
and NTT, the national telephone company of Japan.
   ``We are pleased with the close, productive cooperation we have
had with NTT over the past five years,'' Mosbacher said in a
statement. ``The work both parties have undertaken has been
conducted on the basis of mutual benefit, equality and reciprocity.
It is a model for what we desire in the overall relationship in
science and technology between the United States and Japan.''
   The agreement calls for cooperation in areas such as information
exchange on scientific and technical developments; short-term visits
of scientists, engineers and other specialists; joint research
activities, and an exchange of technical publications.
   ``This agreement allows both Japan and the United States to
enrich their technical capability without duplicating basic research
in costly and time-consuming areas,'' Mosbacher said. ``Both
countries win _ a result we hope to extend to more apsects of our
scientific, commercial and trade relationship with Japan. As in
other aspects of trade, this kind of relationship can only work if
it's a two-way street.''
</TEXT>
